<FIRST>u w AM-OilSpill-Bush 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0402,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Sends Officials to Inspect Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Secretary Lujan in delegation; minor editing changes
throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush dispatched a team led by
Interior Secretary Manual Lujan and Environmental Protection Agency
William Reilly to inspect the oil spill off Rhode Island, the White
House said Friday night.
   Bush was briefed on the spill at 8 p.m. at the Camp David weekend
retreat by White House chief of staff John Sununu, said deputy press
secretary Steve Hart.
   ``He expressed his deep concern and asked to be kept informed,''
Hart said.
   The delegation will fly over the spill Saturday morning, Hart
said.
   Other members of the group include Rear Adm. Clyde T. Lusk. chief
of staff of the Coast Guard, and Elaine Chao, deputy transportation
secretary. The Transportation Department is the parent agency of the
Coast Guard.
   The Coast Guard assumed direction of the cleanup immediately for
the most rapid response, Hart said.
   Hart said officials on the scene had told the White House that as
many as 1.6 million gallons of No. 2 fuel oil could leak from four
penetrated tanks on the vessel. Reports from Rhode Island put the
spill at about 1 million gallons when the leak was stopped at about
9 p.m.
   Steve Goldstein, press spokesman for Lujan, said form his home
Friday night, ``There has been some impact on the shoreline.''
</TEXT>
