<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2340EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Scotus-DeathRow     06-23 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Death Row,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Says Death Row Inmates Don't Get Free Lawyers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Constitution doesn't require that states
provide free lawyers for inmates who are sentenced to death if the
prisoners have already lost a round of appeals, a divided Supreme
Court said Friday.
   The court ruled 5-4 to uphold Virginia officials who said forcing
states to pay for second-round appeals could lead to long delays in
executing inmates.
   When inmates file a first appeal in state courts, lawyers are
provided by the state.
   If that fails, inmates can pursue a second round of appeals. Like
other states, Virginia provides prison law libraries and assigns
part-time lawyers to help all inmates prepare their second-round _
or collateral _ appeals. In some cases, volunteer lawyers are
available.
   Death row inmates who lose a second time may then shift to
federal courts, but legal help in those appeals was not at issue in
Friday's case.
   In writing the majority opinion,, Chief Justice William H.
Rehnquist said convicts' constitutional rights are not violated by
cutting off free access to lawyers.
   ``The additional safeguards imposed by the (Constitution) at the
trial stage of a capital case are, we think, sufficient to assure
the reliability of the process by which the death penality is
imposed,`` Rehnquist said.
   Rehnquist was joined by Justices Byron R. White, Sandra Day
O'Connor and Antonin Scalia.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy supplied the fifth vote to overturn a
federal appeals court ruling that said condemned killers in Virginia
who cannot afford a lawyer are entitled to greater representation at
taxpayer expense than the state provides.
   In a separate concurring opinion, Kennedy agreed with the result
reached by the other four but on narrower grounds.
   In a dissenting opinion, Justice John Paul Stevens said the
ruling violates ``simple fairness'' for death row inmates. He was
joined by Justices William J. Brennan, Thurgood Marshall and Harry
A. Blackmun.
   The 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled a year ago the
Constitution requires special legal help for death row appeals
because of their complexity.
   Twenty states joined in support of Virginia. They are Florida,
Georgia, Mississippi, North Carolina, Missouri, South Dakota,
Wyoming, Delaware, California, Pennsylvania, New Mexico, Indiana,
Kentucky, New Hampshire, Nevada, Utah, South Carolina, Oregon,
Maryland and Idaho.
</TEXT>
