<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Timber-SpottedOwl     06-23 1032</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Timber-Spotted Owl,1054</SECOND>
<HEAD>Debate Focuses on Whether To Log or Preserve Virgin Forests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCKPORT, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Hornbeck aimed his truck up the
winding mountain road and eyed the aged forest looming above.
   ``There is your pristine old-growth forest,'' said the logger,
pointing to silver shafts of dead and dying trees within the green
shag of hemlock, fir and lighter-colored cedar. ``To me, it's not
beauty. It's a little bit pathetic. It's a forest that's overripe.
   ``It would have been logged by now, but it was pulled from the
market because of the spotted owl, and I don't think it will ever be
logged now. If they take it away, it's a way of life that is gone,
not just jobs.''
   Whether, when, and where cutting may resume in many Northwestern
national forests won't be known until U.S. District Judge William
Dwyer in Seattle decides whether to alter a March injunction
temporarily halting the sale of 1 billion board feet of timber in
Oregon and Washington.
   Dwyer's ruling came in a lawsuit challenging a Forest Service
plan to set aside 374,000 acres as habitat for the Northern spotted
owl. Environmentalists charged that the plan fails to set aside
enough old-growth forest to ensure the owls' survival; Dwyer's
injunction expands the affected acreage.
   Meanwhile, the U.S. Fish and Wildlife _ which refused in 1987 to
list the spotted owl as a threatened species _ reversed itself in
March and decided the bird's dwindling habitat warrants giving it
that status, a year-long process.
   Oregon Gov. Neil Goldschmidt and state congressional leaders have
called a summit meeting Saturday in Salem to try to resolve
conflicts over the owl. The governor, the state's entire
congressional delegation and representatives of government agencies
and timber and environmental groups will attend.
   The prospect that the owl will be listed as a threatened species
has added more doubt to the future of timber supplies.
   But there is much more at stake than board feet of lumber and a
subspecies of spotted owls, said forest ecologist Peter Morrison of
The Wilderness Society's Seattle office, who insists, ``I'm no tree
hugger.''
   ``We need to consider long-term impacts on biological
diversity,'' said Morrison, noting that relatively little is known
about virgin forests and interactions between plants and animals in
them.
   ``I can see serious impacts if we give up that biological
diversity found in an ancient forest, and by then it will be too
late. ... It's not going to be just the spotted owl disappearing.''
   The unique attachment of the owl to old growth is what put the
bird in the middle of controversy. Biologists say that while the owl
can use other forest land, it requires a certain amount of old
growth for nesting and mating. If that old growth is too fragmented,
the owl could spend so much time seeking food and shelter that it
wouldn't have time or energy to mate.
   The Forest Service doesn't know how much old growth is left, but
The Wilderness Society has estimated that less than 15 percent of
the original old-growth forest remains in the owl's range from
northern California to southern British Columbia. What is left is so
badly fragmented that much of it is worthless as habitat for the owl
and other wildlife.
   ``People want to say, `Let's sit down at a table and reasonably
talk about this dividing of a loaf,' when in reality the loaf is all
gone. What we are doing is squabbling over the crumbs,'' said Rick
Brown, a former Mount Hood National Forest biologist now working for
the National Wildlife Federation.
   But Ted Anderson, executive director of FFACTS, a group in
Washington's Skagit Valley organized this spring to defend the
timber industry, said it's the livelihood of workers and their
families that's at stake.
   National parks, wilderness areas, wild and scenic rivers and
other set-asides have removed 53 percent of the federal forest lands
in Washington from the timber base, he said. ``We simply can't write
off our industry.''
   For example, six timber sales in the Mount Baker District
covering half of the 2,200 acres set aside for one pair of spotted
owls would have produced 47 million board feet of timber to keep
local mills running for the next year.
   ``To us, that's our life,'' said Anderson. ``To them, it's for
one owl.''
   Andy Kerr, conservation director of the Oregon Natural Resources
Council, said timber jobs are going, owl or no owl. He cited a study
by The Wilderness Society estimating that the 71,500 timber jobs in
Washington and Oregon in 1985 will shrink to half that by 2030
mainly because of increased mill productivity. Stopping the harvest
of old growth altogether would eliminate only 6 percent of the
timber and 2,300 extra jobs in that period, the study said.
   Chuck Sisco of the National Audubon Society, another Forest
Service veteran, said the agency has bungled the works since 1978,
when it picked the owl as the indicator species for the well-being
of the old-growth ecosystem under provisions of the National Forest
Management Act.
   About two-thirds of the sites the Forest Service identified in
Oregon and Washington as owl habitats would affect lumbering, but
``their own data showed that 65 or 70 percent of the areas they said
were spotted owl sites in wilderness (where logging is prohibited)
didn't have any birds in them,'' Sisco said.
   On the west side of the Olympics, Larry Mason, owner of the Mason
Lumber mill in Beaver, reiterated the doubts held by many in the
timber industry that the spotted owl is threatened. Even if the
owl's days are numbered, he said, it is not responsible to shut
timber supplies down overnight.
   Mason complained that the fight over the owl vividly illustrates
the growing urban-rural separation in Washington, where the
Seattle-area economy has been fueled by a growing aerospace industry
and computer-age businesses while the traditional forest industry
has been pushed aside.
   ``You know,'' he said, ``There are people who have to get their
hands dirty every day earning a living, and there are city people
who think the forests should be their private playgrounds.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
