<DOCNO> AP890623-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Timber-Forks     06-23 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Timber-Forks,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Logging Town Suffers Under Weight of Timber Shutdowns</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Timber-Spotted Owl</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORKS, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 15-foot cross made of old-growth timber
stands across from Jerry Leppell's saw shop, where it was hewn.
   A half-dozen plastic owls are nailed to the crossbeam with a sign
that says: ``Here lie the hopes and dreams of our children.''
   The residents of this Olympic Peninsula logging town say they are
being crucified by environmentalists and the government, which have
closed, at least temporarily, thousands of acres of timber to
preserve old-growth forest and one of its elusive denizens, the
Northern spotted owl.
   ``Every way you turn, the government, the preservationists, big
business, they all want your job,'' said Garth Leavitt, a log
hauler. ``What do they want us to do? Move to the cities where
there's no work and no place to live?''
   Forks _ an isolated town of 3,000 on the western edge of the
Olympic National Park, 150 miles from Seattle _ sits in a broad
valley surrounded by bare green hills that still bear scars of what
modern loggers contemptuously call ``cut-and-run boys'' who took the
timber but didn't bother to replant.
   Logging trucks roar down a main street of gas stations and small
stores. Neighborhoods are dotted with swingsets, lush gardens and
yards decorated with rusting saws and other logging tools. The air
carries the peaceful aroma of burning cedar chips from nearby shake
mills.
   But like timber towns across the Northwest, Forks isn't peaceful.
   Yellow ``solidarity'' ribbons flutter on fenceposts and pickup
truck aerials from Forks to Oregon's Willamette Valley, where a
Eugene man is selling hundreds of T-shirts that read, ``Save a
logger, eat an owl.''
   Organized by the timber companies, labor unions and local
governments, millworkers and their families are turning out in
massive demonstrations. About 1,500 participated in a log truck
parade in the Columbia Gorge town of Hood River, Ore. More than
1,000 rallied at the Oregon Capitol.
   The pain from the shutdown of federal timber sales ``really
hasn't hit yet. There's still timber in the pipeline from sales
before this thing got going,'' said Mayor Warren Paul, adding that
it probably will hit just before winter.
   But Forks merchants say people already are pinching pennies, and
houses are going up for sale as loggers leave for Alaska's Tongass
National Forest.
   ``We have a house payment, and a new truck and stuff,'' said
Renee Robinson, a waitress and part of a third-generation logging
family. ``We don't know what's going to happen. A lot of people are
going to Alaska.
   ``We're all scared.''
   At the mental health center serving Forks and Clallam County,
director Steve Ironhill said the area already has the highest
suicide rate in the state and an alcoholism rate among the top 10
percent of U.S. counties. The pending economic disaster ``is going
to be the thing that is going to turn the community upside down.''
   Ironhill, a psychologist, said he hears the fear from children he
and his staff treat for abuse and other problems. ``I'm hearing them
say: `The spotted owl won't let my daddy work,' or `Daddy isn't
working,' or `Daddy went to Alaska.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
