<FIRST>r a PM-Names     06-23 0874</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Names,0909</SECOND>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Known for his crooning cowboy tunes,
singer-songwriter Willie Nelson has turned his fondness for the
American Wild West into a broadcasting network he can call his own.
   The Cowboy Television Network, which Nelson developed with Austin
entrepreneur Edward Yi, will air movies, series, music videos, live
music shows, specials, and historical vignettes in the United States
and several other countries.
   The network's 24-hour programming, to start in late summer or
early fall, will be designed by Nelson and associate Mack Long,
according to a news release Thursday from Nelson and Yi.
   Yi, chairman and chief executive of Sunin International, created
a sister network, the Asian Broadcasting System, to air American
programs in Korea, Japan, China, the Philippines, Taiwan and other
nations in Southeast Asia.
   The networks will be located at Nelson's ranch in Willie, about
30 miles outside Austin.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball manager Tommy Lasorda traded his
Los Angeles Dodger blue for bib overalls, but kept within camera
range as he taped the ``Hee Haw'' TV show.
   Lasorda, enjoying a day off, stood in the famous ``Hee Haw''
cornfield Thursday in a studio at the Grand Ole Opry House. His
segments on the syndicated country music-humor show will be aired
this fall.
   Lasorda posed for pictures with ``Hee Haw'' stars Roy Clark and
Minnie Pearl, saying he positioned himself between the two on advice
given to him years ago by St. Louis Cardinals' great Stan Musial.
   ``He said always get in the middle because that way they can't
cut you out,'' Lasorda said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Morris K. Udall, D-Ariz., plans to marry
former congressional staffer Norma Gilbert this summer.
   No wedding date has been set, Dan O'Neill, Udall's district
assistant in Tucson, said Thursday.
   O'Neill said Ms. Gilbert is a California native who now lives in
the Washington area. He said she worked as a lobbyist before working
for a subcommittee of the House Interior Committee. Udall chairs the
full committee.
   The marriage will be Udall's third. He and his first wife
divorced and his second wife, Ella, committed suicide last August at
the couple's Washington-area home.
   O'Neill said he did not know Ms. Gilbert's age, her employer as a
lobbyist or whether she had been married before.
   Udall, 67, was first elected to the House in a 1961 special
election. He unsuccessfully sought the Democratic presidential
nomination in 1976.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actress Jane Seymour today returned
to Malaysia to attend the world premiere next week of the movie,
``Keys to Freedom,'' in which she plays a doctor.
   Seymour told reporters she had missed ``Malaysian food and the
friendly faces,'' and planned to take a vacation in Kuching.
   The British-born Seymour stars in the film with Omar Sharif,
David Warner and Nancy Kwan and local performers Malek Noor and
Jacinta Lee. The film, an American-Malaysian joint venture,
premieres next Tuesday.
   Producer Eduardo Rossoff said that about 90 per cent of the movie
was shot in the seaside resort city of Penang, and the rest was
filmed in Hong Kong.
   The $5 million movie is about an American merchant sailor who
runs into smugglers and witnesses a murder and along the way falls
in love with a married English physician played by Seymour.
</TEXT>
