<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Wall Street Journal threw a gala bash to
celebrate its 100th birthday, inviting 600 guests ranging from
President and Barbara Bush to Fortune 500 luminaries and pop stars.
   ``If a catastrophe happened in the Winter Garden, the Fortune 500
would be lucky to keep in just double digits,'' Bush told the
black-tie crowd at the sprawling Winter Garden glass atrium Thursday
night.
   The guest list read like a Who's Who of celebrities in the
business, media and entertainment worlds: computer whiz Steve Jobs,
Ford Motor Co. Chairman Donald Peterson, ITT Corp. Chairman Rand
Araskog, CBS Inc. Chairman Lawrence Tisch, ``60 Minutes'' anchor
Mike Wallace, and Washington Post Co. Chairwoman Katharine Graham,
among others.
   The entertainment agenda ranged from jazz great Lionel Hampton to
rocker Chuck Berry and blues singer Buster Poindexter.
   The guest list also included government executives and 52 Journal
readers _ one randomly selected from each state _ and a reader each
from Europe and Asia, representing the paper's European and Asian
editions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SKOWHEGAN, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Chase Smith, a former U.S.
senator who campaigned for more than four decades to make the rose
America's national flower, was sent 91 dozen roses in appreciation
for her efforts.
   ``I always got it passed in the House, but never the Senate,''
said Mrs. Smith, 91, who retired from Congress in 1973. Finally
winning approval in both chambers, the bill was signed into law in
1987.
   The long-stemmed ``Samantha'' red roses, arranged in a single
vase, took on the appearance of a 7-foot Christmas tree as they were
transported through the streets of Mrs. Smith's hometown of
Skowhegan on a flatbed trailer.
   She accepted the gigantic bouquet Wednesday. Most of the roses
will be given to nursing homes and a hospital.
   A radio station and a florists' group presented the giant bouquet.
</TEXT>
