<FIRST>u a AM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0768 06-23 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0768,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marshals Fan Through Southern West Virginia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The wildcat...,' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
Pittston announcing it is moving workers. Picks up 4th graf pvs, `The sympathy...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal marshals roved the southern West
Virginia coal fields Thursday to disperse striking miners and end
wildcat walkouts that have idled nearly 44,000 workers in 10 states.
   A disabled coal miner's 19-year-old son was grazed by a bullet at
a Mingo County mine in what state police said was the most serious
incident since the unauthorized walkouts began in West Virginia last
week. The teen-ager was treated at a local hospital and released.
   The target of the sympathy strikes, Pittston Coal Group Inc.,
announced Thursday night it was planning to move some salaried
workers from its operations in West Virginia to its holdings in
Virginia, where miners have been on strike since April.
   Pittston's president, Michael Odom, refused to elaborate on the
plan to move workers.
   The wildcat strikes in Appalachia and the Midwest are in support
of 1,900 West Virginia, Virginia and Kentucky miners' strike against
Pittston.
   The sympathy strikes prompted a spate of federal court motions
obtained by coal companies who want their miners back on the job.
Several coal companies in some of the 10 states involved have filed
complaints with the National Labor Relations Board against the
United Mine Workers, which in turn has filed unfair labor practice
charges against companies.
   U.S. District Judge Dennis Knapp on Wednesday fined six West
Virginia UMW locals, their officers and members for defying a
back-to-work order issued earlier this week. He ordered the U.S.
marshal's office to have deputies serve picketers at any of 12
Island Creek Coal Co. mines with copies of his order.
   Walt Biondi, U.S. marshal for West Virginia's Southern District,
said deputies were told to order any miners, demonstrators or
picketers to disperse and appear later for a contempt-of-court
hearing.
   Biondi said deputy marshals arrived in West Virginia on Thursday
from other states to help issue the orders. He declined to say how
many marshals were involved or how long they would be in West
Virginia.
   ``I think it's fair to say it's going to cost us at a minimum
several thousand dollars over the next couple of days,'' Biondi
said, declining to estimate the total.
   The additional manpower also is in anticipation of a federal
court hearing scheduled Friday for at least a dozen coal companies
seeking back-to-work orders for their striking miners.
   In U.S. District Court in Clarksburg, Judge William Kidd on
Thursday said he would rule soon on Consolidation Coal Co.'s
petition to force miners from six north central West Virginia locals
to return to work.
   Back-to-work orders also were sought by companies in Alabama and
Pennsylvania, and Consolidation has said it plans to seek similar
legal action in Illinois and Ohio.
   Jamie Blankenship, 19, was wounded early Thursday when a bullet
grazed his head while he was at Hampden Coal Co., a non-union mine
shut down by the wildcat strikes, state police said. Union and coal
company officials blamed each other, and police said they were
investigating.
   The wildcat strikes began June 13.
   The estimated number of miners involved Thursday in unauthorized
sympathy walkouts, according to union and industry officials, are:
West Virginia 16,000; Illinois, 8,000; Pennsylvania, 6,600; Alabama,
5,000; Ohio, 2,660; Indiana, 1,750; Kentucky, 2,325; Virginia, 755;
Missouri, 350; and Tennessee, 200.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Casino-Drunks 1stLd-Writethru a0728 06-23 0687</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Casino-Drunks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0728,0704</SECOND>
<HEAD>Casinos Ponder Liabilities From Drunken Gamblers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT spelling to Shmuel, sted Schmuel.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Casino executives reacted warily
Thursday to a judge's ruling that casinos may be held liable for
money lost by drunk gamblers. Some worried that it could give losers
a way to recoup their money.
   ``Maybe we have to put Breathalyzers at the door,'' said Roger
Wagner, president of the Claridge Casino Hotel, only half-joking.
   U.S. District Court Judge Mitchell Cohen ruled Wednesday that
casino operators, like tavern owners, have a responsibility to their
customers. The judge's decision stemmed from a lawsuit between the
Golden Nugget Hotel and Casino and a customer who lost $200,000.
   Shmuel Aboud, of New York City, said casino officials plied him
with free alcohol and pain killers for his aching back. The ruling
will allow a court case to continue toward a finding of whether the
casino was responsible for Aboud's losses.
   Some observers believe the ruling could mean casinos will stop
serving free drinks to gamblers and could force the gaming halls to
forbid drunk patrons from placing bets for fear of liability claims.
   Some casino executives believe the decision only reinforces what
the gaming halls already do. Jim Wise, a spokesman for TropWorld
Casino and Entertainment Resort, said, ``The judge uses such terms
as `obviously' and `visibly' intoxicated. We already follow those
guidelines. Anyone in that state is neither allowed more alcoholic
beverages or the opportunity to gamble.''
   An intoxicated gambler poses problems for a casino, Wise said.
   ``If someone does not have all his facilities, they have viable
reasons to complain afterward that they were treated unfairly,'' he
said.
   Stephen Hyde, chief executive officer for Donald Trump's two
casinos in Atlantic City, said, ``It is not in our best interests to
have a drunk sitting at a gaming table making a fool of himself.''
   Trump's casinos will stop serving an intoxicated customer, he
said.
   ``When you stop serving him, the patron usually does not go on
much further,'' Hyde said. ``He usually gets a little obnoxious and
ends up leaving the gambling floor.''
   But a liberal interpretation of the ruling could give customers
an easy way to reclaim large losses, Wagner said.
   ``Every idiot in the world will be suing us,'' he said.
   Likewise, casino executives in Nevada were worried about the
judge's decision. Roy Galyean, president of the Union Plaza Hotel
and Casino in Las Vegas, said, ``Are they suggesting that we
administer a drug-alcohol test to a patron before we let him
gamble?''
   Wagner said cocktail waitresses who stroll casino floors have a
scripted question: ``Would anyone like any complimentary coffee,
juice or soda?''
   ``We do not solicit free alcoholic beverages,'' he said. ``But if
a customer says he wants a beer instead of juice, he can have it.''
   Many gamblers will not drink alcoholic beverages ``because it
dilutes the decision-making process,'' Wise said.
   Lois Szabo of New Brunswick, sipping a pina colada at Trump Plaza
Hotel and Casino on Thursday, agreed. She said most casino customers
``are more interested in gambling than drinking. You get so caught
up in the slots that you actually forget to take a drink.''
   Some customers might take advantage of the decision ``because
some people would do anything to sue,'' she said. ``Personally,
everybody should be able to control themselves with liquor. When
some people drink excessively, they should be responsible for their
own actions.''
   Judge Cohen's ruling probably would attract the ``little guy,''
said Anna Krommer of Washington, relaxing with a beer at a casino
bar on Thursday.
   ``The casinos are a big attraction for the poorer people who
imagine they can become richer,'' she said.
   Gus Sunday of Philadelphia, who visits Atlantic City's casinos
about twice a month, said he has never seen a fellow gambler
intoxicated.
   ``Anybody who would get drunk has his own problems. It's not the
casino's problem,'' he said. ``People who come to Atlantic City are
not kids. They should have enough sense to know when to say no.''
</TEXT>
