<FIRST>r a PM-OldestFarmWoman     06-23 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oldest Farm Woman,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Searches for Oldest Farm Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's no prize, and the winner will have
to announce her age publicly. But that has not discouraged entries
in the competition to be named Illinois' oldest active farm woman.
   ``There are so many women active in agriculture today, we thought
it would be fun to see how many keep their hand in the business for
a long time,'' said Karen Benning of the Illinois Department of
Agriculture. The agency honored a 97-year-old Stark County man as
the state's oldest active farmer in 1987.
   The oldest farm woman does not have to live on a farm or drive a
tractor, but she must actively manage the farm or be a full partner
in its operation.
   ``It's hard to say whether there are more women or fewer women in
agriculture than men,'' said Mrs. Benning. ``There are a lot of
widows who have stayed with the operation, and more of that all the
time.''
   So far 20 people have requested entry forms, and many more are
expected by the July 21 deadline, said Mrs. Benning. The oldest
applicant thus far is 88 years old, she said.
   The top five candidates will attend the Illinois State Fair on
Aug. 15, when the winner will be announced.
   ``There is no monetary prize, but they will be our guests at the
fair,'' said Mrs. Benning.
</TEXT>
