<FIRST>r w PM-US-Germany     06-23 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Germany,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eagleburger Sees No Legal German Reunification</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The No. 2 official in the State Department
predicted the Soviet Union will not soon allow East Germany to
reunite with West Germany, despite improved Kremlin relations with
Bonn's government.
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence S. Eagleburger told a Senate
panel that increasing pressure in both Germanies to unify may bring
greater contacts between the nations, but that no legal
reunification will likely result.
   ``I think what you see over the course of the next decade or two
is an increasing German desire for some form of reunification,''
Eagleburger said Thursday. ``If it comes in any reasonable period of
time it will come in fact, not de jure (in law).''
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev recently completed a state
visit of West Germany that highlighted improved relations between
the Soviet Union and Bonn. Gorbachev said during the trip that he
could envision a day when the Berlin Wall dividing East and West
Germany could come down.
   But Eagleburger told the Senate Foreign Relations European
subcommittee that current political conditions are not ripe to erase
the borders that were created after World War II.
   ``There are a lot of countries in western Europe ... and
certainly in eastern Europe, who do not contemplate with any joy
whatsoever a reunified Germany,'' he said. ``So that I have great
difficulty conceiving of a tim when the Soviet Union, in my lifetime
at least, will with equanimity look toward some reunified if neutral
Germany. I just don't think that's in the cards for them.''
</TEXT>
