<SECOND>AM-Gaza-Kidnap, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0452,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S. Relief Worker Kidnapped, Prisoner Release Demanded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 5 beginning `The official ...' to show victim from
New Jersey, ADDS two grafs background, U.S. Embassy comment at end. No
pickup. DELETES final graf to conform and trim.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. relief worker was kidnapped Thursday in
the Israel's occupied Gaza Strip, and the kidnappers apparently
demanded Israel release Palestinian prisoners in exchange for his
freedom, Arab reports said.
   In Washington, U.S. officials confirmed that 37-year-old Chris
George, of the Westport, Conn.-based Save the Children Federation,
was taken by unknown kidnappers.
   It was believed to be the first kidnapping of a non-Israeli in
Israel or the territories it has occupied since the 1967 Middle East
war.
   ``As far as we know, he was taken today,'' a U.S. official said
late Thursday. ``We're not sure by whom.''
   The official, who asked not to be identified, said George
apparently was kidnapped at about noon Thursday in the Gaza area,
although the exact location was unknown. George, a native of
Montclair, N.J., is the co-director of Save the Children in Israel
and the occupied territories.
   ``We've been in touch with local authorities on that, and both
the secretary of state and the president have been fully briefed on
this,'' the official said.
   Arab reports from Gaza said George was last seen at midday during
a trip to Gaza City.
   The reports said a Palestinian man walked into George's office on
the main Omar el-Mukhtar street and told the relief worker:
   ``I would like to talk to you. Could you come outside?''
   George's wife, Liz, reached by telephone early Friday, said she
had no precise information on his whereabouts.
   ``We are not sure what happened,'' she said.
   Several hours after George's disappearance, the office of the Red
Cross in Gaza received a ransom demand, Palestinian reports said.
Some reports said it came in the form of a written letter in which
the kidnappers demanded Israel release Palestinian detainees.
   It reportedly demanded the release of detainees belonging to the
Moslem fundamentalist Hamas (Zeal) group, the radical Syrian-backed
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine and Yasser Arafat's
mainsream Fatah branch of the PLO.
   More than 200 Hamas activists have been detained since an Israeli
army crackdown in May. Among them was the movement's elderly leader,
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, whom the letter reportedly mentioned by name.
   Last Sunday, the Israeli government outlawed Hamas along with two
other Moslem fundamentalist groups, the Islamic Jihad and Hezbollah,
a radical Shiite militia that mostly operates in Lebanon and is
believed to be holding foreign hostages.
   Fourteen foreign hostages, including nine Americans, are being
held in Lebanon by pro-Iranian Islamic fundamentalists.
   The longest-held foreign hostage is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The ransom letter, Arab reports said, also demanded an inquiry
into the death of Omar Qassem, a senior figure in the Democratic
Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a radical Marxist PLO faction.
   Qassem, 48, died on June 4 after spending 21 years in Israeli
jails.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Donald Cofman declined to provide any
comment on the reported kidnapping.
   George, a former peace corps volunteer based in Oman, has also
been stationed in Lebanon and for the last two years has headed Save
the Children in Gaza.
   For the last year and a half, he has been a co-director of the
foundation, based in Jerusalem. George has two children and speaks
fluent Arabic.
   The Save the Children Federation Inc. is a private international
development and relief organization that employs over 3,000
employees in 40 countries.
</TEXT>
