<FIRST>r w PM-AirlinesAntitrust     06-23 0355</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airlines Antitrust,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>American, Delta Drop Reservations System Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines and Delta Air Lines said they
were blindsided by the Justice Department's opposition to the
planned merger of their computer reservation systems into one $2
billion venture.
   The airlines ended the attempted merger Thursday after the
Justice Department threatened to file an antitrust suit alleging the
joint operation would harm competition in the computerized sale of
airline tickets.
   ``We explicitly structured the partnership to satisfy the
previously expressed concerns of several departments of the U.S.
government about single-carrier ownership of (computer reservation)
systems,'' said Robert L. Crandall, chairman and president of
American.
   The proposal to merge the computer reservation systems, known as
CRS, would have ``gotten the government off our back,'' said Delta
spokesman William Berry. ``We owned our system outright, and the
government had been complaining that single ownership of CRS was not
good.''
   Delta and American had intended to sell up to 50 percent of the
merged system to other airlines and already had received expressions
of interest from Alaska, Southwest, Lufthansa and more than a dozen
other carriers, Berry said.
   ``The likely result of this transaction would be higher fares and
poorer service for airline passengers,'' Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh said in a statement.
   American operates Sabre, which has 41 percent of the nationwide
market among the five systems used by airlines and travel agents.
Sabre took in $445 million in fees last year, the Justice Department
said. Delta's Datas II, the smallest of the CRS ventures, did $68
million in business last year.
   The computer systems, the primary channel for the distribution of
airline tickets, provide up-to-the-minute information about
schedules, fares, seat availability, hotels, car rentals and package
vacations.
   Despite a 1986 regulation that says airlines must not favor their
own flights in computer listings, ``Travel agents using a particular
CRS tend to sell a disproportionately high number of tickets on that
CRS owner's airline,'' according to Judy L. Whalley, acting
assistant attorney general for the antitrust division.
   Crandall said American will continue to seek partners for its
computer system.
</TEXT>
