<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     06-23 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Shares Up 206 Points</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against the Japanese yen
Friday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose
moderately.
   The dollar ended trading at 140.35 yen, down 1.05 yen from
Thursday's close of 141.40 yen. It opened at 139.60 yen and traded
between 139.40 yen and 140.60 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which lost 20.31 points
Thursday, gained 205.74 points, or 0.61 percent, to close the week
at 33,530.71. The index continued to rise throughout the trading day.
   The dollar's decline followed its plunge in New York, which
traders attributed to a false rumor that President Bush had been
shot.
   Toru Kanai, foreign exchange analyst with the New Japan
Securities Co., also said the dollar fell in reaction to its surge
of the past few weeks, which was widely considered unsustainable.
   On the stock exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues rose 199.98 points within the first 15 minutes of morning
trading.
</TEXT>
