<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0357EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HistoricAuction     06-23 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Historic Auction,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Historic Estate of Declaration Signer to be Auctioned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOINA CHIACU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   History will get a price tag this weekend
when artifacts from the estate of Josiah Bartlett, a signer of the
Declaration of Independence, are auctioned by his descendants.
   The sale items include an extensive collection of 18th century
letters and papers, a watch, cowhide britches and a handpainted vest
Bartlett is said to have worn when he followed John Hancock in
signing the Declaration.
   ``I've never done anything of this magnitude and it's very, very
exciting,'' said auctioneer Martin Willis, who will handle
Saturday's ``American History at Auction'' at the Bartlett home in
Kingston.
   Born in 1729, Bartlett gave a lifetime of public service as
doctor, judge, governor from 1790 to 1794 and founder of the New
Hampshire Medical Society.
   He signed the Articles of Confederation, which governed the
nation after the Revolutionary War, and played a role in New
Hampshire's decisive ratification of the U.S. Constitution in June
1788, which replaced the articles.
   ``We think he was an extraordinary man who gave of himself
extraordinarily,'' said state archivist Frank Mevers.
   One of the more unusual sale items is an apothecary chest with
Bartlett's handwritten labels intact, as well as some of the
medicines he used as a physician, according to Willis. The
historical value of the chest, as well as pieces of period furniture
kept in the Bartlett house built in 1774, makes it difficult to
predict what prices they will bring, he said.
   But Bartlett's papers are even more difficult to value, Willis
said. The Smithsonian Institution made one of a flood of inquiries
from around the nation about the documents, and the state has set
aside $1 million to buy some of the papers.
   They include a 1743 copy book from Bartlett's school days in
Amesbury, Mass., where he was born; official correspondence marking
the ``Surrender of Proud Cornwallis to the Illustrious Washington''
at Yorktown to end the American Revolution; a 1748 receipt for
payments to the families of two soldiers and an Indian killed near
Concord, during the French and Indian War; Bartlett's charter for
the New Hampshire Medical Society; and a copy of a handwritten
biography of Josiah Bartlett by his son Levi.
   Mevers said state historians see the documents, which include
records kept by Bartlett's descendants after his death in 1795, as
an excellent account of early New Hampshire life.
   ``That's what makes them so unusual and so inestimable in
value,'' he said. In a recent interview, Bartlett's
great-great-great-great granddaughter, Ruth Ready, says she has
struggled with having to part with meticulously kept family history.
   Ready, 38, owns the home with her 71-year-old aunt, Janet Donahue
of New Rochelle, N.Y., who wanted to sell the estate. Ready hopes to
buy her aunt's half of the house with her share of the auction
proceeds.
   Pausing before a delicate-looking 18th century duckfoot table,
Ready described how it was saved from a fire that destroyed the
original Bartlett house in February 1774. The present house was
built later that year.
   ``The main reason I always liked it was because it has some
history,'' said Ready, a postal clerk. ``When I grew up, I wasn't
looking at it like a piece of furniture that could be worth a lot of
money _ it was more to me.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
