<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionSentencing 1stLd-Writethru a0455becomeNewarkAirport.
06-23 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Sentencing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0455,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Abortion Protesters Ready to Go to Jail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS third graf, `Police prepared...', to CORRECT number facing
sentencing to up to 50 sted 54, SUBS seventh graf, `More than...', to drop
reference to 54. Spelling of Landwhr cq in graf 14. Sentencing set for
5 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LUIS CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of anti-abortion demonstrators say they're
prepared to spend a year in jail rather than promise not to blockade
abortion clinics for two years, a defense lawyer said.
   ``We're willing to face the consequences,'' attorney Thomas
Olmstead said Thursday.
   Police prepared for a possible confrontation at the District
Court in adjacent Bellevue, where up to 50 faced sentencing today on
criminal trespass charges for attempting to block an abortion clinic
on Nov. 12.
   Fifty officers were placed on call and protesters were expected
to come from as far away as California, said Maj. Paul Olson, head
of the Bellevue Police Department patrol division.
   The security is partly in response to dozens of angry letters
Judge Joel Rindal has received from abortion foes, Olson said.
   An an initial sentencing hearing in April, Rindal stunned the
protesters when he said he would sentence them to the maximum
penalty of $5,000 in fines and a year in jail unless they promised
not to commit the same offense for two years. He gave them two
months to make up their minds.
   More than 40 defendants say they'll choose jail time, Olmstead
said.
   ``Throughout the Bible there are instances where the law of God
was more important than the laws of man,'' he said. ``Martin Luther
King broke the law throughout the South because he believed God's
law was higher than the law of Alabama.''
   Olmstead said protesters believe ``God is on our side.''
   ``There's no question what I'll do, I don't have a choice but to
go to jail,'' Jim Demers, who is defending himself in the case, told
the Journal-American, a Bellevue newspaper.
   Another defendant, Kenneth Bridges, said he would give up his
$45,000-a-year oil refinery job and go to jail if necessary.
   ``In good conscience, I couldn't promise a judge I wouldn't
commit another `rescue' for two years,'' he told the newspaper. The
protesters claim their blockade was an attempt to rescue fetuses
from abortion.
   But some defendants said they would promise not to break the law
because of family obligations.
   ``The harm psychologically and emotionally to my children would
be greater than any good I could do in jail for a year,'' defendant
Pat Landwhr said. But she said she was willing to spend as long as
50 days in jail rather than pay a possible fine of $1,000.
   ``I will not pay for the privilege of protesting in this
country,'' she said.
</TEXT>
