<FIRST>r a PM-NYDeathPenalty     06-23 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NY Death Penalty,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cuomo Calls For Passage of Life Without Parole</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo urged the Legislature to
adopt a punishment of life without parole after lawmakers
indefinitely postponed an attempt to override his latest veto of a
death penalty bill.
   State Senate Majority Leader Ralph Marino said Thursday he was
postponing an override vote because of new cancer surgery for Sen.
James Donovan.
   A consistent death penalty supporter in the past, Donovan stunned
his colleagues last week when he said his bout with cancer had
caused him to have second thoughts about capital punishment.
   The bill's chief sponsor, Sen. Dale Volker, has said Donovan's
support was crucial to winning an override vote in the Senate.
   The chief Assembly sponsor of the bill, Democrat Vincent Graber,
said the postponement effectively put off a showdown on the issue
until next year, when all 211 legislative seats and the governorship
go before the voters.
   New York governors have vetoed legislation to reinstitute the
death penalty every year since 1977.
   After learning of the postponement, Cuomo issued a statement
appealing for quick passage of legislation for life without parole
for murderers.
   With senators unable to override his veto, the Democratic
governor said ``it is incumbent on them to explain what steps they
can take to provide the people of this state, particularly its
police officers, with a tougher penalty for the worst crimes.''
   The Legislature is expected to end its regular 1989 session at
the end of next week.
   New York's electric chair hasn't been used since 1963.
   For the past four years, the Republican-controlled Senate has
voted to override Cuomo's death penalty vetoes, but the effort has
fallen short repeatedly in the Democratic-controlled Assembly.
   This year, death penalty supporters felt they were within one
vote of winning in the Assembly before problems began appearing in
the Senate.
</TEXT>
