<DOCNO> AP890623-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0409EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ProgeriaReunion     06-23 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Progeria Reunion,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victims of Rare Accelerated-Aging Disease Attend Annual Reunion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE WALES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They are coming from Australia, Argentina
and South Africa as well as other far-flung places in search of
support and a cure for their rare disease.
   Fifteen victims of the accelerated-aging disease known as
progeria are gathering this weekend at the River Ranch resort in
this central Florida community for the eighth annual reunion
sponsored by the Sunshine Foundation.
   The boys and girls, ages 4 to 19, meet once a year with their
parents and siblings to enjoy themselves in a vacation setting,
exchange experiences and come under observation from doctors, who
monitor their progress and hope to develop an effective treatment
for the rare condition.
   The genetic syndrome, which has a reported incidence of 1 in 8
million newborn children, is characterized by rapid aging, dwarfism,
baldness and distortion of facial features and bodily joints. Its
cause is unknown. Patients usually die of cardiac complications
between ages 7 and 27.
   Among those who will take part in the weeklong gathering is
16-year-old Fransie Geringer, perhaps the best-known of the progeria
victims because of previous visits to the United States from his
home in South Africa.
   The publicity surrounding Fransie's trip to Disneyland in
California in the early 1980s led to the series of reunions by the
non-profit Sunshine Foundation, which was formed in Phildelphia in
1976 to grant wishes to terminally ill children.
   The youngest child scheduled to attend is 4-year-old Courtney
Arciaga of Bonita, Calif. The oldest is 19-year-old Greg Mercer of
Warner Robins, Ga.
   ``The families are very close. None of them knew each other
before the foundation began its reunions,'' said publicists Julie
Auspitz.
   The founder of the Sunshine Foundation, former Philadelphia
policeman Bill Sample, said: ``Because of these reunions, they're
not alone anymore. They have brothers and sisters now.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
