<DOCNO> AP890623-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0446EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Angola-Glance     06-23 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola-Glance,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angola at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Angola, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures on Angola.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE HISTORY _ Portuguese settlers reached Angola in the 15th
century and ruled it as a colony until Angola gained independence in
1975. Virtually all the Portuguese fled at that time, leaving the
country more than 90 percent illiterate and woefully short of
capital and skilled workers. After fighting a civil war since
independence, Angola formally accepted an agreement along with South
Africa in July 1988 that was designed to withdraw foreign troops
from Angola and grant independence to Namibia.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND AND PEOPLE _ Angola, twice the size of Texas, is on the
southwest coast of Africa. Its capital is Luanda. Most of the
country is a plateau, with a tropical climate. Angola is bounded by
Congo on the north, Zaire on the north and northeast, Zambia on the
east, Namibia on the south and the Atlantic on the west. It has 8
million people, most of them living in tribal villages and rural
areas from three ethnic groups, the Ovimbundu, the Kimbundu, and the
Bakongo. Mixed-race and white Angolans comprise about 1 percent.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE GOVERNMENT _ The Marxist Popular Movement for the Liberation
of Angola, one of the guerrilla groups that fought the Portuguese,
has controlled the country since it seized Luanda in 1976 with the
help of Cuban troops. An estimated 50,000 Cuban troops helped the
government of President Eduardo dos Santos fight the rebels of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), which
seeks a power-sharing agreement.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ Almost 200 oil wells in the Angolan enclave of
Cabinda supply more than 90 percent of the country's export
earnings. U.S. oil companies help run the petroleum fields. Cuban
and Angolan troops protect the fields against UNITA guerrillas, who
use American weapons to try to sabotage the facilities. Angola is
also rich in diamonds and has potential for mining other minerals,
including uranium. It also has rich agricultural land, but the
economy has been seriously disrupted by civil war since independence.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   UNITA _ Jonas Savimbi's UNITA rebels fought the Portuguese until
they departed and now oppose the MPLA government. UNITA receives
U.S. aid. South African troops backed the rebels until a pullout in
August 1988 under terms of a regional peace accord that UNITA did
not sign. UNITA says it controls about one-third of Angola and
claims widespread popular support.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE REFUGEES _ About 1.5 million Angolans fled areas of fighting
and are registered as displaced persons in the country by the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Disabled     06-23 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Disabled,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Backs Civil Rights for Disabled, Lists Some Areas
of Concern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration endorsed landmark
legislation to bring millions of disabled Americans into society's
mainstream but has disagreements over several specific provisions.
   ``We must end the anomaly of widely protecting women and
minorities from discrimination while failing to provide parallel
protection for people with disabilities,'' Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh said Thursday.
   Thornburgh told the Senate Labor and Human Resources Committee
the administration was prepared ``to work in good faith toward a
consensus'' on areas of concern.
   Those areas included the scope of the public accommodations
provisions, the size of businesses covered by the employment
discrimination section and the inclusion of punitive damages as a
legal remedy, he said.
   But the attorney general and representatives of disabled-rights
groups played down the disagreements over the proposed Americans
with Disabilities Act.
   ``It's a historic day, the administration and the legislature for
mainstreaming disabled people,'' said Evan Kemp Jr., a member of the
U.S. Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. ``This is the first
administration that has ever taken a disability bill seriously.''
   ``I don't see any potential major areas of disagreement,'' said
Pat Wright, Washington director of the Disabled Rights Education and
Defense Fund.
   David Runkel, Thornburgh's chief spokesman, said ``there are some
differences'' but added that ``I don't think anybody sees there's
any insolvable problem at this time.''
   The bill would prohibit employment discrimination against people
with disabilities by business with more than 15 employees.
   It would also require theaters, restaurants and public offices to
make ``reasonable accommodations'' to improve access for disabled
persons that are ``readily achievable'' without posing an ``undue
hardship'' on businesses.
   New buses purchased by public transit authorities would be
required to be equipped with wheelchair lifts.
   ``We are firmly committed to the notion that every new bus
purchased by public transit authorities in the United States should
be fully accessible, period,'' Thornburgh said.
   ``What has to be examined is the coverage of the public
accommodations language. How many public accommodations are covered
will depend to a great extend on the definition that's given to
`reasonable accommodation,''' Thornburgh said.
   ``I hope that kind of examination will be at the top of the list
that should be considered in reaching some specificity'' of
definitions, Thornburgh said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
