<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     06-23 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bradley, Lautenberg Say Federal Regs Send Message to Dumpers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot federal program that tracks medical
waste from the hospital to the dump should make life more pleasant
for beachgoers and more expensive for illegal dumpers, New Jersey's
senators say.
   ``Who wants to tiptoe through the needles?'' asked Sen. Frank
Lautenberg, D-N.J., as he and Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., discussed
implementation of the 1988 Medical Waste Tracking Act, which became
effective Thursday.
   The two senators held a news conference after meeting with
Environmental Protection Agency officials to discuss the program,
which could be made nationwide after it is evaluated by Congress.
   The federal law authorizes a two-year pilot program that subjects
producers, transporters and disposers of medical waste in New
Jersey, New York, Connecticut, Louisiana, Rhode Island, the District
of Columbia and Puerto Rico to federal and state inspections and
legal action.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Panel Restores Funds For V-22 Osprey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee has sent Defense Secretary
Dick Cheney ``a clear signal'' by approving an amendment to save the
V-22 Osprey aircraft by giving it $351 million of research and
development funds, says Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa.
   The amendment was approved 11-7 during a closed session of the
Armed Services research and development subcommittee, according to
aides to Weldon, who sponsored the amendment with Rep. Thomas
Foglietta, D-Pa.
   The amendment was backed despite opposition by the subcommittee
chairman, Ron Dellums, D-Calif., and by Rep. William Dickinson,
R-Ala., the panel's ranking Republican, according to Weldon press
aide Doug Ritter.
   Cheney, in overseeing cuts in the fiscal 1990 budget promised by
President Bush, announced in April that he was scuttling the V-22
program as too expensive. He has held that position in spite of
congressional pressure and threats by contractors to begin layoffs.
   The V-22, described by the Marine Corps as its most important
weapons program, is a revolutionary aircraft designed to take off
like a helicopter and fly like a plane.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>TV Networks Ask Congressional Help in Battle for TV Rerun Rights</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The three major TV networks, contending the
tradition of free television is threatened, have asked Congress to
side with them in a war against Hollywood studios over lucrative
syndication rights to reruns of popular shows.
   The top executives of CBS, ABC and NBC warned that unless the
rules are changed so they can get in on the syndication of such
shows as ``Jeopardy'' and ``Cheers'' viewers may have to start
paying for the World Series, Olympics and Super Bowl on TV.
   ``At any point in time, the cable systems can take away the World
Series,'' Laurence A. Tisch, president of CBS Inc., told the Senate
Commerce Committee's communications subcommittee.
   At issue is a regulation issued in the 1970s by the Federal
Communications Commission forbidding networks from having any
ownership in programing they did not produce or from selling them to
independent TV stations for syndicated reruns.
   The FCC, as well as the Federal Trade Commission and Justice
Department, called for repeal of the so-called Financial Interest
and Syndication Rule in 1983 as an antiquated regulatory practice.
</TEXT>
