<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0204</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off 1.05 Yen, Tokyo Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar dropped sharply against the Japanese
yen today, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index rose
moderately.
   The dollar ended trading at 140.35 yen, down 1.05 yen from
Thursday's close of 141.40 yen. After opening lower at 139.60 yen,
the currency traded between 139.40 yen and 140.60 yen.
   Shigeru Tamaki, a senior currency dealer at the Industrial Bank
of Japan Ltd., said the dollar was ``well bidded above the 140-yen
level,'' though it fell briefly below 140 yen in early trading.
   ``The dollar will remain firm for the time being,'' Tamaki said.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which
shed 20.31 points Thursday, gained 205.74 points, or 0.61 percent,
to end the week at 33,530.71.
   Dealers said the market's main index gained broadly, encouraged
by the relative stability of the dollar-yen exchange rate.
   ``With the stability in the exchange rate, investors gained
confidence in a broad range of stocks,'' Tamaki said.
   Among major winners were shipbuildings, shippings, constructions
and basic material-related issues. The volume traded in the first
section totaled 750 billion shares, up from Thursday's 550 million
shares.
