<HEAD>Judge Agrees to Seek Outside Jury in Cottam Case</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. (AP) _ A judge has granted defense motions to
look for jurors from another county for the trial of a couple
accused of starving their son to death.
   ``A fair trial is impossible at this time in Luzerne County,''
Judge Gifford S. Cappellini said Thursday. ``Because of the nature
of the pretrial publicity, virtually every prospective juror in
Luzerne County was exposed to it.''
   Defense attorneys for Larry and Leona Cottam renewed their calls
to seek jurors outside the county after 14 potential jurors were
dismissed during the eighth day of jury selection on Wednesday.
   The Cottams face third-degree murder charges in the Jan. 3 death
of their 14-year-old son, Eric.
   Authorities said the Cottams allowed their two children to go
without food for 42 days rather than spend more than $2,130 in cash
set aside as a religious tithe. The Cottams and their 12-year-old
daughter, Laura, were hospitalized for malnutrition.
   The nine jurors who had been picked from among 82 prospects were
dismissed Thursday morning by Cappellini.
   The state Supreme Court will decide what county the jurors will
be chosen from, Cappellini said.
   The Cottams continue to be held in the Luzerne County
Correctional Facility in lieu of $50,000 bail. Their daughter was
placed in a foster home.
   If convicted of third-degree murder, the Cottams would face a
maximum sentence of 20 years in prison. They also have been charged
with two counts each of recklessly endangering another person and
endangering the welfare of children.
