assistant to the television ministry's music director and soon
became Bakker's most trusted aide. According to PTL records, he drew
more than $620,000 in pay in the 15 months ending March 1987, when
Bakker resigned in a sex and money scandal.
   James Taggart received nearly $300,000 during that period, when
he was PTL's interior decorator.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Potter asked some potential jurors if
they contributed regularly to a church or a religious organization.
He also asked if they were familiar with brand names such as Gucci,
Jaguar, Cartier and Mercedes-Benz. He then asked if they buy
clothing and jewelry in discount stores or expensive shops, and if
they normally pay with cash, credit cards or checks.
   It was not known whether any prospective jurors were excluded on
the basis of their answers to those questions.
