<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan-China     06-23 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Denies Sending Spies to China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Ministry today denied that 13
men arrested in China on charges of promoting the pro-democracy
movement were spies for Taiwan.
   The ministry said in a statement that the accusations were
China's ``conventional way of framing people with false charges
rather than a fact.''
   Communist China announced the arrests Thursday. It said the 13
men, all Chinese nationals, were recruited by military intelligence
officers of Taiwan's Nationalist government or by local agents.
   China's national television news showed videotapes of some of the
accused men mixing with demonstrators during pro-democracy rallies
in Beijing before the June 3-4 military crackdown. The television
also showed secret codes, letters and invisible ink it said were
used by the men.
   Taiwan's mass-circulation China Times quoted an unidentified
Nationalist intelligence officer as saying that, although Taiwan
maintains agents on the mainland, they long ago stopped using secret
codes and invisible ink.
   Nationalist legislator Chien Han-sheng said China intended to
``divert mainland people's anger and indignation'' over the
crackdown by putting the blame for the turmoil on Taiwan.
   The Chinese Nationalist government fled to Taiwan following its
1949 defeat by communist forces in a civil war.
   The Nationalists remain technically at war with the communists
but recently adopted a more flexible policy that allows visits
across the strait separating the two nations and trade through third
countries.
</TEXT>
