<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-23 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rain Soaks Much of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain fell in much of the nation today and caused flooding in
western New York after flash floods in Pennsylvania led to the
drowning death of a disabled woman.
   Early morning showers and thunderstorms extended today from
Oklahoma across Wisconsin into western Indiana, and across northern
parts of the Virginias and from Georgia across Florida.
   A state of emergency was declared for Genesee County in western
New York, where heavy rains washed out parts of some roads and left
some elevated railroad bridges in danger of collapsing. Roads also
were washed out or closed by flooding in three other counties. At
Arcade, 3{ inches of rain fell Thursday evening.
   Flood watches were posted through the morning in much of the
central and southern Appalachians and a large part of western New
York.
   Heavy thunderstorms in southeastern Pennsylvania unleashed flash
floods that stranded rush-hour commuters Thursday and led to a freak
drowning accident, authorities said.
   Linda J. Sanford, a 22-year-old woman with cerebral palsy, was
sitting in her family room at her home in Holland when the room
filled with about 2{ feet of water, said Detective Ken Barnes of the
Northampton Township Police Department. She apparently fell into the
water and drowned, Barnes said.
   Rain soaked parts of Alabama again Thursday, with thunderstorms
downing trees and power lines in Chilton, Cullman and Talladega
counties. Birmingham's suburb of Leeds received nearly 1.7 inches of
rain.
   Rain that flooded farmers' crops and inundated homes has caused
at least $2 million in damage in east-central Alabama, officials
said Thursday.
   More harsh weather also hit Georgia Thursday afternoon, with
lightning sparking at least three house fires in Gwinnett County,
one of which injured four firefighters when a roof collapsed on them.
   A Fire Department spokesman said the firefighters were taken to
Gwinnett Medical Center, where they were treated and released.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
in much of the Gulf Coast, Florida, the southern and middle Atlantic
Coast and the upper Great Lakes; and showers and thunderstorms in
central Oklahoma, the middle and upper Mississippi Valley and the
northern and central Rockies.
   Predicted highs: 60s in eastern Colorado, the northern Rockies
and parts of the Pacific Coast; 90s in Florida, southern Georgia,
the Gulf Coast, much of Texas and southern Oregon; 100s in the
desert Southwest and inland valleys of California; and 70s and 80s
elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming to 90 at Blythe,
Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 67 fair; Boston 67 hazy; Buffalo 65 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 73 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 69 foggy; Cleveland 69
foggy; Detroit 66 foggy; Miami 78 fair; New York 71 foggy;
Philadelphia 73 foggy; Pittsburgh 67 foggy; Portland, Maine 63
partly cloudy; Washington 74 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 53 partly cloudy; Chicago 79 hazy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 76 partly cloudy; Denver 56 cloudy; Des Moines 63 cloudy;
Indianapolis 70 foggy; Kansas City 63 rain; Minneapolis-St. Paul 65
cloudy; Nashville 71 foggy; New Orleans 75 cloudy; St. Louis 77 hazy.
   _West: Albuquerque 55 windy; Anchorage 57 cloudy; Las Vegas 75
fair; Los Angeles 62 cloudy; Phoenix 85 fair; Salt Lake City 61
cloudy; San Diego 62 cloudy; San Francisco 60 fair; Seattle 63 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 68 fair; Toronto 66 foggy.
