<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Party     06-23 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Party,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary Party Meeting Opens Amid Calls for New Party Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Central Committee of Hungary's
deeply split Communist Party met today as some progressives called
for the replacement of centrist party chief Karoly Grosz.
   The state news agency MTI in a terse report announced only that
the meeting had started and that the committee was working on
preparations for a party congress this fall.
   On Thursday, the reform-minded speaker of parliament, Matyas
Szueroes, appeared to lend his voice to calls from other reformers
inside the ruling party for a replacement of Grosz. He took up the
post of party general secretary 13 months ago.
   Szueroes did not criticize Grosz by name. But, according to MTI,
he said the Communist Party could only work for national integration
``if the reform wing unambiguously takes the upper hand and the key
positions are filled by ... popular and intelligent leaders of the
reform wing.''
   Szueroes' remarks followed calls from at least five party reform
groups for Grosz's ouster and a caretaker leadership under
reformers' control until the fall congress.
   The central ground that Grosz tried to stake out has eroded as
the divisions between reformers and more orthodox Communists become
increasingly evident.
   Imre Poszgay, a minister of state and Politburo member who is the
country's leading Communist reformer, said Thursday that the
113-member, policymaking Central Committee would be told to keep
Grosz on as party leader until the congress.
   But he said anything might happen given the fluid situation in
Hungarian politics.
   Democratic reforms have advanced rapidly since Grosz became party
leader in May 1988.
   This week, the Communists and democratic opposition groups agreed
to work out plans for multiparty elections.
   A week ago, Imre Nagy and once reviled fellow leaders of the
failed 1956 uprising against Stalinism were buried after a
nationally televised mourning ceremony attended by Pozsgay, Szueroes
and up to a quarter of a million Hungarians.
</TEXT>
