<FIRST>r a PM-Lite     06-23 0288</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lite,0297</SECOND>
<BYLINE>On the Light Side</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a summer school program that could
really take off, students filled tissue paper balloons with hot air,
built gliders and rigged eggs with parachutes to learn the mysteries
of flight.
   ``It's really not like school,'' said Julie Taylor, a 9-year-old
sky school cadet. ``It's fun because you get to make your own
airplanes and balloons and fly them.''
   Taylor was one of 100 fourth- through 11th-graders who postponed
their summer break for one week to participate in the NASA-inspired
program.
   It was to end today with a hot-air balloon contest and a
soft-landing competition, in which students will try to drop a
one-pound package containing an egg and suspended from a parachute
from a second-story window, without breaking the egg.
   ``My first attempt was a complete disaster, basically,'' said
Marcel Malfregeot, 13, as he proudly displayed his entry _ a small,
white box wrapped in bubbly plastic packing material.
   ``This time I've got a box inside of a box and the egg is totally
surrounded by oatmeal, which is a good shock absorber.''
   Other cadets launched brightly colored gliders or compared models
of real aircraft they built.
   ``Each one of the students has been in the cockpit of an airplane
and learned how to work the controls,'' said Thelma Nutter, a
kindergarten teacher who spent a week at NASA's Sky School in
Orlando, Fla., to prepare for the program.
   Students from 10 counties in north-central West Virginia
participated in the program.
   ``The only problem, as I see it, is that it wasn't long enough,''
said Bob Beckwith, a Randolph County science teacher. ``We had
enough material left over to run the school for another 10 days.''
</TEXT>
