<FIRST>r a PM-FlagBurning     06-23 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Flag Burning,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minature U.S. Flags Burned by Communists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As about 50 onlookers yelled in protest,
seven members of the Revolutionary Communist Youth Brigade set fire
to six miniature American flags at the University of California.
   There was no violence when a 3-by-5 inch and five postage-stamp
size flags were burned on Thursday, one day after the Supreme Court
ruled 5-4 that states cannot enforce laws against burning the
American flag.
   Dean Tuckerman, a self-described anarchist who was not part of
the demonstration, also burned a tiny paper American flag stuck on a
toothpick.
   ``I think it's important to burn flags,'' Tuckerman said. ``I'm
in favor of burning that red flag they're carrying, too, and my
black flag of anarchy. They're just symbols. They're not sacred.''
   As the demonstrators stomped on the burned remains, onlookers
yelled ``Get real!'' and ``Let's talk about Stalin.''
   ``This makes me angry,'' said Michael McCormick, 39, a Vietnam
veteran. ``Americans fought and died for the flag.''
   Demonstrator Chila Morris said she wanted to ``put the flag on
trial against mindless flag-waving.''
   The American flag ``is the flag that flew over slave ships, that
flew with the cavalry that shot Indians,'' she said. ``Now it stands
for U.S. domination of the Third World.''
   John Spahr of Punxsutawney, Pa., said he was delighted his family
encountered a demonstration while visiting Berkeley.
   ``This demonstration's what the flag and this country are all
about,'' he said after his son suggested that the deomonstrators
should be gagged. ``I'm glad my boy got to see this.''
</TEXT>
