<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0838EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-USDoctors     06-23 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-US Doctors,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Burn Specialists End Mission In Ural Mountains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.S. burn specialists returned to Moscow
today after helping Soviet officials treat victims of a gas
explosion that engulfed two passenger trains in flames three weeks
ago.
   At least 600 people died in the June 4 inferno when a spark from
a railroad electrical line ignited a highly flammable mixture of
benzine and propane-butane gas that leaked from a pipeline in the
Ural mountains near the city of Ufa. About 800 passengers were
hospitalized with severe burns.
   The team of about 30 specialists from the Institute of Surgical
Research at Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio, Texas,
carried out 26 skin grafting operations at Ufa's burn center,
according to Dr. Lisa Walker, a team surgeon.
   ``We took care of two intensive care wards and a surgical ward
for less critically burned patients,'' Ms. Walker said at a news
briefing. ``Overall we took care of approximately 80 to 90 victims.''
   She said the U.S. team included three surgeons and support
personnel who worked hand-in-hand with Soviet physicians. They
brought seven tons of special surgical equipment and left most of it
behind in Ufa, Ms. Walker said.
   The burn center team, composed of military doctors, nurses and
technicians, was sent to Ufa after President Bush went to the Soviet
Embassy in Washington to offer condolences to the blast victims and
proposed sending U.S. experts to help survivors.
   ``Our flight team was on standby and ready to be deployed at any
time,'' Ms. Walker said. ``It was easy to mobilize us.''
   She said all of the 26 surgical patients treated by the U.S. unit
were now in stable condition.
   Ray Keith, a medical operations officer, said Soviet treatment of
the blast victims was more than adequate.
   ``I was impressed by the distribution of patients, the equipment
and technology,'' he said. ``They treated the patients very well.''
   Ms. Walker said the team would return to Texas on Sunday.
``Overall it was a very good experience for all of us,'' she said.
   The burn center at Brooke Army Medical Center is the only U.S.
military facility for burn treatment. The burn teams are on standby
to fly anywhere in the world and were used extensively during the
Vietnam War to transfer patients from the battlefield to Japan for
treatment.
</TEXT>
