<SECOND>PM-People-Hurt,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Sitter Says Hurt Referred to Jennings as His Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former baby sitter joined witnesses testifying
that actor William Hurt called Sandra Jennings his wife, but none
has referred to the four weeks on which the former ballerina is
basing her claim for a common-law marriage.
   Linda Patrick testified Thursday that she and Hurt went to lunch
with Hurt's and Jennings' son, Alexander, in the summer of 1985.
   ``How do you like working with my wife?'' she quoted Hurt as
asking.
   However, the value of Patrick's testimony isn't clear. State
Supreme Court Justice Jacqueline Silbermann, who is hearing the case
without a jury, has said what matters is what happened in South
Carolina during four weeks between Dec. 9, 1982, when Hurt learned
that his divorce from actress Mary Beth Hurt was final, and the time
he and Jennings left the state, Jan. 19, 1983.
   South Carolina recognizes common-law marriages; New York does not.
   Jennings is seeking to have the court declare she and Hurt are
married so she can get a divorce and a share of his assets,
estimated by her lawyer, A. Richard Golub, to be about $10 million.
   Jennings, 32, says Hurt introduced her to people in Beaufort,
S.C., where he was filming ``The Big Chill,'' as his wife. But no
testimony or other evidence has been offered to support that
assertion.
   Earlier in the day, Dr. Barbara Ann Barker, who was Hurt's
ophthalmologist and the wife of one of the actor's lawyers,
testified she was unable to explain why Jennings' name was whited
out of a space marked ``spouse'' on one of her office records while
the copy of the record had Jennings' name.
   ``I did not, to my knowledge, white it out,'' Barker replied to a
question by Golub. The lawyer tried to suggest the document was
altered after Jennings sued Hurt.
   The witness also testified that she had never heard Hurt refer to
Jennings as his wife. She said he did hear him say, ``This is the
mother of my child.''
   The civil trial is scheduled to resume Monday.
</TEXT>
