<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--McDonald'sPlastics     06-23 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--McDonald's Plastics,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>McDonald's Customers Cooperate In Recycling Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot program by seven local McDonald's
restaurants to determine if customers will separate recyclable trash
has been labeled a success.
   McDonald's and the Polystyrene Packaging Council, a national
trade and lobby group, wanted to know whether customers would
separate plastic items for recycling.
   At a news conference Thursday, Susan Ferris, the council's Oregon
spokeswoman, said the program worked. The program had customers drop
plastic utensils, straws and hamburger containers into bins marked
for recyclables.
   In the McDonald's program, 300 to 400 pounds of plastics have
been carted away three times a week by recyclers, according to Bruce
Holser of Denton Plastics.
   Ferris said Portland was chosen for the pilot project because
many residents are environmentally conscious. ``We have a willing
community,'' she said. She said she didn't know how long the program
would be continued.
</TEXT>
