<DOCNO> AP890623-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Angola-Chronology 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola-Chronology, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0421,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Main Events in Angolan Peace Process</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs grafs 10-11, `Sept. 17...to UNITA,' to CORRECT sequence
of events and date and CORRECT name of guerrilla group. Pickup 12th, `January
16...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Angola, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of major events in
Angola since 1974:
   April 1974 _ Portugal's Revolution of the Carnations topples a
48-year-old rightist dictatorship and begins the independence
process for African colonies.
   Jan. 1, 1975 _ Angolan liberation movements sign the Alvor
Accords that set Nov. 11, 1975, as the date for Angolan
independence. Beginning of the transitional government, which
included members of all three movements: the Popular Movement for
the Liberation of Angola, Angolan National Liberation Front and
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
   September and October 1975 _ UNITA and the Liberation Front split
from the Popular Movement. Fighting begins.
   Nov. 11, 1975 _ Popular Movement leader Agostinho Neto
unilaterally declares Angolan independence from Portugal. He
requests aid from Cuba. An estimated 50,000 Cuban troops begin
arriving in Luanda.
   Sept. 10, 1979 _ Neto dies of cancer in Moscow. Jose Eduardo dos
Santos elected successor. Seen as moderate candidate between rival
Popular Movement factions.
   August, 1981 _ Operation Protea, in which an estimated 15,000
South African soldiers enter 75 miles into Angolan territory backed
by tanks and air force. Angolan government estimates more than 700
Angolans killed and 130,000 left homeless in the fighting.
   February, 1984 _ Angola, South Africa and the United States sign
Lusaka Agreement that foresees pull-out of South African troops and
sets up joint military commission to monitor Angola's border with
Namibia.
   July-September, 1984 _ UNITA attacks Cabinda oil field, Benguela
railroad, ships in Luanda harbor.
   August, 1985 _ U.S. Clark Amendment repealed, allowing United
States to resume aid to UNITA.
   Sept. 17, 1985 _ South African troops enter Angola claiming to
pursue guerrillas from the South-West African People's Organization.
   January 16, 1988 _ About 6,000 South African troops begin
operation to conquer Cuito Cuanavale, southern Angolan garrison town
contested by the Popular Movement.
   May 4, 1988 _ Cuban and Angolan troops claim to have pushed back
South Africans at Cuito Cuanavale. South Africa and UNITA also claim
victory.
   July, 1988 _ Angola, Cuba and South Africa agree in New York for
Cuban withdrawal and Namibian independence. The rebels are not a
party to the agreement.
   August 1988 _ The three declare cease-fire.
   November 1988 _ With U.S. mediation, they agree on timetable for
Cuban pull-out and implementation of U.N. Security Council
Resolution 435 for Namibian independence.
   Dec. 13, 1988 _ Angola, Cuba and South Africa sign Brazzaville
Agreement in Congolese capital that sets April 1, 1989 as date for
start of Namibian independence plan and mid-1991 as final date for
Cuban withdrawal.
   Dec. 22, 1988 _ Final New York peace accords signed.
   January 1989 _ First Cubans leave Angola.
   April 1, 1989 _ Namibian independence process stumbles day it
begins as supporters of SWAPO, the rebel South-West Africa People's
Organization clash with South African-led security forces in
northern Namibia.
   May 16, 1989 _ Angola proposes peace plan to eight African
leaders at Luanda summit.
   June 22, 1989 _ Dos Santos and Savimbi shake hands at Gbadolite,
Zaire, and agree on cease-fire to begin at midnight tonight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0086 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1027EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a StanfordAgreesToReturnSkeletalRemainsToIndiV-37-jerusalem-(jocelynnoveck)-israelileadersrefuseto
    06-23 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>Stanford Agrees To Return Skeletal Remains To Indians</SECOND>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stanford University has agreed to return
the bones of more than 500 Indians to the Ohlone-Costanoan people
for reburial.
   Indians, who consider ancestral remains sacred, have praised the
move announced Wednesday, following followed five years of
negotiations between the university and the Ohlone tribe. But some
anthropologists say it is a blow to medical research.
   Stanford is ``giving the Indians the right to decide'' whether to
take possession of the remains or allow delays for further research,
Stanford archaeologist Barbara Bocek said.
   Once the Indians take charge of the remains, she said, it would
be assumed that they would be reburied and gone forever from
research.
   The decision is up to the Ohlones, she said, and ``if they came
today for the bones'' they would be returned.
   Rayna Green, a Cherokee scholar and author from Washington, D.C.,
said she knew of no other formal agreement like the one between
Stanford and the Ohlones.
   ``It's really extraordinary,'' she said. ``I'm deeply admiring of
what Stanford is doing.''
   ``The decision to support reinterment has been difficult,''
Provost James Rosse wrote to the elders of the Ohlones.
   In Washington, the chairman of the anthropology department of the
Smithsonian Institution said researchers have made important strides
recently in analyzing proteins in Indian remains that could help
medical researchers in the study of bone and joint diseases.
   ``From a scientific standpoint, it's a very bad move,'' Donald
Ortner told The Washington Post. ``There is going to be a terrible
price to be paid down the road.''
   Bocek said most of the remains involved come from California's
Ryan Mound in Fremont and the Castro Mound in Mountain View. Most
were acquired by Stanford scholars as far back as the turn of the
century.
   ``Indians feel an extremely great sense of continuity with their
ancestors over generations,'' she said. ``The tradition of respect
and responsibility for their elders, including those who died long
ago, is still a very vital part of the culture.''
   Rosemary Cambra, a representative of the Ohlones, said she was
``very, very happy Stanford has agreed to respect the religious
rights of the Indians.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe 1stLd-Writethru a0454 06-23 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Using Connections to Get Government Millions OK, Ambassador Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS new 14th graf, When she, to include background on earlier
testimony by Pierce and Ms. Dean.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a group of former federal housing
officials says there was nothing wrong with using their connections
to get millions of government dollars for apartment projects they
were developing.
   ``Is it unethical for anybody who has been in government to use
the expertise they picked up?'' Philip Winn, now the U.S. ambassador
to Switzerland, asked following his testimony Thursday before a
congressional panel. ``I don't see anything unethical.''
   Winn, who was an assistant secretary of HUD for a year before
making an unsuccessful run for the 1982 GOP gubernatorial nomination
in Colorado, led a group that won HUD funds for several projects in
the West and Southwest. In tax credits alone, those projects got
some $29 million from the federal government.
   Asked if he and his partners used their influence with the agency
to their advantage, Winn replied: ``It may very well be the case.''
   ``I don't believe my partners willfully disregarded any rules or
regulations,'' he added.
   Among Winn's other partners were Silvio DeBartolomeis, former
general deputy assistant secretary for housing; J. Michael Queenan,
the former director of HUD's Denver regional office; and Lance
Wilson, a former executive assistant to then-HUD Secretary Samuel
Pierce Jr.
   Winn was greeted skeptically by members of the House Government
Operations subcommittee on employment and housing when he said no
rules were broken and that competition wasn't squelched.
   ``If it is your purpose to show how that is not the way things
worked, you have a tall order, Mr. Ambassador,'' said Rep. Tom
Lantos, D-Calif., the subcommittee's chairman.
   Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn., also criticized Winn: ``You're
really out of touch.''
   One of Winn's partners was Philip Abrams, who had been HUD
undersecretary _ the second-highest post in the department.
   Earlier, Abrams told the panel that his position at HUD _ which
he likened to being vice president of the United States _ rarely
gave him operational authority and that some of those functions had
been handled by Deborah Gore Dean, who followed Wilson as executive
assistant to Pierce.
   In testimony before the panel, Ms. Dean has been identified time
and again as the key individual within the department whose support
was needed to get increasingly scarce government funds to pay
developers for fixing up and running housing projects for the poor
and the elderly.
   Her wide-ranging but unofficial authority, as well as Pierce's
detached management of the department, have become focal points of
the investigation into allegations of influence peddling at HUD.
   When she appeared before the subcommittee a few weeks ago, Ms.
Dean invoked her constitutional right against self-incrimination and
refused to testify. Pierce's testimony before the panel in May at
times became a shouting match as the former secretary tried to
defend his role at the department and members of Congress accused
him of trying to deflect blame.
   Abrams testified that before leaving HUD in 1984, his
relationship with Ms. Dean was cordial but became strained on
occasion.
   He said it flared up ``on one occasion when she thought that I
had sidestepped her.''
   But he said they became more friendly after he quit the
department and went into partnership with Winn.
   On two occasions in 1986, Abrams sent hand-written notes to Ms.
Dean, both addressed ``Dear Debbie,'' seeking HUD funding for
projects in Oklahoma and Nevada. Both projects got the money.
   The subcommittee on Thursday also heard from Joseph Strauss, a
former special assistant to Pierce who received $1.3 million in
consultant fees in connection with 13 moderate rehabilitation
projects.
   After leaving HUD to go into private business, Strauss hired
former Interior Secretary James Watt on a retainer to help get money
from the department.
   ``The reason was because of his access and his influence,''
Strauss said of his decision to retain Watt. ``I don't want to make
any bones about that.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0088 </DOCNO>
