<FIRST>r a PM-PoliceDisciplined     06-23 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police Disciplined,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>L.A. Police Chief Disciplines 38 Officers in Violent Drug Raid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-eight police officers are being
disciplined and some could be fired after inner-city residents filed
a civil rights lawsuit saying their homes were vandalized and they
were terrorized during a drug raid.
   ``This is not something I do with any joy at all,'' Chief Daryl
Gates said during a news conference Thursday. ``But clearly, the
situation got out of control. The officers were trying very hard to
do the right thing _ to solve the gang problem, to solve the
narcotics trafficking problem. Unfortunately, while doing the right
thing, they were doing it in the wrong way.''
   A drive-by shooting involving gang members prompted the raid by
88 officers Aug. 1. Police officials later determined that during
the raid, walls and plumbing fixtures in four homes were smashed and
some residents were beaten and humiliated.
   Nine officers have been ordered to appear before department Board
of Rights tribunals and face firing or long suspensions from duty
without pay, Gates said. Twenty-five others agreed to suspensions of
22 days or less without pay.
   Three other officers had letters of reprimand placed in their
files, and a captain has been reassigned to another job at a lower
salary, Gates said.
   The 38 were charged with violations ranging from lying to
department investigators to damaging personal property.
   In addition, two officers also involved in the raids have
resigned, and another was fired for an unrelated rules violation,
police officials said.
   Police seized crack cocaine, marijuana and a sawed-off rifle
during the raid, Gates said. Of 32 people taken into custody, nine
were arrested.
   The lawsuit, filed in federal court by some of the 32, alleges
they were forced to whistle the theme song from the old Andy
Griffith television show and run a gantlet of officers at the police
station. It also says that officers spray-painted walls of the homes
with such anti-gang slogans.
</TEXT>
