<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Israel     06-23 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Israel,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Say Israeli Troops and Militiamen Stage Attack in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RASHAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops and allied militiamen
backed by helicopter gunships today launched attacks on pro-Iranian
guerrillas in southeast Lebanon, outside Israel's self-proclaimed
security zone, police said.
   Israeli army officials denied their troops were involved and said
their militia allies, the South Lebanon Army, carried out the
``initiative actions.''
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, Iran's main Shiite Moslem ally in
Lebanon, said in a statement its guerrillas suffered ``a number of
casualties, killed and wounded'' in the three-hour attack that began
at 11 a.m.
   Police said about 300 Israeli troops and militiamen of the South
Lebanon Army in 35 armored personnel carriers moved up for the
assault behind an artillery barrage, with backing from three Israeli
helicopter gunships.
   The attackers fought their way into the villages of Kawkaba,
Dellafeh, Kfar Houna and Mydoun, three to four miles north of the
security zone in the Syrian-controlled western Bekaa valley, police
reported.
   They blew up several houses in a search for Hezbollah guerrillas,
said a police spokesman who cannot be named under standing
regulations. He said it was not known if any guerrillas were
arrested.
   Israeli officials said the force made sweeps for guerrillas and
weapons south of Mydoun and returned safely early in the afternoon.
   The attack occurred two miles south of the Syrian army's front
lines in the Bekaa valley. The Syrians took no part in the
hostilities, the police spokesman said.
   Israel carved out the security zone when it withdrew the bulk of
its invading army from south Lebanon in the summer of 1985 after a
three-year occupation.
   The 6-to-10-mile deep enclave, a buffer against guerrilla attacks
on northern Israeli settlements, is patrolled by the Israeli army
and the SLA.
</TEXT>
