<FIRST>r a PM-DumpsterTransient     06-23 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dumpster Transient,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Man Scooped Up in Trash Bin Found Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CULVER CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A transient with a history of sleeping
in big trash bins was found dead after he was scooped up by a
garbage truck crew.
   An autopsy performed Thursday to determine the cause of death was
incomplete, which means the man could have been dead before he was
hoisted into the truck, said Los Angeles County coroner's spokesman
Bob Dambacher.
   The man's body was covered with cuts and bruises but didn't
appear crushed, although he had been tossed into the truck's trash
compactor, which can exert more than 17,000 pounds of pressure per
square inch, said police Lt. Ellis Smith.
   The man probably failed to awake when the trash hopper at a
storefront district on Sepulveda Boulevard was picked up
mechanically Wednesday morning and upended over the cargo bay of the
garbage truck.
   But Culver City sanitation manager Mark Gauerke conceded the
possibility that the hydraulic lifts could have drowned out the
homeless man's screams.
   Authorities withheld the 41-year-old man's name early today
because his family had not yet been notified.
   ``He had a history of wrapping himself up in carpets and sleeping
in dumpsters,'' Ellis said.
</TEXT>
