<FIRST>u i PM-GeorgeProfile 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0586</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-George Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0517,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnapped U.S. Aid Worker Knows Palestinian Life from Inside</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with George released. Pickup 9th
pvs, `George was...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gaza-Kidnap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chris George devoted more than a decade to
helping Palestinian refugees in the Middle East. Now, Palestinian
militants are being blamed for his abduction.
   George, co-director of the Save The Children Federation in
Jerusalem, was seized Thursday and released today after about 30
hours.
   George knows how to survive and even make things happen in the
complex and often tumultuous Middle East. He is fluent in Arabic
after earlier postings in Oman and Lebanon. Friends know him as a
man who can be called for help at any time, day or night.
   Because he and his wife lived in a Palestinian community in the
West Bank, they were more affected by the 18-month uprising than
many foreigners who live in Israeli cities.
   Frequent strikes closed the local market. A boycott of
Israeli-made goods declared by underground leaders had the Georges
asking friends for recipes on how to make butter and yogurt at home.
   On Thursday, the turmoil of this part of the world overwhelmed
George like never before.
   The 35-year-old, from Montclair, N.J., was kidnapped in Gaza
City, and the Israeli army blamed ``terrorists linked to the PLO.''
Palestinian sources said handwritten letters demanded Israel release
Palestinian prisoners in exchange for his freedom.
   George was the first foreigner kidnapped in Israel or the
occupied areas since the 1967 Middle East conflict, according to the
Foreign Ministry.
   George is no stranger to detention. On May 24, Israeli soldiers
seized him in a raid on the Al Amari camp in the occupied West Bank,
where he lives, and held him several hours. The soldiers finally
realized he was an American and set him free.
   George was especially upset that the soldiers entered his home
with M-16 automatic rifles.
   ``We do not allow weapons in my home, and I certainly did not
want my children to see them,'' he said.
   George lives with his wife, 34-year-old Elizabeth Webb, and their
two daughters, 4-year-old Susannah and 2-year-old Rosalind, in an
apartment house overlooking the camp on the outskirts of Ramallah.
   He told the The Associated Press that during his detention, he
tried to make sure Palestinians held by the soldiers at the camp
were well treated.
   He complained, however, that ``if anyone talked, they were
shouted at or kicked.''
   George said that when he saw a soldier kick a Palestinian in the
side, he told the soldier ``that isn't necessary'' and was told
``shut up.''
   The relief official began work overseas with the Peace Corps in
Oman in the 1970's.
   Before and after Israel's 1982 invasion, he lived and worked in
the Ein Hilweh camp outside Sidon, Lebanon. The camp had a large
civilian population but also served as a base for Palestine
Liberation Organization guerrilla groups.
   George helped Palestinian families readjust and rebuild after
Israeli shells and bombs devastated the camp in the 1982 war.
   Foreigners left the Lebanon office of Save the Children after a
series of kidnappings by Shiite Moslem radicals made the country
unsafe for Westerners. When the Israeli army last month began
restricting movement of Gaza workers into Israel, George told The
Associated Press he would survey the strip to see if the 700,000
Palestinian residents needed more projects to improve their
self-sufficiency. He was on a field trip Thursday when he
disappeared.
</TEXT>
