<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     06-23 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal,0316</SECOND>
<UNK>Women Protesting Uno Geisha Scandal Reportedly Scuffle With Supporters</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A scuffle broke out today between supporters of
Prime Minister Sousuke Uno and women who say he should resign
because of allegations he kept a mistress, a news agency reported.
   Uno was speaking at a campaign rally for a candidate running for
the Tokyo assembly when the confrontation occurred, the Kyodo News
Service said.
   Several members of the governing Liberal Democratic Party shouted
insults at women who carried placards saying ``A prime minister who
buys sex is a national disgrace'' and ``We don't need a prostitution
premier,'' the report said. Kyodo quoted one of the women as saying
a party member shoved a Japanese flag at her after several placards
were pulled down.
   No one was injured, and police reported no arrests.
   Party officials could not be reached for comment tonight. Kyodo
said one official had apologized for the scuffle.
   A Tokyo police official said he had no knowledge of the scuffle
but that women carrying placards with anti-Uno slogans held a march
before Uno arrived and attended the rally. About 3,000 people
attended the rally, said the official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Women's groups across the nation have called on Uno to either
confirm or deny a published report charging that he paid a geisha to
be his mistress for several months in 1985.
   Uno, who is married, has refused to comment. His took over as
prime minister on June 3 after his predecessor, Noboru Takeshita,
was forced to resign because of the Recruit influence-peddling
scandal.
   The scandal involved dozens of prominent politicians and
businessmen. Prosecutors say the politicians bought stock in a
Recruit subsidiary and then profited handsomely when it went public.
   The Liberal Democrats chose Uno as their leader because of his
clean image. The geisha report surfaced later.
</TEXT>
