<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Greece     06-23 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Greece,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservatives Fail to Form Government; Papandreou Asked to Try</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president today asked interim Premier
Andreas Papandreou, who is hospitalized with pneumonia, to try to
form a new government after conservative leader Constantine
Mitsotakis failed to do so.
   There was no immediate comment from Papandreou, who was admitted
to General State Hospital on Thursday. He has until Monday to come
up with a government.
   A medical bulletin today said the 70-year-old Papandreou, who led
Greece eight years until his party lost Sunday's election, was
``receiving the proper medical treatment and will remain in the
hospital.'' Papandreou underwent a triple heart bypass operation in
London eight months ago.
   Mitsotakis told President Christos Sartzetakis today he was
unable to form a government in the three-day constitutional limit.
He blamed the failure on the Coalition of Left and Progress, an
alliance of the Communist and Greek Left parties.
   Sunday's national elections ended without a majority in
Parliament, forcing the country to seek its first coalition
government since the return to democracy in 1974.
   Under the constitution, the president offers the leading party,
Mitsotakis' center-right New Democracy, the first chance to form a
government. Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or PASOK,
which finished second in the election, gets the second chance,
followed by the Coalition, which finished third.
   ``New Democracy made specific proposals to the Greek political
world and especially to the left. The proposals I made were honest
and went beyond the demands of the left,'' Mitsotakis said at a news
conference after his meeting with the president.
   The conservative leader had appealed to the Coalition to join an
interim government with a mandate limited to rooting out allegations
of corruption and scandal in Papandreou's government.
   He said the government would last only a few months and would
call new elections after carrying out the ``catharsis,'' or
cleansing of Greece's government.
   Mitsotakis met twice with Harilaos Florakis, the president of the
Coalition, in his efforts to reach an agreement.
   ``I have offered two crucial ministries to the left. The ministry
of catharsis _ the Justice Ministry _ and the Interior Ministry,''
Mitsotakis said.
   ``The offer remains open. Our party remains open for discussion,
with the left or anyone else. The catharsis must occur,'' the
conservative leader said.
   Papandreou and most of his socialist Cabinet retained their posts
in a caretaker capacity following Sunday's election.
   New Democracy won 145 parliamentary seats in the vote, seven
short of the number needed for a majority in the 300-seat
Parliament. PASOK won 125 seats and the Coalition 28.
   Mitsotakis said a government must be formed quickly as Greece was
``being shamed internationaly'' following revelations of a new
banking scandal.
   The scandal involves the arrest of 13 executives of the Greek
Mortgage Bank who allegedly laundered about $700 million though its
American braches.
   Papandreou's defeat at the polls came after another bank scandal
involving the Bank of Crete and its chairman, George Koskotas, who
was accused of taking money from the bank.
   Koskotas claimed Papandreou and other members of his government
took some of the money to finance their campaign. Papandreou denied
wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
