<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Bankruptcy     06-23 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Bankruptcy,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>States Immune from Suits for Monetary Damages by Bankrupt Businesses
and People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   States are immune from being sued for monetary
damages by bankrupt businesses and individuals, the Supreme Court
ruled today.
   By a 5-4 vote in a Connecticut case, the court said federal
bankruptcy law may not be used to pierce the legal armor the
Constitution gives states.
   In a separate bankruptcy ruling, the court voted 6-3 that
defendants charged by a bankruptcy trustee with fraud are entitled
to jury trials.
   The decision in the Connecticut case was a defeat for Martin W.
Hoffman, a court-appointed trustee supervising payment to creditors
of the Wilington Convalescent Home and Edward Zera, who ran a
maintenance service.
   The nursing home, which shut its doors in 1983, said Connecticut
owed it $64,000 in Medicaid payments for patients it treated.
   ``Congress did not abograte 11th Amendment immunity by enacting
(federal bankruptcy law),'' Justice Byron R. White wrote in the
court's main opinion.
   Justices Thurgood Marshall, William J. Brennan, Harry A. Blackmun
and John Paul Stevens dissented.
   In the second case, the court threw out a $1.6 million judgment
against two Colombian banking corporations won by a bankruptcy
trustee for the Chase &amp; Sanborn Corp.
   In an opinion by Brennan, the court said Granfianciera and Medex
wrongly were deprived of a jury trial when facing allegations that
three money transfers from Chase &amp; Sanborn to them were fraudulent
and could be avoided by the bankruptcy trustee.
   Chase &amp; Sanborn filed for protection under federal bankruptcy law
in Miami in 1983.
   Two years later, bankruptcy trustee Paul C. Nordberg filed a
complaint against the two Colombian corporations.
   A bankruptcy judge awarded the trustee $1.5 million from
Granfianciera and $180,000 against Medex.
   But Brennan's opinion said the award cannot stand because the
Constitution's 7th Amendment guarantees such defendants a jury trial
if they request it.
   Justices White, Blackmun and Sandra Day O'Connor dissented.
   The cases are Hoffman vs. Connecticut Department of Income
Maintenance, 88-412, and Granfinanciera vs. Nordberg, 87-1716.
</TEXT>
