<HEAD>Lawmaker Demands Action Against Smokers in Churches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people seem unable to distinguish a cathedral
from a pub, according to a lawmaker who complained Friday about
cigarette smoking in churches.
   Harry Greenway, a member of the Conservative Party, said he had
reported a tourist for smoking in Westminster Abbey last week. An
abbey warden who had warned the offender received ``a packet of
cheek'' in return, Greenway said.
   ``More and more people are casual. They come into churches and
cathedrals, not having a religious background of any kind and not
even a real respect for God's house,'' Greenway said.
   ``They don't even know what they are doing. They don't know that
it is offensive.''
   Speaking in a House of Commons debate on the problem of litter,
Greenaway proposed that people who smoke or throw trash in a church
should be fined at least $1,550.
