<DOCNO> AP890623-0122 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1408EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Crash     06-23 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Crash,0220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jammed Airfoil Caused Crash That Killed 18</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jammed airfoil caused the jetliner crash that
killed 18 people after an aborted takeoff in East Berlin, East
Germany's news agency said Friday.
   The Soviet-built Ilyushin-62 of East Germany's Interflug airline,
with 113 people on board, crashed through trees and burst into
flames at East Berlin's Schoenefeld airport June 17.
   The nose of the Moscow-bound jetliner lifted during takeoff but
then slammed back onto the runway, witnesses said. The jet careened
through a field, ripping apart as it hurtled along, and burst into
flames after coming to a stop.
   One of those killed was a farmer hit by debris as he was working
in the field.
   A commission found that a blocked elevator caused the accident,
the official ADN news agency said. An airplane's elevator, an
airfoil hinged to the tail section, is used to make a plane go up
and down.
   The reasons for the malfunction were still under investigation by
the commission, headed by Transport Minister Otto Arndt, ADN said.
   No evidence of negligence by the crew or ground personnel had
been found, the news agency said.
   The death toll in the accident rose to 18, apparently after a
victim died of injuries suffered in the crash.
</TEXT>
