<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet     06-23 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Confirmation Hearings End With Failed Endorsements for Some</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Committees of the new Soviet legislature have ended
confirmation hearings on nominees for Cabinet posts after failing to
endorse some appointees, news reports said Friday.
   ``Not all candidates proposed by Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov were
supported by the deputies,'' Tass reported without identifying the
rejected appointees.
   Committees of the Supreme Soviet began hearings Monday on 13
Ryzhkov aides and more than 50 ministers in an exercise of the new
oversight powers they gained under President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
political reforms.
   The Communist Party daily newspaper Pravda reported Friday the
nominees who failed to win committee endorsements were Supreme Court
members and officials of the nation's prosecutor's office. The
newspaper did not identify the rejected candidates, saying they
still had a chance to be approved by the full Supreme Soviet that
convenes Monday.
   Deputy Nikolai I. Ignatovich, an investigator in the Byelorussian
prosecutor's office, told Pravda he opposed the Supreme Court
nominees because they were incumbents who had arbitrarily
interpreted the law and continue to distort it. He also told Pravda
the court system had not guaranteed fair trials, and he held the
nominees responsible.
   Pravda also gave a partial account of a Supreme Soviet
committee's grilling of Alexandra P. Biryukova, nominee to head the
government's Bureau of Social Development. She has been in that post
since last October, working on consumer issues and social policy.
   The newspaper said one deputy asked Biryukova whether it was true
the special department of the Health Ministry that provides medical
care for the Soviet elite had a budget of $692.3 million and served
only 480,000 people. The Health Ministry, the deputy charged, was
spending far less per capita on ordinary citizens.
   She said she didn't know the budget of the secretive Fourth
Midecal Department, but that the figure cited was too high.
Biryukova said the Health Ministry was placing priority on improving
childrens hospitals and maternity clinics.
   At a May 31 meeting of the parliament, the Congress of People's
Deputies, party maverick Boris N. Yeltsin called for the Fourth
Medical Department to be used for caring for mothers and their
children.
   ``This should be done for the sake of our future, to avoid having
a situation when infant mortality its twice that of any civilized
country,'' Yeltsin said.
   But Health Minister Yevgeny Chazov rejected the suggestion,
saying the Fourth Medical Department's facilities were not suitable
for care of mothers and children.
   The hearings were not televised, and foreign reporters were
barred from attending. The Soviet press has given them only sparse
coverage.
   Tass has said that among the candidates under scrutiny were
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze, Defense Minister Dmitri T.
Yazov and KGB Chairman Vladimir Kryuchkov.
   The 542-member Supreme Soviet is scheduled to meet for 40 days to
confirm the appointees and begin drafting legislation.
   In proposing the Cabinet members June 10, Ryzhkov said the number
of ministries would be slashed to streamline the government.
</TEXT>
