<FIRST>r w AM-US-Poland     06-23 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Bill on Trade Preferences</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Finance Committee approved
legislation Friday that could lead to U.S. trade preferences for
Poland.
   The committee without dissent voted to strike Poland from the
list of countries whose exports are not eligible for tariff-free
entry into the United States. That list includes communist
governments, developed countries and others, such as South Africa,
that are penalized for foreign-policy reasons.
   Enactment of the House-passed bill would let President Bush
determine whether some Polish exports should be eligible for
duty-free treatment. The administration asked expedited action on
the legislation so Bush could make the determination before visiting
Poland early next month.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, the Finance Committee chairman,
urged approval of the legislation, noting Poland's low per capita
income and the government's moves toward democracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
