<DOCNO> AP890623-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1518EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-HumanRights     06-23 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Human Rights,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>East-West Conference Closes with Criticism of Bulgaria, Romania</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An East-West conference on human rights ended Friday
with bitter attacks on Bulgaria and Romania for flouting human
rights accords during the month-long meeting in which they took part.
   Delegations from the 35 nations at Conference on the Human
Dimension generally applauded the results, but several Western
nations closed with final attacks on Bulgaria and Romania for
disregarding the accords.
   The Soviet Union, in its first public stance against an East bloc
ally, implicitly chastised Romania for building a barbed-wire fence
on its border with Hungary.
   ``The Helsinki Final Act makes no mention of a barbed wall,''
chief Soviet delegate Yuri Kashlev said at a news conference. ``If
we were the Romanians, we wouldn't have done it.''
   Hungarian authorities announced this week that Romania, already
under criticism for its treatment of dissidents and ethnic
minorities, has been building a barbed-wire fence on its border.
   While the delegates met, the rate of expulsions of ethnic Turks
living in Bulgaria mounted. An estimated 50,000 have been expelled
or invited to leave on short notice. The move follows resistance by
Bulgaria's ethnic Turkish population to an assimilation campaign
begun in 1984.
   Chief U.S. delegate Morris B. Abram said he was ``outraged'' at
the conduct of Bulgaria and Romania. ``We are, and every delegate
here should be, offended at the contempt that these countries have
shown for their neighbors,'' he said in a final address.
   French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas called on Bulgaria to end
the exodus, while chief Dutch delegate Max Van der Stoel called it a
``human tragedy'' and denounced the Romanian fence as ``a new iron
curtain in the heart of Europe.''
   The Paris conference is the first of three human rights meetings
being held by the Conference for Security and Cooperation in Europe
in the framework of the 1975 Helsinki accords.
   ``We have taken yet another step to consolidate the humanitarian
breakthrough started in Vienna, from confrontation toward
interaction,'' Kashlev told the assembly.
   ``The Iron Curtain ... is melting at the edges,'' Abram said,
noting that Hungary challenged Romania and none of the delegates
stood up in defense of Bulgaria. ``I think we're beginning to see a
thaw.''
   Abram praised changes in Hungary, Poland and the Soviet Union.
   Under a four-tiered mechanism worked out in Vienna, the member
nations can call other nations to account for human rights abuses.
   Romania also drew criticism for rejecting the mechanism.
   At a bilateral meeting Friday, the Soviet Union informed the
United States that ``a number'' of pending emigration cases had been
resolved, Abram announced. He called the Soviet action ``one of the
effects of this meeting.''
   But the Soviet Union ``clearly has not gone far enough,'' he told
delegates.
   The United States has set conditions for attending a 1991
conference in Moscow: that there be no ``backsliding'' on human
rights; that there be clear progress; and that free access to
protesters, dissidents and non-governmental organizations be
guaranteed.
   No final document of the conference's work was issued, and none
of the more than 30 proposals tabled was adopted. The proposals are
to be taken up at the next meeting in Copenhagen in 1990 and in
Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
