<DOCNO> AP890623-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SpendingBill     06-23 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending Bill,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Emergency Spending Bill Without Antidrug Extras</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Friday sent to President Bush a
$3.5 billion emergency spending bill for veterans, education,
refugee assistance and other programs requiring a cash infusion this
year.
   The fiscal 1989 supplemental appropriations bill, approved by the
Senate Thursday night, passed the House 318-6 only two days after
the chamber rejected a version that would have sparked a veto fight
with the president.
   President Bush was expected to sign the revised bill, which was
stripped of $821 million House Democrats had earmarked for anti-drug
programs. The White House contended federal agencies already had all
the money they could spend this year.
   The new version adds just $75 million for the anti-drug effort,
with that money coming from deferring spending on two other programs
until fiscal 1990.
   ``Either we ought to get in there and try to win the war on drugs
or we ought to get out of there,'' said Rep. Neal Smith, D-Iowa, who
promised to fight again for increased anti-drug spending in the
future.
   ``What we have established so far is that the administration
supports wide-ranging drug legislation but does not... support the
kind of resources that are necessary to make it effective,'' said
House Speaker Thomas S. Foley, D-Wash.
   Despite continuing arguments over the drug money and some other
items in the bill, the House overwhelmingly decided it could no
longer continue fighting and leave veterans facing health care
cutbacks over Congress' fourth of July recess.
   The largest single item in the bill is $1.2 billion for the
Department of Veterans Affairs, of which $340 million is for medical
care. Compensation and pensions, loans and other veterans programs
also would get more money.
   The bill also covers a mosaic of other federal programs lawmakers
said could not wait until the next fiscal year for more money.
   Those include nearly $900 million to the federal guaranteed
student loan program, $342 million to cover the cost of fighting
last year's widespread forest fires, and $423 million for foster
care and adoption.
   The food stamp program would be increased $225 million and aid to
the unemployed $90 million. An estimated 24,500 Soviet refugees
would be aided as a result of $100 million in new assistance
allocated for them and emigres from Eastern Europe, Africa and Asia.
   Congress' budget rules say the bill must contain money only for
``dire emergencies,'' but lawmakers took advantage of the must-pass
nature of the legislation to attach their favorite projects.
   Senate Appropriations Committee chairman Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va.,
in the compromise cut in half the $75 million he had inserted for
rebuilding a radiotelescope for scientists in his home state. He
agreed to wait until next year to provide the rest of the money.
   The balance of the $75 million allocated for the drug programs
would come from deferring some agriculture spending.
   The bill also would:
   _Add $90 million for benefits and training for the unemployed.
   _Provide $6.6 million to continue subsidies of air passenger
service to small communities which commercial companies would
otherwise drop from their schedules.
   _Require the installation of devices at airports which could
detect plastic explosives.
   _Earmark $125 million for United Nations peacekeeping activities.
   _Provide $1.5 million divided three ways for Puerto Rico's three
political parties for participation in determining the island's
future political status.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
