<FIRST>r a AM-LavaFlow     06-23 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lava Flow,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Funds To Replace Lava-Destroyed National Park Visitor Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAPANA, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Park Service has no plans
for a new visitor center to replace the facility which was destroyed
by a lava flow, a spokesman said Friday.
   ``There is no money for it,'' said Jon Erickson, spokesman for
Hawaii Volcanoes National Park. ``We are contemplating an
information kiosk at the Kamoamoa Campground.''
   Lava from Kilauea Volcano crept beneath the raised, wooden
structures of the Waha'ula Visitor Center Thursday afternoon. The
main building burst into flames after park rangers, who were aiming
fire hoses on the 2,200-degree molten lava, ran out of water.
   The three buildings were destroyed in less than an hour, ending a
two-day effort to save the facility.
   Park officials earlier had removed anything that was not nailed
down in the $600,000 visitor center. A nearby maintenance complex
and power generation facility, valued at $400,000, was wiped out
early Wednesday.
   More than 200 visitors and dozens of park personnel watched
helpessly as the 24-year-old complex was destroyed.
   The Waha'ula Heiau, an ancient Hawaiian temple estimated to be
more than 700 years old, and three park ranger homes on the grounds
of the visitor center were spared, Erickson said.
   The flow was moving westward Friday toward the campground, about
two miles away, Erickson. The only stucture there burned in an
unrelated fire several weeks ago, he said.
   The eruption began Jan. 3, 1983, at a vent in the volcano's east
rift zone, about seven miles from the visitor center.
   Lava has destroyed 68 homes in the surrounding area.
</TEXT>
