<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceSpinoffs     06-23 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Spinoffs,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>Astronaut Donates Outer Space Flag to Unusual Exhibit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flag from outer space joined super-absorbent
diapers, a Teflon frying pan and heated ski boots on Friday at an
exhibit of ``space spinoffs'' _ everyday products developed through
space research.
   Astronaut Jerry Ross took an official Museum of Science and
Industry flag into space on the 1988 Atlantis space shuttle mission,
and returned the flag to the museum as a memento for the exhibit.
   ``Even though we put a little over 1.8 million miles on that flag
in four days,'' it's still in good shape, Ross said as he presented
the royal blue and white nylon flag bearing the museum's name and
initials.
   Ross, 41, a native of nearby Crown Point, Ind., used to visit the
museum as a boy, and wanted to take on the Atlantis mission a
reminder of a place that helped spark his interest in space.
   ``It captured my imagination and helped foster the goals I had''
of becoming an astronaut, he told a small crowd gathered at the
South Side museum.
   The flag was stored in a vacuum-sealed container in a sub-floor
portion of the spacecraft during the December flight, Ross said. It
will be displayed permanently at the museum.
   While the flag doesn't exactly qualify as a ``space spinoff,'' it
easily upstaged the 100 such items on display for several little
boys whose eyes sparkled with delight as they watched Ross, wearing
his dark blue spacesuit, present the flag to James Kahn, the
museum's director.
   The real space spinoffs are consumer products and industrial
processes that were developed through three decades of space
research.
   More than 30,000 items, including Velcro and the Jarvik
artificial heart, have been developed from technology associated
with the nation's space program.
   One display case features a shiny potato chip bag made from a
material similar to that which formed the skin of a radio satellite
used in the 1960s.
   Another contains a pair of ski boots equipped with a
battery-operated heating element that can be turned on or off. The
boots were patterned after boot liners for lunar spacesuits.
   And there's a ceramic tennis racket and fishing reel developed
from early use of graphite composite materials during the 1973
Skylab missions.
   Ross also donated to the exhibit a photograph he took of Chicago
while traveling 5 miles a second about 270 miles above Earth.
   The museum shows up on the picture as a miniscule dot adjacent to
the Lake Michigan shoreline.
   The traveling exhibit, which originated in Fort Worth, Texas,
opened June 19 in Chicago. In September it will travel to science
museums in Boston, Philadelphia and other cities. It was designed
and produced by the Fort Worth Museum of Science and History.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
