<FIRST>r w AM-SenateArmsControl     06-23 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate Arms Control,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Groups of Senators Visits Geneva, Vienna to Observe Treaty Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven senators will visit Geneva and Vienna
next week to observe US-Soviet arms control negotiations on nuclear,
chemical and conventional weapons.
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., who is leading the delegation, said
Friday the delegation intends to remind Soviet negotiators in Geneva
and Vienna ``that the Senate will need to be confident that we can
prevent cheating in any successful treaty.''
   Lugar is co-chairman of the U.S. Senate Arms Control Observer
Group, which has monitored arms control negotiations since 1985. The
delegation was planning to leave as early as Saturday, depending on
when the Senate could finish its business.
   The delegation will discuss strategic nuclear weapons at the
Strategic Arms Reduction Talks and examine prospects for eliminating
chemical weapons at the Conference on Disarmament, both in Geneva.
They will then spend two days at the conventional weapons talks in
Vienna before returning to Washington on June 30.
   Members of the observer group are Lugar, and Sens. Claiborne
Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee;
Ted Stevens, R-Alaska; Jake Garn, R-Utah; Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.;
Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.; Paul S. Sarbanes, D-Md.; John Warner,
R-Va.; Carl Levin, D-Mich.; Don Nickles, R-Okla.; and Albert Gore
Jr., D-Tenn.
   The Senate earlier this week approved a resolution declaring
support for a verifiable and stabilizing strategic arms treaty and
urging President Bush to work closely with the Senate and U.S.
allies as the negotiations proceed.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, expressed hope
that the Bush administration ``will devote its energies to solving
such issues as whether to ban mobile missiles and sea-launched
nuclear cruise missiles and devising counting rules for missiles
carried on bombers.
   ``There is a clear need to forge a unified and creative approach
to these issues at the START negotiations,'' Mitchell said.
   Mitchell said the involvement of the Senate observer group in the
various arms control talks will enhance ``the ongoing process of
dialogue and consultation between the Senate and the executive
branch on arms control.''
</TEXT>
