<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1956EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Israel     06-23 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Israel,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Assures Support For Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush reassured senators Friday of the
United States' ``unwavering and unquestioned support'' of Israel
after questions were raised by a speech given by Secretary of State
James A. Baker III.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Bush
``reaffirmed the United States' commitment to Israel, speaking of
our unwaving and unquestioned support. He said Israel is a steadfast
ally and friend.''
   Moreover, Fitzwater reiterated that the United States views
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzkhak Shamir's proposal for elections in
the occupied territories as ``a very helpful proposal that we want
to pursue with all the parties in the region.''
   The senators asked for a meeting with the president after Baker
said last month that Israel should renounce ``the unrealistic vision
of a greater Israel,'' meaning the Jewish state should forswear
annexation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Baker also urged Israel to stop settlement activity in the
occupied lands and allow Palestinian schools to reopen. The speech
did not represent a change in U.S. policy but the tone of Baker's
remarks was viewed as a toughening of U.S. rhetoric.
   Shamir called Baker's speech ``useless.''
   After the meeting with Bush, Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, said
``there has been some misinterpretation'' of U.S. policy.
   ``But I don't think that the president could have been stronger
in indicating the recognition on the part of the United States that
Israel is our strongest ally in the Middle East and a reaffirmation
of continued concern and assistance and working together.''
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., said the meeting was intended ``to
make sure that we all understood where the president was with regard
to his view on the elections policy proposed by the Israeli
government.
   ``And he reinforced to us that he believed it was extremeley
useful and an extremely courageous move by the Shamir government and
that he was strongly supportive of that initiative,'' Biden said.
   Biden said Bushed wanted to dispel the notion that Baker's speech
was a change in policy.
   ``There is no change in policy on the part of the United
States,'' Biden said after the meeting. ``Israel is the first among
equals in the region and Israel, in fact, is going through a
difficult period that the president fully understands and fully
intends on continuing to support.''
</TEXT>
