<DOCNO> AP890623-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1624EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-23 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0571</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Hoss Attacks Militias; Israelis Attack Hezbollah; Aoun Urges Protests;
^By MOHAMMAD SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem leader Salim Hoss on Friday
attacked militia leaders suspected of illegal taxation and shady
deals, and accused them of kidnapping a government official.
   Also Friday, police said Israeli troops and allied militiamen
advanced into southeast Lebanon and attacked pro-Iranian guerrillas.
Hezbollah said two of its guerrillas were killed in the attack. But
Israel denied its troops left their self-designated security zone.
   Hoss' attack Friday, his strongest yet on the unruly militias,
came as Syrian and Christian gunners traded howitzer shells in
Beirut and Christian commander Gen. Michel Aoun urged Lebanese
around the world to stage protests to focus attention on the
country's problems.
   Hoss, Lebanon's acting prime minister and leader of the Moslem
Cabinet in the divided government, did not identify the militias he
believes responsible for Wednesday's abduction of Raja Bsat, in
charge of importing grain and sugar.
   A previously unknown group, calling itself Father of the Poor,
said it kidnapped Bsat in Syrian-policed west Beirut to protest a
bread shortage.
   Hoss blamed shortages on ``leaders who have become merchants'' _
apparently referring to leaders of various Moslem and leftist
militias accused of making big profits from shady deals.
   Private citizens, politicians who do not belong to militia
factions and moderate government leaders privately have complained.
They claim militia leaders bomb power lines and block fuel supplies
to power stations to force people to buy auxiliary generators
imported by them.
   Hoss, in a statement on local radio stations, accused such
militias of kidnapping Bsat to ``cover up for their crimes.''
   The prime minister, who does not have a political party or
militia, said he is ``aware of the population's plight,'' including
illegal taxation. He did not offer any solutions, however.
   Militias collect customs dues in illegal ports they run and levy
taxes in their areas of influence.
   A police spokesman said Syrian gunners fired about 20 shells
Friday to maintain their blockade of Christian ports north of Beirut.
   Christian gunners responded with 155mm howitzers, the spokesman
said. Witnesses said Christian shells damaged some cars. No one one
was reported injured.
   Current fighting broke out March 8, pitting Aoun's 20,000 troops
against three times as many Syrian and allied forces.
   By police count, 373 people have been killed and 1,457 wounded in
the confrontation that continues despite repeated Arab calls for a
cease-fire.
   Fighting started after Aoun blockaded illegal ports run by
Syrian-backed militias. Syrian and allied forces retaliated by
besieging Beirut's Christian enclave.
   Aoun on Friday protested ``the silence practiced by the world
regarding the killing of Lebanon (by Syria).''
   He called on ``the Lebanese and their friends in the world to
stage sit-ins near the U.S. and Soviet embassies all over the world
as of Monday.''
   He said he hopes to pressure Syria into accepting a cease-fire.
   Israeli army officials, meanwhile, denied their troops left their
self-designated security zone to attack guerrillas of Hezbollah, or
Party of God. They said their militia allies, the South Lebanon
Army, carried out the ``initiative actions.''
   But police and witnesses said a column of 300 troops protected by
armored personnel carriers and artillery barrage that advanced into
southeastern Lebanon included Israeli soldiers and were backed by
three Israeli helicopter gunships.
</TEXT>
