<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Espionage     06-23 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Espionage,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Soldier Apologizes For Espionage, Asks Forgiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FULDA, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American soldier broke down in
tears during his court-martial on espionage charges Friday and
pleaded for forgiveness for handing U.S. Army defense secrets to
communist East Germany.
   ``I'm sorry for what I've done,'' Spec. 4 Michael A. Peri sobbed
during his testimony. ``I just want forgiveness from the unit and
the Corps,'' he said.
   The defendant also said he received no money from the East
Germans.
   In testimony earlier Friday, Peri's commander said the
information Peri gave East Germany was crucial and concerned the
Army's electronic defense capabilities.
   Peri, 22, of Laguna Niguel, Calif., pleaded guilty Wednesday to
charges he gave defense secrets to East Germany during his
disappearance in February from his unit in Fulda.
   He worked as an electronic signal interceptor in the S-2
intelligence section of the 11th Armored Cavalry Regiment.
   Peri disappeared from his unit Feb. 20, crossing the border into
East Germany with a small computer and computer discs containing
classified information. He returned March 4 and was arrested.
   Peri said he returned ``because I couldn't handle leaving my
parents behind, my friends behind. Taking what I had coming was
better.''
   Peri's parents, Fred and Winnie Peri, sat in the back of the
courtroom, holding hands and sobbing.
   Under questioning from his attorney, Maj. William G. Stokes, Peri
cited job pressures and a lack of privacy in Army life as the
reasons for his actions.
   Peri said that during his stay in East Germany, communist
security officials in civilian clothes interrogated him at a house
north of East Berlin.
   Just before leaving East Germany, Peri said, he asked communist
officials to hand back the computer and discs, and they complied.
   U.S. military prosecutors say it appears the East Germans copied
the discs before giving them back.
   Asked by Stokes if he was given money by the East Germans for the
information, Peri replied: ``No, I was not, sir.''
   Peri's parents also testified, saying there had never been any
indication such a serious thing could happen to their son.
   ``He was a perfect child, he never gave us any problems,'' his
mother said.
   The defendant's father, a civil engineer, said, ``I'm proud to
call him my son.''
   Col. John N. Abrams, Peri's commander, testified the defendant
was a valuable part of the unit's intelligence section.
   Asked by chief prosecutor Maj. Michael D. Graham how he assessed
the damage done by Peri's actions, Abrams said: ``Those plans (taken
by Peri) show the wisdom and judgment of the field commander who is
directing the battle.''
   Abrams said one part of the classified plan Peri gave away
``shows how I will specifically distribute and organize electronic
warfare.''
   Also Friday, an Army psychiatrist described an examination
conducted on Peri after his arrest.
   ``He was so wrapped up with himself that he could not make
connection with others, either male or female,'' said Col. Robert G.
Schearer, chief of the psychiatry section of the 97th General
Hospital in Frankfurt.
   ``It is our belief that he is not getting messages from the real
world,'' Schearer testified. But he said he believes Peri knows
right from wrong.
   In addition to espionage, Peri is charged with being absent
without leave, wrongfully appropriating government property, and
entering a restricted zone without permission.
   He faces up to life imprisonment on the espionage charge.
   Closing statements were scheduled Saturday.
</TEXT>
