<HEAD>Israeli Troops and Allied Militia Attack Hezbollah; Kill At Least
Two</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RASHAYA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops and allied Lebanese
Christian militia advanced Friday on southeast Lebanon and attacked
pro-Iranian guerrillas, police said.
   Israeli military officials initially said they were not involved,
but an army spokeswoman said later that Israeli troops participated
in one of two attacks staged by their militia allies, the South
Lebanon Army.
   Four guerrillas were killed and one soldier was slightly wounded,
the spokeswoman said.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, said at least two of its guerrillas
were killed and two wounded.
   About 300 Israeli troops and Christian militiamen advanced in 35
armored personnel carriers amid a barrage of artillery fire while
three Israeli helicopter gunships hovered above, Lebanese police
said.
   Attackers fought their way into the villages of Kawkaba,
Dellafeh, Kfar Houna and Mydoun, three to four miles north of the
security zone in the Syrian-controlled western Bekaa valley, said a
police spokesman.
   They blew up several houses in searches for suspected Hezbollah
guerrillas, said the spokesman who cannot be named under standing
regulations.
   Villagers fled to towns to the north, he added.
   The Israeli army spokeswoman said Israel's ``action outside the
security zone was designed to foil the organization and activities
of the terrorists.''
   She said the guerrillas fired Katyusha rockets into the security
zone during the attack.
   Lebanese police said five howitzer shells from the attackers fell
near Syrian army positions 2 miles north of the villages, but the
Syrians did not retaliate.
   Israel carved out the security zone when it withdrew the bulk of
its invading army from south Lebanon in summer 1985, ending a
three-year occupation.
   It uses the six- to 10-mile-deep enclave as a buffer against
cross-border guerrilla attacks. Israeli troops and South Lebanon
Army militiamen patrol the zone.
