<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-SouthKorea     06-23 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-South Korea,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Reduce Troop In Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Democratic lawmakers introduced
legislation Friday withdrawing 10,000 U.S. troops from South Korea
by 1992, arguing that the Asian nation must assume a greater defense
burden.
   ``More than 35 years after the end of the Korean War, we still
maintain 43,000 troops in South Korea,'' said Sen. Dale Bumpers of
Arkansas. ``The rationale for this presence, which costs $2.6
billion a year, has grown weaker every year as the South Korean
economy has gotten stronger.''
   Bumpers and Sen. Bennett Johnston of Louisiana joined Lloyd
Bentsen of Texas and Kent Conrad of North Dakota in sponsoring the
bill that requires pulling out 10,000 Army personnel over three
years.
   About 21,000 troops and two Air Force wings of about 12,000
troops would remain.
   The measure also would require President Bush to report to
Congress by May 1990 on withdrawing all U.S. forces from South Korea.
   The United States should ``allow the South Koreans to more fully
shoulder the burden of defending themselves against their poorer,
smaller neighbor to the north,'' Bumpers said.
   On Thursday, a handful of Democratic lawmakers urged Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney to reject any agreement with South Korea that
would require the United States to maintain troops at current levels.
   Members cited a recent letter that South Korean Defense Minister
Lee Sang-Hoon sent to Cheney asking the United States to promise not
to withdraw American troops.
   At a hearing of the Senate Appropriations defense subcommittee,
Bumpers argued that South Korea's gross national product is seven
times that of North Korea, its population twice that of North Korea
and it only spends 5 percent of its GNP on defense.
   Cheney said the United States has no plans to reduce the U.S.
committment to Korea, but that cuts in troop levels are possible,
``just as there is a proposal to reduce our troop level in Europe.''
</TEXT>
