<FIRST>r w AM-MIARemains     06-23 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-MIA Remains,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five US Personnel Identified</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of five U.S. servicemen killed in
Vietnam have been identified and will be returned to the continental
United States next week, the Pentagon said Friday.
   Officials at Hickam Air Force Base in Hawaii identified the
remains of four servicemen reported missing in North Vietnam and one
reported missing in South Vietnam. The remains will be returned to
Travis Air Force Base in California on June 27, the Defense
Department said.
   The five identified were:
   _Air Force Col. Gerald W. Alley of Pocatello, Idaho, who was
reported missing in North Vietnam on Dec. 22, 1972. Alley was born
July 28, 1934.
   _Air Force Lt. Col. Robert A. Stubberfield, Stockton, Calif.,
reported missing in North Vietnam on May 6, 1965. Stubberfield was
born Nov. 30, 1929.
   _Navy Lt. Cmdr. Claude D. Wilson Jr., of Stockton, Calif.,
reported missing in North Vietnam on Dec. 14, 1966. Wilson was born
Aug. 14, 1935.
   _Air Force Capt. Joseph B. Copack, Jr., of Chicago, Ill.,
reported missing in North Vietnam on Dec. 22, 1972. Copack was born
June 4, 1947.
   _Marine Corps Sgt. Edwin R. Grissett, Jr., of San Juan, Texas,
reported missing in South Vietnam on Jan. 22, 1966. Grissett was
born Sept. 19, 1943.
   The remains of Grissett were among 25 repatriated by Vietnam in
January of this year, and the second to be identified from that
group. The four other remains were among 38 repatriated by Vietnam
on Dec. 15, 1988. Twenty-four of those remains have been identified.
</TEXT>
