<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2008EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Railroads     06-23 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Railroads,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hopper Car Shortage Predicted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A severe shortage of covered hopper cars to
carry grain will develop by the end of this century unless railroads
buy new ones, an Agriculture Department official said Friday.
   Martin ``Buzz'' Fitzpatrick Jr., administrator of the
department's Office of Transportation, said grain shippers
experienced severe car shortages a year ago and could run into them
again as early as 1991.
   ``In early 1988 there was a two- to six-week delay for shippers
in getting grain cars,'' he said. ``For some shippers, the delay was
as high as 14 weeks.''
   Fitzpatrick said a study at the time showed the cause was a
``shrinking and aging'' grain car fleet, combined with increased
demand, particularly for grain exports.
   A recent follow-up study shows that since 1982 virtually no new
cars have been added to the nations rail-car fleet. At the same
time, more cars are being lost each year as the result of accidents,
derailments and retirements because of age.
   ``The bottom line is that today's fleet of 98,600 cars used for
grain shipments will drop to 66,300 by they year 2001,'' Fitzpatrick
said. ``Our study shows the peak fleet requirement for that year to
be 96,000 cars _ resulting in a projected deficit of nearly 30,000
cars.''
   Currently, railroads own about 60 percent of the jumbo
covered-hopper grain cars, and shippers own the rest.
   ``If this ratio is to be maintained, the primary burden of adding
new rail cars for grain shipments lies with the railroads, because
82 percent of the cars over 20 years old are owned by the
railroads,'' he said.
   Fitzpatrick spoke at a luncheon for transportation writers
sponsored by the National Press Club.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
