<FIRST>u a PM-RoseInvestigation 2ndLd-Writethru a0668 06-23 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rose Investigation, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0668,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baseball Has Substantial Evidence Against Rose, Investigator Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts lead to move higher ruling set for noon Sunday.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE KAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge who was told that evidence shows Pete
Rose bet on his own team said today he would rule at noon Sunday on
a request by the Cincinnati Reds manager to delay a meeting with
baseball's commissioner.
   John M. Dowd outlined the evidence, saying his investigation
found telephone records, taped conversations, checks signed by Rose,
and ``betting sheets'' that have been verified as bearing Rose's
handwriting.
   The evidence is substantial, with nine witnesses giving
information about Rose betting on baseball games, including Reds
contests, Dowd said.
   While defending his report Thursday against attacks by Rose's
lawyers, Dowd said he's taken no enjoyment from presenting the case
against Rose, who has the most career hits.
   ``Do I like it? No,'' Dowd said. ``There isn't a day I haven't
felt enormous sadness about this matter.''
   Dowd unveiled the case against Rose during a hearing for Rose's
lawsuit against baseball Commissioner A. Bartlett Giamatti.
   Rose sued him earlier this week, asserting the commissioner is
biased and has already decided against him.
   The hearing Thursday was on Rose's request for a temporary
restraining order that would block his Monday meeting with Giamatti
in New York _ the final step before the commissioner decides the
case.
   If Giamatti determines Rose bet on Reds games _ which the manager
has steadfastly denied _ he could ban him from baseball for life.
   Dowd was questioned today by Rose's lawyers to complete the
hearing. Hamilton County Common Pleas Judge Norbert A. Nadel said he
would issue a ruling Sunday.
   Under pointed cross-examination by Robert G. Stachler, one of
Rose's lawyers, Dowd said repeatedly that Giamatti has not yet
decided Rose's fate.
   Dowd repeated today that corroborative evidence indicated Peters
was being truthful when he said Rose bet on Reds' games. But he
became testy when Stachler rephrased his questions several times in
an attempt to get Dowd to say Giamatti had made a determination in
the case when he sent the letter on behalf of bookmaker Ronald
Peters to a federal judge as part of the Peters' sentencing.
   On Thursday, baseball attorney Louis L. Hoynes Jr. told Nadel
that it's important to let the commissioner use his full authority
in deciding Rose's case.
   ``What's at stake here is the integrity of the game of
major-league baseball,'' Hoynes said.
   The evidence is contained in a 225-page report by Dowd and seven
volumes of exhibits that were wheeled into the courtroom Thursday.
Nadel has decided to keep the report confidential, against Hoynes'
wishes.
   ``There is evidence, substantial and heavily corroborated
evidence, that Mr. Rose bet large sums of money on major-league
baseball games and on games of the Cincinnati Reds,'' Hoynes said.
   Hoynes' and Dowd's statements were the first confirmation by the
commissioner's office that it had evidence Rose bet on baseball
games.
   Dowd explained that the report involves testimony and evidence
from more than 80 witnesses and is broken into segments. It opens
with a summary of the findings and is followed by a chronological
narrative of the investigation.
   Of the nine witnesses who supplied information that Rose bet on
baseball and Reds' games, only two have been in trouble with the
law, Dowd said, blunting contentions by Rose's lawyers that the
report was based on the testimony of criminals.
   Nine other witnesses told the investigators that Rose didn't bet
on baseball.
   Rose's lawyers are trying to get the judge to disqualify Giamatti
on grounds he's already decided that Rose is guilty, thus depriving
the manager of a fair hearing next week.
   ``The basic foundation of a fair hearing is missing,'' Stachler
told Nadel.
   Baseball's lawyers provided a memorandum Thursday from Giamatti,
who said he hasn't yet made up his mind on the case.
</TEXT>
