<FIRST>r w AM-Wheat-Soviets     06-23 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wheat-Soviets,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy More Grain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
96,000 metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized prices, the
Agriculture Department said Friday.
   Christopher E. Goldthwait, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said the wheat was sold
by Cargill Inc. and is scheduled for delivery by the end of the
month.
   The subsidy paid Cargill averaged $6.69 per ton, or about 18
cents per bushel. The total for the 96,000 tons _ about 3.5 million
bushels _ would be about $642,000.
   Moscow has bought more than 4.2 million tons of U.S. wheat for
1988-89 delivery at prices subsidized under the department's Export
Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Although the Soviets had virtually used up the previous EEP
allocation, a new deal for an additional 1.5 million tons of wheat
was announced May 2. Goldthwaite said Moscow has 814,200 tons
remaining under the program.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels
of wheat. According to the latest USDA five-day average, the price
of wheat has been $3.89 per bushel, meaning the latest sale could
have a farm value of around $13.6 million.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition
in selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
</TEXT>
