<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Greece     06-23 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hospitalized Papandreou Asked to Form New Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP DOPOULOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospitalized caretaker Premier Andreas
Papandreou was asked Friday to try to form a new government after
leftist parties refused to join the Conservatives in an alliance.
   Greece's political impasse developed after no party or alliance
gained a majority in Sunday's election for the 300-member Parliament.
   Constantine Mitsotakis' conservative New Demoracy won a plurality
and 145 seats. The incumbent Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist
Movement, or PASOK, got 125 seats, and the Coalition of the Left and
Progress wound up as the power broker with 28. An independent and
small party won the two other seats.
   President Christos Sartzetakis first asked Mitsitakis to form a
new government, but he could not reach an arrangment with the
communist coalition.
   Sartzetakis then turned to Papandreou, who governed Greece for
eight years, with the last few years embroiled in scandals.
   Papandreou, 70, was admitted to an Athens hospital Thursday night
with breathing difficulties.
   One opposition newspaper questioned Papandreou's motives and
suggested he was seeking to avoid a political showdown.
   ``Using his sickness as an excuse, Andreas is leaving. He
definitely lost the game. He is withdrawing from the political
scene,'' said the afternoon daily Apoyevmatini.
   Sartzetakis phoned Papandreou at his hospital room and reportedly
told him he had until Tuesday night to form a government.
   Papandreou issued a statement saying he would try to reach
agreement with Harilaos Florakis, leader of the Coalition of Left
and Progress.
   ``In the next few days I will take the initiative to meet
coalition general secretary Mr. Florakis. During our talks I will
have the chance to present PASOK's positions and commitments for a
viable government,'' said Papandreou.
   Because of the continued uncertainty it was announced Sartzetakis
would replace Papandreou at a two-day summit meeting of the European
Economic Community opening Monday in Madrid.
   Medical bulletins said Papandreous is capable of handling the
duties of the premier's office, but he underwent heart surgery last
September in London and his health is fragile.
   A bulletin issued Friday by a medical team at General State
hospital said Papandreou had pneumonia. It did not say how long he
might remain in the hospital.
   After his final meeting with the president, Mitsotakis told a
news conference he was saddened by the leftist coalition's rejection
of his proposal to form an interim government.
   Coalition members are the Moscow-line Greek Communist Party and
the Eurocommunist Greek Left Party.
   Mitsotakis, 71, had been given 72 hours to form a government.
   ``I offered two crucial ministries to the left ... the Justice
Ministry and the Interior Ministry, the key ministry if one wants to
hold elections,'' he said.
   He added the Communist coalition now could be blamed if people in
Papandreou's government who were responsible of wrongdoings escaped
prosecution.
   Members of Papandreou's administration have been accused of
corrupt deals in arms and banking. A $200-million embezzlement
scandal involving the Bank of Crete resulted in the dismissals or
resignations of eight ministers.
   Two former PASOK ministers have been charged with receiving
payoffs from the former owner of the Bank of Crete, George Koskotas,
now in custody in the United States awaiting a hearing on his
extradition to Greece.
   Mitsotakis said a new government must be formed quickly in light
of a new scandal involving the National Mortgage Bank of Greece in
the United States.
   ``Greece is being shamed internationally. Something must be done
in order to prosecute the responsible parties,'' he said.
   Representatives of the National Mortgage Bank were arrested in
four U.S. cities on Wednesdy and charged with laundering about $700
million for movement out of the country.
</TEXT>
