<FIRST>u a AM-TankerSpill 1stLd-Writethru a0646 06-23 0960</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0646,0984</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede VALDEZ, Alaska</HEAD>
<HEAD>Crippled Tanker Headed For San Diego</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 21 grafs to UPDATE with color, quotes and protest
boat; picks up 13th graf pvs, `As I...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAKED ISLAND, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tanker Exxon Valdez on Friday
began its long, slow journey to San Diego for $25 million in
renovations to repair the hull it shredded on a reef three months
ago, causing the nation's worst oil spill.
   Seas were calm, but fog and a low ceiling shrouded the 987-foot
vessel as it lifted anchor and began moving under tow by two
tugboats, Exxon spokesman Henry Beathard said.
   A lone fishing boat, dwarfed by the crippled hulk of the tanker,
circled in silent protest as the ship was pulled from its protected
anchorage at Outside Bay on Naked Island.
   Thick cable and chains stretching from two 7,000-horsepower
tugboats formed a yoke for the tanker as it crept toward
Hinchenbrook Entrance and the Gulf of Alaska.
   A third tug was attached to the tanker's stern and a salvage boat
trailed not far behind. The end of the rain-drenched procession was
brought up by two escort vessels loaded with 9,000 feet of
containment boom and each carrying an oil skimming vessel with 4,000
barrels capacity.
   Progress was slow initially, and the tanker moved only about two
miles in the first two hours ``because of some turns it had to make
to get out in the channel,'' Beathard said.
   Once adjustments are made, the speed is expected to increase to
about 5 mph, meaning it should take about 20 days to cover the 2,500
miles to the San Diego drydock where it was built nearly three years
ago.
   ``I must say we're not sorry to see it go,'' Gov. Steve Cowper
said at a news conference in Juneau.
   The Coast Guard said there was minimal danger of additional
pollution from the ship as it moves down the West Coast about 100
miles offshore.
   ``It's stable and clean,'' Exxon spokesman Joe Tucker said. ``I
understand there are some fish swimming in one of the tanks.''
   An Exxon Shipping Co. official expressed optimism that the vessel
would make it to San Diego for its nine months' of repairs.
   ``If anybody thought there was a concern, the ship wouldn't be
going,'' said shipping coordinator Paul Meyers. ``Exxon is very
confident based on calculations and two months of work that it's
going to be OK.
   ``There is roughly a 1 percent chance that the vessel would
encounter a wave that could cause it a problem,'' said Meyers, who
was aboard an Exxon-chartered boat ferrying reporters and
photographers to watch the Exxon Valdez depart.
   The Exxon Valdez had been en route to Long Beach, Calif., on
March 24 when it struck Bligh Reef, bleeding nearly 11 million
gallons of North Slope crude oil into then-pristine Prince William
Sound.
   The spill killed thousands of birds and sea mammals and spoiled
hundreds of miles of coastline. It also dealt a severe blow to
Alaska's $2 billion fishing industry, forcing officials to ban,
postpone or restrict fishing in polluted areas.
   Al Kapp, skipper of the salmon seiner Journeyman out of
California, posted a hand-letered sign on the side of his boat as he
ushered the Exxon Valdez away.
   ``Thanks a lot Exxon,'' the sign said.
   Kapp, speaking by radio to the media vessel, said fishing
closures in the sound this season have hurt him. ``It's disrupted my
life; it's disrupted our industry. It's not going to be a normal
season.''
   After the accident, authorities pumped the remaining oil from the
ship into other tankers, refloated it and towed the crippled vessel
to an anchorage off an oil-fouled beach on Naked Island, about 24
miles from Bligh Reef.
   For the past two months divers and specialists have worked to
stabilize the ship and patch it up for its journey south. Eight of
the ship's 13 cargo tanks were breached in the accident and it
suffered major damage to more than half of its bottom, Exxon
officials said.
   ``As I understand it, the Valdez will not be moving under its own
power,'' he said. ``But they (engines) are capable of being fired
up. The vessel will be towed with the on-board power plant available
as necessary.''
   Seven Exxon officers and four salvage experts were aboard for the
trip to San Diego, Tucker said. They will monitor air pressure in
the vessel's cargo tanks, conduct inspections and be ready to help
with the ship's engines.
   Repairing the tanker will require the replacement of 3,000 tons
of steel. That comprises about 10 percent of the vessel's structure,
said officials with National Steel and Shipbuilding Co., which is
repairing the ship it built.
   Exxon Shipping Co. president Frank Iarossi has said the ship will
be rebuilt to original specifications, which include a single hull.
   The Coast Guard on Wednesday approved Exxon's towing proposal and
issued the necessary permits allowing the move.
   The Coast Guard will be aboard to monitor the ship's movement as
it leaves Prince William Sound and again as it enters the approach
to San Diego, said Lt. Alan Carr, a Coast Guard spokesman.
   Exxon and the Alyeska Pipeline Service Co. have been criticized
for their slow handling of the spill during the first few days, when
winds were calm, seas were flat and before the oil spread.
   Today, oil with a sludge-like consistency can be found on the
Alaska Peninsula, some 700 miles from the reef.
   The tanker's former captain, Joseph Hazelwood, faces three felony
counts of criminal mischief and misdemeanors including negligent
discharge of pollutants and operating a vessel while drunk. The
42-year-old mariner has pleaded innocent to all charges. He is free
on $50,000 bail.
</TEXT>
