<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     06-23 0440</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Rocket Afghan Capital, Kill Four</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Islamic rebels fired 24 rockets into
Kabul in a 45-minute barrage early Friday, killing at least four
people, according to the capital's mayor and witnesses.
   It was the fiercest attack on the capital since June 3, when 12
rebel rockets killed five people.
   The mayor, Gen. Mohammad Hakim, told reporters the rockets fired
Friday probably were aimed at Kabul airport but hit civilian areas,
killing two men and a boy. A woman also was killed, residents
reported.
   Hakim said the mujahedeen (Islamic holy warriors) launched the
rockets from a base in Paghman hills, 12 miles north of Kabul. He
said government forces fired back BM-21 rockets, 122mm missiles with
a range of about nine miles.
   About 80 senior Afghan army officers, including a few generals,
were in Kabul at the time, diplomatic sources said.
   Like the residents, the sources spoke on condition of anonymity.
   They said the officers were summoned from the provinces to an
extraordinary meeting on Thursday of the Supreme Military Council.
They met as reports circulated that the Soviet-backed, Marxist
government was planning a decisive military strategy to fight the
guerrillas, who have been trying to overthrow the government for 11
years.
   The mujahedeen, based mainly in neighboring Pakistan, want to
establish an Islamic republic of Afghanistan.
   Soviet forces fought on the government side for nearly 10 years
but completed a withdrawal from Afghanistan on Feb. 15.
   Foreign ministers Eduard Shevardnadze of the Soviet Union and
Abdol Wakil of Afghanistan held talks in Moscow on Friday and asked
for new talks to settle the conflict in Afghanistan, the official
Soviet news agency Tass said.
   It said Wakil was on a brief stopover en route to The Hague for a
conference on peace and international law..
   The ministers agreed that the position of the Kabul government is
stronger than ever, Tass said.
   ``By successfully repelling desperate opposition attacks at
Jalalabad, Khost, Kandahar and elsewhere, the government ... has
enhanced its prestige both inside the country and in the
international arena, and has demonstrated the stability and
viability of central authorities,'' Tass said.
   Shevardnadze and Wakil said their countries were ready to open
new talks with Pakistan and the United States, both supporters of
the rebels, ``in any place and at any time'' to achieve peace in
Afghanistan, the dispatch said.
   A U.S. diplomat in Moscow, who spoke on a background basis and
demanded not to be identified, said last week that U.S.-Soviet talks
which will include Afghanistan will take place this summer during a
regular meeting on regional issues.
</TEXT>
