<DOCNO> AP890623-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CleanCoal     06-23 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Clean Coal,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Withdraws From Energy Department Coal Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Houston company is withdrawing from the
Energy Department's $2.5 billion program for developing cleaner ways
of burning coal, the department said Friday.
   M.W. Kellogg Co. notified the department June 1 that it wanted to
withdraw because it could not find a place to build a proposed
electric power plant that would attempt to demonstrate a technique
in which coal is changed to a gas. The gas would then be used to
power both a gas turbine and a steam turbine.
   Mary Jo Zacchero, a department spokesman, said the withdrawal was
accepted Friday.
   Kellogg is the first participant to withdraw from the project
since it began in 1986.
   Kellogg, with project partner Bechtel Development Co. of San
Francisco, had received about $900,000 in Energy Department money
since it signed an agreement on Jan. 22, 1988 to proceed with the
project. The eventual cost was to be $244 million.
   Zacchero said Kellogg was obligated to repay the $900,000 if it
eventually developed the technology and put it to commercial use. If
it does not, the money will not be repaid, she said.
   Zacchero said Kellogg wanted to build the plant in Johnstown,
Penn., but was unable to reach agreement with the local utility
company on a contract to purchase power from the proposed plant.
Alternative sites in New York and Virginia also were discarded.
   ``Nobody had anything bad to say about the technology; the
economics just aren't there yet,'' Ms. Zacchero said.
   The department also said it had decided to open negotiations on a
clean-coal proposal from the city of Tallahassee, Fla. The city has
proposed building an advanced clean-burning coal combustor. It would
be the first large-scale utility boiler of this type to burn
eastern, high sulfur bituminous coal.
   The Energy Department now has nine participants in its clean-coal
program and is negotiating terms of participation agreements with 20
others, including Tallahassee.
</TEXT>
