<DOCNO> AP890623-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2038EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     06-23 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Increases Bread Prices; Shortages, Protests Feared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has increased prices of
ordinary bread slightly and doubled the cost of better-quality
loaves in a move that could cause street protests.
   The new prices were decreed Thursday by a government committee
appointed to ease the burden of soaring living costs on poor
Sudanese.
   A five-ounce loaf of brown bread will cost 1.25 cents, up from
1.17 cents, and premium white bread went up from 2.12 cents a loaf
to 4.25 cents.
   Only well-to-do Sudanese can afford premium bread and they are in
a minority in this nation of 22 million that, according to the World
Bank, is among the poorest in the world.
   In raising prices, the committee failed to set production quotas
for the two kinds of bread. This raised fears that bakeries, intent
on profit, will concentrate on producing premium bread and aggravate
existing shortages.
   The government was forced to abandon announced price increases in
December, when raises in prices of sugar, cigarettes and other
commodities sparked street riots and clashes with police in which
four people were killed.
   The opposition National Islamic Front, which has a substantial
following, protested the new prices.
   Its newspaper Al-Raya published interviews Friday with angry
citizens and quoted one unidentified man as saying: ``We will not
allow the government to increase prices under the cover of
alleviating the burden of living costs. ... These increases will not
happen.''
   Commodity shortages are common in Sudan, saddled with a $13
billion foreign debt and six-year southern civil war that costs $1
million daily.
</TEXT>
