<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2042EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-PlayAwards     06-23 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Play Awards,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Theaters, Playwrights Awarded Grants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five theaters and playwrights have been awarded
private grants totaling $313,500 to develop and produce new plays in
the 1989-90 season, it was announced Friday.
   The Fund for New American Plays at the Kennedy Center awarded:
   _$90,000 to the Mark Taper Forum in Los Angeles and $10,000 to
playwright Arthur Kopit for ``Discovery of America,'' scheduled to
open in July 1990.
   _$90,000 to the Cleveland Play House in Cleveland, Ohio, and
$10,000 to playwright Reynolds Price for ``New Music,'' a trilogy
opening next fall.
   _$18,500 to Pacific Jewish Theater at Berkeley, Calif., and
$10,000 to playwright Shem Bitterman for ``Beijing Legends,''
scheduled to open in May 1990.
   _$25,000 to Organic Theater Company of Chicago and $10,000 to
playwright Jeffrey Sweet for ``American Enterprise,'' opening in
April or May 1990.
   _$40,000 to The People's Light and Theater Company at Malvern,
Pa., and $10,000 to playwright Ernie Joselovitz for ``The Devil And
All His Works,'' opening in June 1990.
   The 3-year-old non-profit fund, financed primarily by American
Express Co. and several private foundations, is a joint project of
the Kennedy Center, American Express and the President's Advisory
Committee on the Arts and Humanities, which promotes private
financing of cultural activities.
   ``Our intention is to allow non-profit theater companies to mount
full and sophisticated productions of promising new works,
productions that are worthy of the creative vision of America's best
playwrights,'' said Roger L. Stevens, the fund chairman and retired
chairman of the Kennedy Center.
   The fund already has awarded $507,000 for 14 plays. One of them,
Wendy Wasserstein's ``The Heidi Chronicles,'' won a Pulitzer Prize
this year and a Tony Award for best play. It originally was produced
at the Playwrights Horizons Theater in New York.
</TEXT>
