<FIRST>u i AM-China-Reax     06-23 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Reax,0631</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Parliament Demands Executions Stop; Firebombing at Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's parliament on Friday demanded that China stop
executing protesters and urged that development funds be cut off to
Beijing, but Japan's government says it is avoiding sanctions that
would isolate its neighbor.
   Italy put off a decision on development assistance to China to
show its protest of China's crackdown this month against a
pro-democracy movement.
   In Oslo, a firebomb destroyed a car at the Chinese Embassy on
Thursday but caused no injuries, Norwegian police said Friday.
   West Germany's top lawmaking body, the Bundestag, said it
``emphatically demands, along with the federal government, that the
Chinese government neither impose nor carry out any further death
sentences.''
   Chinese authorities this week executed 27 people charged with
taking part in the demonstrations.
   The Bundestag, in the statement forged by all major parties,
urged the West German government to suspend further capital
development assistance to China and urged the World Bank to cease
giving credits.
   The Chinese crackdown began on June 3-4 as government troops
stormed student protesters at Beijing's Tiananmen Square. Official
Chinese media say 200 police and protesters were killed, but Chinese
witnesses and foreign intelligence sources say as many as 3,000 died.
   In East Berlin, church sources said East German security police
on Thursday night temporarily detained 30 people who had tried to
deliver a protest message to the Chinese Embassy.
   East Germany's ruling Communist Party has defended China's
official version of the crackdown on activists.
   Japan is taking cautious steps despite charges at home that it
has not responded strongly enough, the Foreign Ministry in Tokyo
said Friday.
   Prime Minister Sousuke Uno, in a speech to business leaders, said
he worried about isolating China from the international community.
   Japan has halted high-level diplomatic contacts, put off talks on
a new five-year $5.6 billion loan package and publicly expressed
``sorrow and disappointment'' over the executions.
   Japanese opposition politicians, some business leaders and the
media have criticized the cautious stance of the government, which
provides 80 percent of China's foreign aid.
   Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti said Italy will not make any
decision regarding development aid to China before next week's
Common Market summit in Madrid ``as a sign of serious disagreement
with what is happening with executions and unacceptable repression.''
   Italian development aid to China is estimated to have been about
$1.5 billion over the past eight years. It wasn't immediately known
how much new aid was put on hold by Friday's action.
   In London, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher on Friday conferred
with a senior Hong Kong official and renewed promises to be flexible
about allowing the colony's residents to emigrate to Britain.
   But in her meeting with Dame Lydia Dunn, a member of Hong Kong's
Executive Council, Mrs. Thatcher resisted demands to give the 3.25
million Hong Kong Chinese who have a form of British passport the
right to settle in Britain.
   The colony is due to be handed over to China in 1997 under an
agreement which calls for the communist giant to preserve Hong
Kong's capitalist system for 50 years. The crackdown in China has
made many residents uneasy about the change.
   In Hong Kong, a public opinion poll published Friday indicated
only about 6 percent of the residents would move to Britain if
granted the right of residency, while two-thirds would remain in
Hong Kong.
   The poll by Survey Research Hong Kong, which had a margin of
error of 3 percent, also found that 71 percent of the respondents
believed Britain could bolster confidence in the future of Hong Kong
by offering the right of residency.
</TEXT>
