<SECOND>BC-AP Appointment,0145</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simon Named Chief of Omaha Bureau</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OMAHA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Simon, assistant chief of bureau for The
Associated Press in Los Angeles, has been named chief of bureau in
Omaha.
   The appointment was announced Friday by AP President Louis D.
Boccardi.
   Simon, 37, will direct AP's news and marketing operation in
Nebraska. He succeeds Dan Day, who recently was named bureau chief
in Seattle.
   Simon joined the AP in Los Angeles in 1979 and became news editor
in Dallas in 1985. He returned to Los Angeles as assistant bureau
chief the following year.
   Simon is a native of Yucaipa, Calif. He received an undergraduate
degree for California Polytechnic State University, San Luis Obispo,
and a master's from California State University, Northridge.
   Prior to joining the AP, Simon worked at the Ventura County
Star-Free Press in Ventura, Calif.
