<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     06-23 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Raid Cocaine Labs in Sustained Anti-drug Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police destroyed 10 drug laboratories
that were turning out 22,000 pounds of cocaine weekly, the national
police reported Friday.
   The raids this week were the latest in the most sustained
anti-drug campaign ever undertaken by Colombian police.
   It began five months ago after a new national police commander
was named, replacing a general who has been indicted in a
drug-trafficking case.
   A police communique said about 70 policemen using five
helicopters carried out the raids as part of Operation Rainbow. It
said there was a gun battle at one of the labs and two of the lab
guards were killed. It did not mention police casualties.
   The communique said the police destroyed 207,000 gallons of
ether, acetone and other chemicals used to process cocaine.
   A source who accompanied the police told The Associated Press
that some of the ether was in drums identified as latex that had
arrived from the United States through Guatemala. He said evidence
indicated the labs had been operating for about a year.
   He also said traces of cocaine were found on a trail, indicating
the lab workers fled with bags of cocaine as the police helicopters
approached.
   The communique said police seized grenades and automatic weapons
but gave no amount.
   Anti-drug units have seized 24,900 pounds of cocaine this year,
nearly as much as was seized by police in all of 1989, according to
national police statistics.
   Gen. Miguel Antonio Gomez Padilla was appointed national police
commander in February.
   He succeeded Gen. Jose Guillermo Medina Sanchez, who was fired by
President Virgilio Barco. An indictment against Medina Sanchez and a
colonel who worked for him accuse them of cocaine trafficking.
   The 10 labs destroyed this week all were within 10 miles of each
other in the northwestern state of Antioquia, according to the
source who went on the raids.
</TEXT>
