<FIRST>u w AM-Bush-CivilRights 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0790</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Civil Rights, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0727,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Praises Mississippi Slain as Heroes, but Leaves Supreme Court
Alone</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf pvs `Bush has ...' with 3 grafs to detail Bush
opposition to Ford proposal. Picks up 16th graf pvs `Another participant
...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush declared Friday that three young
civil rights workers killed 25 years ago by Ku Klux Klansmen were
``heroes,'' but he declined to promise their survivors he would work
to reverse the effects of recent Supreme Court rulings on civil
rights.
   Bush met at the White House with the family members of Michael
Schwerner and Andrew Goodman, both white New Yorkers, and James
Chaney, a black Mississippian, whose lives were the subject of a
fictionalized account in last year's Academy Award-winning movie
``Mississippi Burning.''
   The families were on a commemorative visit to the capital,
including an afternoon rally at the Capitol, to mark the 25th
anniversary of the disappearance of the three young men.
   In a statement released by spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, Bush
lauded the accomplishments of Chaney, Goodman and Schwerner, saying
they ``gave their lives in the struggle to guarantee one of
democracy's most basic civil rights _ the right to vote-for all
Americans.''
   ``We can erect no greater monument to their memory than to ensure
that the arrogance and bigotry that took their lives never again
exists in America,'' Bush added.
   But Rita Schwerner-Bender, who was married to Schwerner, told
reporters she was disappointed Bush did not commit himself when they
asked him to back bipartisan legislation ``to deal with the Supreme
Court cases that have so badly eroded civil rights in this country.''
   The court has drawn criticism from civil rights advocates for
recent rulings that have chipped away at affirmative action and make
it harder to win racial discrimination cases against employers.
   That criticism was renewed Friday at the rally.
   ``This present majority on the Supreme Court is far more
dangerous than Bull Connor with a fire hose,'' Benjamin Hooks,
executive director of the NAACP said. He was referring to the
Birmingham, Ala., sheriff's action against civil rights
demonstrators.
   But Bush was non-committal Friday on the legislation the family
members sought, telling them he is waiting for a Justice Department
to complete a review of the new Supreme Court rulings, said
Fitzwater.
   The visitors also brought up the problems such as housing,
education and medical needs as an extension of the civil rights
struggle. In the meeting characterized by Fitzwater as a classic
liberal vs. conservative discussion, Bush told them the federal
government could not solve everything without participation from
other sectors of society as well.
   ``I think he believes that a group of volunteers will solve the
problem. I don't,'' Mrs. Schwerner-Bender said, referring to Bush's
call for volunteerism.
   She added that she asked the president if he envisioned inviting
a homeless family to live in his Kennebunkport, Maine, home to help
solve the housing problem and he replied negatively.
   Bush also did not express a position on their request for support
of (universal and same-day) voter registration and elimination of
such practices as frequent purging of voter rolls.
   The Bush administration has not taken a postion on any
legislative proposals regarding reforming voter registration, except
to oppose one by Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky.
   That measure would allow voter registration by mail with driver's
license applications, said Deborah Burstion-Wade, deputy director of
public affairs for the Justice Department.
   The president has not voiced any personal sentiments on the
various proposals, the White House said.
   Another participant, Julian Chaney, sister of the slain activist,
said she was not disappointed to get no commitment because ``I did
not expect any commitment.''
   Carolyn Goodman, mother of Andrew Goodman, was less critical of
the president. She said ``he seemed in accord and we hope that he
follows through.'' But she and others said he gave them no specific
commitments.
   The families were on a bus caravan from Philadelphia, Miss.,
where the three were killed, to Washington and New York to
commemorate the June 21, 1964 disappearance of the men. They had
been conducting a black voter registration drive in Neshoba County.
   Their bullet-riddled bodies were found buried in an earthen dam
near Philadelphia, Miss., and the FBI found that the Ku Klux Klan
had killed them.
   Mississippi's attorney general, Mike Moore, is considering
reopening the case in which murder charges against 19 whites
initially were dropped in state court. The suspects, most of whom
are still alive, were tried in federal court. Seven were convicted
of violating civil rights law, another defendant pleaded guilty,
eight were acquitted and the cases against three others ended in
mistrials.
   The most time any spent in prison was six years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
