<FIRST>r a AM-TysonBiography     06-23 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tyson Biography,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Tyson Bio: Undefeated, Untied, Unstable</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents, especially in the 11th and 13th grafs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavyweight champion Mike Tyson is portrayed as a
sadistic thug in a new biography where he's quoted as saying his
best punch sent ex-wife Robin Givens bouncing off walls in a
friend's apartment.
   Tyson, who has battered Michael Spinks, Larry Holmes and
Bonecrusher Smith in posting a career 36-0 record, with 32
knockouts, told biographer and one-time friend Jose Torres that he
never hit an opponent as hard as he did Givens.
   ``She really offended me and I went BAM. She flew backwards,
hitting every ----- wall in the apartment,'' Tyson reportedly told
Torres. ``That was the best punch I've ever thrown in my entire
life.''
   The biography, ``Fire and Fear: The Inside Story of Mike Tyson,''
provides an insider's view of the volatile champion. Torres, a
former light-heavyweight champion, was a member of the Tyson camp
until they had a falling out last year.
   Tyson and Givens had a stormy one-year marriage, highlighted by
her nationally televised claim that Tyson often terrorized her.
Tyson in turned charged the couple only married on Feb. 12, 1988,
because Givens lied and said she was pregnant.
   Their divorce was finalized earlier this year.
   Givens' attorney, Raoul Felder, said the ``Head of the Class''
television series star would not comment on the unauthorized
biography.
   ``They had an amicable divorce. Part of the agreement was that
neither would make statements about the other. She will honor
that,'' said Felder. ``Robin is looking forward, not backward.''
   ``Tyson encouraged me to write the book,'' Torres said in an
interview, adding he has 12 hours of taped conversations with the
champion. ``He knew I would not do a story to hurt him. From two or
three excerpts, it appears like a hatchet job. It is not.''
   Excerpts of the book provided by its publisher, Warner Books,
Inc., indicated Givens was not the only woman Tyson abused.
   ``I like to hurt women when I make love to them. I like to hear
them scream with pain, to see them bleed,'' Tyson says in the book,
which will be excerpted in the August issue of Playboy magazine.
   Torres also gives a look at the killer instinct Tyson brings to
the ring for his fights.
   Talking about his 1986 first-round knockout of Jesse Ferguson,
Tyson says, ``I was trying to push his nose bone up into his
brains.''
   The book also portrays Givens as gold-digging and wild-haired
fight promoter Don King as anti-semitic.
   Torres writes of Givens screaming at one of Tyson's
representatives at Merrill Lynch: ``I want my money! Where is my
money?''
   Tyson's managers were Jim Jacobs and Bill Cayton. Jacobs has
died, and Cayton and Tyson are embroiled in a bitter court fight
over the champion's finances.
   King, who has taken over as Tyson's adviser, is quoted as telling
Torres, ``You know very well, Jose, that the Jews want to control
Tyson ... The Jacobses, the Caytons. You know it.''
   King and Tyson were meeting with their attorneys on Friday
afternoon and planned to release a statement later, King's office
said. Earlier, King told the Daily News both he and Tyson were
considering lawsuits against Torres.
   ``Jose Torres is a name-dropping fool. He's dragging Mike into
his own personal cesspool,'' King said. ``He's joining the club of
unauthorized biographers that have smeared people like Ronald and
Nancy Reagan for their own financial gain and ego gratification.''
</TEXT>
