<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2022EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     06-23 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANTANA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maintenance crews working ahead of schedule
gave motorists on a 21-mile stretch of the Florida Turnpike a
temporary head start on an increase in the speed limit.
   The state has approved increasing the speed limit from 55 mph to
65 mph on 330 miles of highways, and it becomes effective June 29.
But when crews were notified of the change, they got right on the
job and put up the new 65 mph signs. Unfortunately, it was 10 days
too early.
   The state requires that law enforcement agencies be given 14 days
notice of any change in speed limit. So the 65 mph signs started
coming down Thursday morning.
   The mix-up meant that drivers heading from Jupiter to Boca Raton
between Monday and Thursday traveled 65 mph with impunity, but could
have been pulled over for going 56 mph by noon Thursday.
   The Highway Patrol said it was unlikely drivers would be given
tickets because of the confusion.
   ``Let me put it to you this way,'' said Lt. Jim Howell, district
commander of the Florida Highway Patrol's turnpike substation.
``We're going to use the utmost in discretion.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PROSPER, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pines and tall grass obscure a 28-ton
``Welcome to Minnesota'' marker to the point where few people are
being welcomed by it, and officials want it moved.
   The hard part is finding someone who'll undertake the task for a
less than monumental fee.
   The marker in this southeastern Minnesota town is one of 20 such
monuments around the state. Minnesota transportation officials want
to move it one mile from where it was built in 1941.
   Tourism officials forwarded the idea of moving the weighty
monument to the Transportation Department, which decided to seek
bids for the project.
   After one round failed to attract any bidders, the agency
contacted 50 building movers directly and received one bid, which
``was about five times what we expected,'' said Craig Churchward,
project landscape architect for the department.
   The department already has designed the new signs that will hang
from 11 of the 20 monuments. They will read ``Welcome to Minnesota''
on one side, while the other will show pine trees and a canoeist and
the words ``Visit Again.''
   The monuments are unique because each was built with local stone
by federal Works Progress Administration laborers in the 1930s and
early 1940s. The monuments generally mark secondary entrances to the
state, Churchward said.
</TEXT>
