<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2050EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Solidarity     06-23 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Members of Parliament Hold First Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity's newly elected legislators held
an organizational meeting Friday but postponed a decision on the
issue of Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's expected bid to be president.
   During the six-hour meeting at Warsaw University the new senators
and deputies chose Bronislaw Geremek to be chairman of the Citizens
Parliamentary Club _ the organization of Solidarity legislators.
   Geremek, a close adviser to Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, was
elected to the Sejm, or Parliament.
   Solidarity candidates scored overwhelming victories in the June 4
election and June 18 runoff against Jaruzelski's communists.
   Senator-elect Andrzej Wielowieyski will be Geremek's deputy, said
Solidarity spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
   Solidarity candidates won 99 of the 100 seats in the newly
created Senate and all of the 161 seats open to the opposition in
the 460-member Sejm. The remaining Sejm seats were reserved for the
governing communists and their allies.
   The Senate and Sejm will meet together as the National Assembly
at the end of next week or in early July to elect Poland's first
president in 37 years.
   The communist party is expected to nominate Jaruzelski, its first
secretary. He imposed martial law in December 1981 and used it to
crush Solidarity, which had been chartered in the fall of 1980 as
the first free union movement in the Soviet bloc.
   Solidarity was legalized again under an agreement reached in
April by Solidarity and communist auhtorities that also provided for
the freest elections in Poland in more than four decades.
   Onyszkiewicz told a news conference a decision has not been made
on the presidency.
   ``But the debate indicates that we will not propose our own
candidate, and we will accept the formula that senators and members
of Parliament will vote according to the wishes of the electorate as
expressed during electoral meetings,'' he said.
   He did not elaborate, but apparently meant most Solidarity
legislators would abstain or vote against Jaruzelski's candidacy.
   He noted that the Polish United Workers Party, the official title
of the communist party, has not formally nominated Jaruzelski and
said there is no reason for the opposition to take an immediate
stand.
   The communists are expected to nominate Jaruzelski at a Central
Committee meeting Wednesday.
   Solidarity will have 260 members in the National Assembly and the
communist-led coalition 300, so the communists can elect Jaruzelski.
   He has proposed a ``grand coalition'' with Solidarity, but
Onyszkiewicz said, ``The debate rather indicates that we will not
accept the offer to form a government with the (communist)
coalition.''
   Solidarity leaders previously rejected Jaruzelski's offer but
said legislative cooperation is possible.
   A strong presidency is being restored to Poland for the first
time since 1952. The president will serve for six years, be
responsible for defense and foreign relations and have limited
powers to dissolve Parliament and declare states of emergency.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
