<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     06-23 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Seizes Coffee Growers' Land; Soldiers And Family Defect To
Costa Rica</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three dissident coffee growers said
Friday that authorities seized their farms after the leftist
government accused them of stirring up trouble and running up the
price of one of the country's main crops.
   Also Friday, two soldiers crashed their jeep through a barrier at
the Costa Rican border and asked for political asylum. One of them
brought his family hidden inside the vehicle, Costa Rican officials
said.
   Jaime Wheelock, Nicaragua's minister of agricultural development,
announced Wednesday that the government would be taking over
property belonging to coffee growers Nicolas Bolanos, Jaime Cuadra
and Arnoldo Aleman.
   Jimmy Bolanos, son of Nicolas, told The Associated Press at the
family's land that government officials notified him Friday of the
seizure after surrounding the farm Wednesday. He said that the
confiscation order does not affect the houses where his family lives.
   Arnoldo Aleman told the AP that as of Friday, he still had not
received official notification. ``Police arrived the day before
yesterday and decided that this farm was no longer mine yesterday,''
he said.
   Cuadra, 63, said in a telephone interview from Matagalpa, ``So
far no one has officially notified me of the expropriation, but my
two farms have been taken over militarily.'' He said the land had
belonged to his family for 23 years.
   The Bolanos and Cuadra properties are in Matagalpa province south
of Managua and the Cuadra land is outside Matagalpa, 80 miles north
of the capital.
   The move was viewed as a crackdown on government critics. The
three are members of the Superior Council of Private Enterprise, an
opposition business organization known as COSEP.
   Wheelock, in his declaration, accused the three of fostering
``chaos, disorder, price-gouging, contraband and speculation.'' He
declared the properties ``public utility and social interest'' but
did not mention compensation.
   Coffee growers on Sunday decided to pull out of the National
Coffee Commission. They called the regulatory and
development-oriented panel useless and saying it had ruined the
industry, which produces one of Nicaragua's main export items and is
a principal earner of foreign exchange.
   Ortega accused the growers of trying to sabotage an economic
austerity plan to reduce inflation, which last year topped 10,000
percent.
   As part of the plan, the Sandinista government this week ordered
a 100 percent devaluation of the currency, which sent prices of
consumer goods and services skyrocketing.
   Two brothers, both officers in the Sandinista army, crashed a
military jeep through a chain barrier Friday morning at Penas
Blancas in northwest Costa Rica and asked for political asylum,
Costa Rican officials said.
   Arturo Alfaro, spokesman for Costa Rica's Public Security
Ministry, identified them as Maj. Douglas Zunig Salazar and his
brother, Lt. Walter Zunig Salazar.
   There was no immediate comment by the Nicaraguan government.
   Col. Sergio Sergio Fernandez, Costa Rica's chief of security said
the the border has a metal chain to prevent unauthorized vehicles
from crossing, ``but the two escaping soldiers broke it while
crossing the border at full speed in a Soviet-made vehicle.''
   Fernandez said Douglas Zunig Salazar was accompanied by his wife
and two daughters, who were hidden in the vehicle apparently to
escape detection by Sandinista soldiers. He did not identify the
family members by name.
   Fernandez did not elaborate on the motives of the defecting
officers and said the asylum request will be investigated.
Authorities say Sandinista soldiers occasionally cross the border
into Costa Rica to defect.
</TEXT>
