<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines     06-23 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economic Planning Secretary Quits Over Policy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic Planning Secretary Solita
Monsod, one of the original members of President Corazon Aquino's
Cabinet, resigned citing differences over policy, it was announced
Friday.
   Mrs. Aquino accepted the resignation Friday ``with deep regret,''
said spokesman Adolfo Azcuna. Mrs. Monsod said she submitted her
resignation June 16 because she no longer ``enjoyed the full
confidence'' of the president.
   Mrs. Aquino named Mrs. Monsod's deputy, Filologo Pante, as acting
secretary and as acting director of the National Economic
Development Authority, a post she held concurrently.
   Mrs. Monsod, a U.S.-trained economics professor, was an outspoken
advocate of cutting back payments on the $28 billion foreign debt,
which Mrs. Aquino has pledged to repay.
   Mrs. Monsod, 48, also advocated reform in the country's
market-oriented economy.
   ``President Aquino cited the principal reason given by Secretary
Monsod for resigning as `honest but irreconcilable differences of
opinion on economic policy, negotiating strategy and the definition
of national interest,''' Azcuna said.
   The resignation, rumored for months, was announced after Mrs.
Monsod met Mrs. Aquino at the presidential palace. Afterward, Mrs.
Monsod refused to talk about the resignation or elaborate about her
differences.
   Critics of the decision to repay the foreign debt in full say
much of the arrears during the administration of President Ferdinand
Marcos came from loans siphoned off by Marcos and his associates.
   Mrs. Aquino took power after Marcos was ousted in February 1986
in a popular uprising sparked by an allegedly fraud-ridden
presidential election between the two.
   Mrs. Monsod graduated from the University of the Philippines and
received a master's degree in economics from the University of
Pennsylvania in 1962.
</TEXT>
