<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Kidnap 1stLd-Writethru a0675 06-23 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Kidnap, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0675,0795</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Kidnap Victim Freed; Captors Ask for Bush-Arafat Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos JTL1,JTL2; TLV1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with George recognizing kidnapper,
his quotes and quotes from letter. Pickup 10th pvs, `U.S. Embassy...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American relief worker kidnapped in the Gaza
Strip was released Friday along with a letter from his captors
urging President Bush to meet with Yasser Arafat and appealing for
greater understanding of the Palestinian problem.
   Chris George, co-director of the U.S.-based Save the Children
Federation, said he was treated well during his 30 hours in
captivity. George, 35, of Montclair, N.J., walked into the Marne
House hotel in Gaza City about 6 p.m. (11 a.m. EDT).
   ``They were nice to me,'' he said. ``I practiced my Arabic during
this period, I ate my food, fish.''
   Later, speaking to journalists outside his home in the West Bank
town of Ramallah, he said: ``When I asked my kidnappers, `Why me?'
they said, `Because you are a well-known and important American.'''
   He said he knew one of his kidnappers and identified him as
Mohammed Abu Nasr, who signed the letter George was asked to relay
to Bush.
   Nasr is believed to be a Palestinian released from an Israeli
jail in a 1985 prisoner swap. Palestinians in Gaza say he is not
known to be affiliated with any political faction.
   The affiliation of the abductors remained unknown. The Israeli
army blamed ``terrorists linked to the PLO.'' The Palestine
Liberation Organization denied involvement.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said a note in
Arabic attributed the incident to the Palestinian Popular Army,
about which the United States has no information.
   In the 13-page letter to Bush, the captors said they kidnapped
George to draw world attention, particularly American, to
Palestinians' plight.
   ``I appeal to you in my name and the name of my comrades and all
my comrades in jail and all Palestinians to do your best to deal
seriously and effectively with the Palestinian cause.
   ``Why don't you do your duty and receive the head of our state,
Mr. Yasser Arafat, in your office?'' the letter said.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Len Lefko said he was not aware of any
conditions for George's release.
   George was seized about 11:30 a.m. Thursday when he was lured
from his Gaza City office. He was freed at a U.N. hostel on Gaza
City beach, then taken to the Marne House by U.S. Embassy officials.
   Ann Nixon, co-director of Save the Children in the occupied
territories, said George immediately called his wife, Elizabeth
Webb. The couple have two daughters.
   ``He said he was very well treated and thought his family
probably suffered more than he did,'' Ms. Nixon said.
   George was the first foreigner kidnapped since Israel captured
the Gaza Strip and West Bank in the 1967 Middle East war.
   The territories have been torn by a Palestinian revolt against
Israeli rule for the past 18 months, and more than 520 Palestinians
have been killed.
   During the uprising, the PLO-backed underground has maintained a
policy exempting foreigners from attacks.
   In Tunis, PLO spokesman Ahmed Abdul-Rahman denounced the
abduction. He said earlier that the PLO was ``making the greatest
effort'' to secure George's release.
   Arab reports said at least two handwritten communiques from
George were passed to the Red Cross during his captivity, outlining
demands for the release of Palestinian prisoners.
   The reports said George wrote that he was taken by five men armed
with a machine gun and grenades. Israeli officials said he may have
known the man who lured him from his office.
   A Palestinian journalist shown one of George's letters said it
was written in English and addressed to U.S. Ambassador William
Brown and Bush.
   In the letter, George said his captors were demanding Israel
release seven senior Palestinian activists, including Sheikh Ahmed
Yassin, spiritual leader of the Hamas fundamentalist movement, and
three members of PLO factions.
   George is fluent in Arabic and has worked in the Middle East many
years. He was with the Peace Corps in Oman more than a decade ago
and worked in the Palestinian refugee camp of Ein Hilweh in Lebanon
with Save the Children before moving to Israel in January 1986.
   He left Lebanon after kidnappings by Moslem radicals made it
dangerous for Westerners.
   The kidnapping was condemned by several Palestinian organizations
in Israel, including leaders of six Palestinian workers' and women's
groups.
   ``The ugly crime is not linked to the Palestinian people,'' their
statement said. ``It is aimed at hurting our people, our intefadeh
(uprising) and our leadership, the PLO.''
</TEXT>
