<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru a0730 06-23 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0730,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grenade In Central Market Kills Two</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE deaths to two. Pickup 10th pvs,
`The attack came...' Minor editing to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grenade hurled into a crowded
downtown market Friday killed two people and wounded 56, police and
doctors reported.
   No group asserted responsibility for the attack, which police
said could have had only one objective: killing and maiming vendors
and shoppers, mostly women and children.
   One person was killed instantly and the other died at Rosales
Hospital, according to Dr. Manuel Angulo, chief of emergency
services at the hospital.
   He said five of the wounded were in critical condition.
   ``I heard a tremendous blast and came running,'' said onion
seller Rit Estela Alas, 32. ``People were lying on the ground,
clutching themselves and crying. One young boy's face was
destroyed.''
   Her stand is about 30 feet from where the grenade exploded at a
shack-like structure that sold cheap lunches and snacks of
cheese-filled tortillas.
   Half-eaten tortillas and pieces of pineapple and mango were
scattered among puddles of blood.
   Ms. Alas and market security guard Salvador Hernandez said they
helped rush about 20 people to the hospital.
   ``We stopped four or five pickups and loaded in the most
seriously wounded,'' said Hernandez, his jeans and T-shirt stained
with blood.
   Two police experts said the explosive device apparently was a
grenade thrown by hand and not fired by a launcher.
   The attack came after armed forces and leftist rebels reported a
surge in combat that left dozens of fighters killed or wounded.
   The Armed Forces Press Committee said government troops killed 23
insurgents and wounded 13 others in fighting Thursday and early
Friday, and that seven soldiers were killed and four wounded.
   Rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front announced
a regional offensive in northern Chalatenango province on the
clandestine radio. They said they killed or wounded 38 soldiers in
13 clashes Thursday and early Friday.
   The heaviest fighting appeared to be in and around La Palma, 50
miles north of San Salvador, where the rebels claimed to have killed
13 soldiers and the government claimed to have killed 14 insurgents.
Both sides routinely exaggerate enemy casualties and it usually is
impossible to confirm their figures.
   About 70,000 people, mostly civilians, have been slain in the
9-year civil war. President Alfredo Cristiani, who took office June
1, plans legislation giving police, armed forces and courts more
power against suspected subversives. Opposition political and union
organizations and human rights groups say the proposed laws are
Draconian.
   The new administration on Friday tied its proposed legislation to
Wednesday's shooting of American nun Mary MacKey, 72.
   ``This deed violates human rights and once again demonstrates
that the terrorist delinquency has reached a point that obliges the
government to adopt urgent laws to protect people's lives and
property,'' said a government communique.
   But it said, ``Preliminary investigations indicate common
criminals were responsible'' for the shooting at a vehicle in which
three nuns were traveling. The two other women were not injured.
   Sister MacKey was conscious Friday when she left on an ambulance
plane for Houston, Texas, according to the Rev. Ken Myers.
   Myers, her priest and director of the orphanage where she worked,
said the nun will lose the sight in her left eye.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
