<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2113EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Canada 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0509</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0685,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>One-Year Countdown Starts to Approval of Constitutional Accord</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 9th graf, `Quebec was...' to CORRECT year to 1987.</NOTE>
<NOTE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada on Friday began the one-year countdown to
the deadline for approval of a constitutional agreement that would
recognize Quebec as a ``distinct society.''
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney calls the Meech Lake accord
critical to national unity, but the proposal is off to a rocky start.
   Two of Canada's 10 provinces have yet to ratify the accord and
there have been threats to reconsider it elsewhere.
   ``One year from today, the Meech Lake constitutional accord
either lives or dies and some of the major players in the drama are
already betraying hints of the exasperation they feel,'' the Toronto
newspaper The Globe and Mail said Friday.
   Canada gained independence in 1867, but British jurisdiction over
the constitution did not formally end until April 17, 1982, when
Queen Elizabeth II proclaimed the new Constitution Act.
   But Quebec, where 80 percent of the population speaks French,
refused to join the nine other provinces in signing the national
constitution.
   Officials feared that Quebec's legal and social traditions,
established by the region's French founders and unique among the
provinces, would not be protected from tampering by the federal
government.
   Seven years later, in April 1987, Mulroney and the 10 provincial
premiers reached an agreement in principle at Meech Lake, Quebec,
that would recognize those distinctions and bring the province into
the constitutional fold.
   Quebec was the first province to ratify the accord, on June 22,
1987. At that time a three-year deadline for full ratification
began. The federal Parliament approved the accord last year, but
ratification is still needed by two provinces, New Brunswick and
Manitoba.
   A new provincial government in Newfoundland has been threatening
to rescind approval by a previous government.
   The Constitution applies to Quebec even though it has not signed
the document, but the refusal makes it more difficult to consider
national policy changes on issues such as how the Senate operates.
   Although the Meech Lake accord has become a major issue in
Canadian political circles and is a frequent topic for national news
media, the public remains largely indifferent.
   A Gallup poll published Thursday in the Toronto Star found that
30 percent of Canadians believe the Meech Lake accord is good for
the country, 31 percent believe it isn't good and 40 percent don't
know.
   In January, 31 percent said it was good, 18 percent said it
wasn't and 52 percent didn't know.
   Opponents charge that recognizing a distinct society within
Canada could weaken the national Charter of Rights, and they say the
provinces would be given too much power. English-speaking provinces,
especially those in Western Canada, traditionally have been wary of
Quebec.
   ``The people here generally are questioning the distinct society
provision,'' Premier William Vander Zalm of British Columbia told
the Canadian Press news agency Thursday in an indication his support
for the accord could be wavering as well. ``They're worried about
it, becoming afraid.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
