<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-23 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Storms Soak Texas and Atlantic Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms swept through southeast Texas on Friday, swelling
rivers and creeks, and other storms drenched the Atlantic Coast,
dumping 3 inches of rain on New Jersey and leaving parts of Maryland
and Delaware without electricity.
   Flash flood watches were posted overnight for southeast Texas,
which already has received heavy rains.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed along the Atlantic Coast
through Friday afternoon and were widely scattered from eastern
Tennessee to New England.
   In southwestern New Jersey, many roads across Cumberland County
were flooded. In Bridgeton, 3 inches of rain fell in just little
more than an hour.
   In northwest Delaware, thunderstorms soaked west central New
Castle County with 2{ inches of rain in one hour; Glasgow was hit
with 1} inches; and Newark received almost 1{ inches.
   More than 30,000 customers lost power in the Dover-Wilmington,
Del., area during the midday storm, utility officials said. More
than 5,000 were left without electricity on Maryland's Eastern Shore.
   Power was restored to about 95 percent of the customers in both
cities and in outlying areas.
   Also in Delaware, lightning struck 15 homes or buildings in
Wilmington, New Castle County, fire officials said. County officials
said they answered more than two dozen fire reports.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms also rumbled through Kansas and
northwestern Oklahoma. Conditions were cloudy from the Rockies to
the Atlantic Coast, and sunny skies prevailed west of the Rockies.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 48
degrees at Evanston, Wyo., to 101 degrees at Gila Bend and Phoenix,
Ariz.
   Saturday's forecast called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from the middle Atlantic Coast through the upper
Mississippi Valley to the northern Plateau region; showers and
thunderstorms in the northern Rockies and the northern high Plains
and in Florida to eastern Texas; scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the southern Atlantic Coast to eastern Oklahoma and central
Texas; and fair to partly sunny across the rest of the nation.
   Forecasters predicted high temperatures in the low 90s across
Florida and Georgia; above 90 degrees from southwest Texas to
southern and central California, above 100 degrees in southern
Arizona and southern California; in the 70s across New England;
below 80 degrees along the California coast, and from the upper
Mississippi Valley to the northern half of the Plateau region; and
in the 60s in the northern Rockies and the northern high Plains.
</TEXT>
