<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-Dissidents     06-23 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Dissidents,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Intellectual Leader Escapes to Hong Kong</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student activists helping dissidents escape from
China said Tuesday they had smuggled the leader of an outlawed
organization into this British colony.
   They said they expected other Chinese who were active in the
pro-democracy movement in communist China would be arriving in Hong
Kong.
   The students, speaking with the condition they not be identified,
said Yan Jiaqi and his wife, Gao Gao, came to Hong Kong Tuesday from
China and the couple planned to go to the United States by way of
Western Europe.
   They said Yan and his wife ``were in a safe place'' but would not
say where.
   One student said the couple did not come here by train or plane
but refused to give any details. ``There are many ways to leave
China,'' he said.
   Yan was a leader of the Beijing Independent Intellectuals
Association and faced certain arrest and possible death in China.
The organization was formed in May to support the campaign for more
democracy. It and other independent organizations were banned with
the imposition of martial law in Beijing on May 20.
   Yan and thousands of other dissidents went into hiding when
communist authorities sent troops into Beijing on June 3 to crush
the reform campaign and hundreds of people were killed.
   More than 1,600 have been arrested since the crackdown began and
27 people were executed this week.
   China has reinforced its border and customs units to catch
dissidents trying to flee and the government news media has reported
the arrests of people at airports and railroad stations.
   Hong Kong students who belong to the New York-based Committee for
the Advancement of Democracy in China helped Yan and his wife escape.
   Su Shaozhi, another prominent dissident, arrived in the United
States on Thursday and went to live with his brother in Chicago. He
refused to tell reporters how he got out of China.
   Su headed the Research Institute of Marxist Thought until 1987
when he was removed during the campaign against ``bourgeois
liberalization.'' He was not active in the pro-democracy movement
but signed an open letter this year calling for the release of
political prisoners.
   Yan participated in the protests.
   He drafted an essay criticizing senior leader Deng Xiaoping and
on the day before the military assaults began he was named president
of the symbolic Democracy University set up by students who occupied
Tiananmen Square.
</TEXT>
