<DOCNO> AP890623-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Anglicans-Pope     06-23 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anglicans-Pope,0528</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope and Canterbury Will Concentrate on What Unites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A joint declaration that could lead to closer
cooperation between Roman Catholics and Anglicans is expected when
Pope John Paul II and Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie meet in
Rome this fall, a Church of England official said Friday.
   The Rev. Christopher Hill said they will discuss the mission and
potential unity of their churches and not allow the vexed question
of women priests and bishops _ strongly opposed by the Vatican _ to
dominate their talks.
   Hill, Runcie's secretary for ecumenical affairs, briefed
journalists at Runcie's Lambeth Palace residence on the archbishop's
four-day visit to Rome, Sept. 29-Oct. 2.
   The pope leads about 650 million Catholics and the archbishop,
spiritual head of the state Church of England, leads the world's 70
million Anglicans.
   Hill said Runcie's party will include the archbishop of Nigeria,
Joseph Adetiloye.
   Adetiloye's presence ``makes the point visible that it is the
worldwide Anglican Communion'' at the talks, Hill added.
   Runcie's visit will be only the fourth to the Vatican by an
archbishop of Canterbury since the 16th-century Reformation, but
Runcie has had four meetings elsewhere with John Paul.
   When the visit was announced in March, Runcie's office said
church unity would top the agenda. It stressed that the visit was
planned before the election and consecration in February of the Rt.
Rev. Barbara Harris as the first Anglican woman bishop by the U.S.
Episcopalians' Boston diocese.
   Opponents of women priests and bishops said the consecration made
Catholic-Anglican unity impossible and threatened to split the
world's 27 self-governing Anglican churches.
   There are now women priests in six Anglican churches _ the U.S.
Episcopal Church, Canada, New Zealand, Uganda, Kenya and Brazil. The
other 21 churches, including the Church of England, still refuse to
admit women to the priesthood although some, including England, are
moving toward doing so.
   The pope wrote Runcie in December that ordaining women priests
and recognizing the right to proceed to women bishops, appeared to
preempt nearly 30 years of Catholic-Anglican dialogue on unity and
``effectively block the path'' to mutual recognition of each other's
clergy.
   Hill said the joint declaration from the Rome meeting is likely
to encourage closer coperation between Catholics and Anglicans in
spreading the Christian gospel, particularly in Africa where the two
churches are both seeing their greatest growth.
   Previous visits to the Vatican of archbishops of Canterbury were
by Geoffrey Fisher in 1960, meeting Pope John XXIII; Michael Ramsey,
to Pope Paul VI in 1966, and by Donald Coggan, also with Paul VI, in
1977.
   John Paul and Runcie are expected to worship together in the
church of St. Gregory the Great, which stands on the site of a
monastery where Pope Gregory I in 596 gave his blessing to Augustine
and 40 other monks setting out to convert England to Christianity.
   During the Reformation, King Henry VIII broke with Rome in 1534
to set up the English church when Pope Clement VII refused him a
divorce from Catherine of Aragon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
