<FIRST>r w AM-US-Sugar     06-23 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Sugar,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>US to Change Sugar Import System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uneasy members of Congress from sugar-producing
states said Friday they were waiting for proposals from the Bush
administration to change U.S. sugar import quotas, now labeled an
official violation of international trade agreements in a ruling
accepted by the administration.
   Sen. Spark Matsunaga, D-Hawaii, noted that U.S. Trade
Representative Carla A. Hills had maintained there should be no
``unilateral disarmament'' by the United States on sugar and added,
``I aim to hold her to this position.''
   In an earlier statement Thursday, Mrs. Hills said:
   ``We have an obligation under the General Agreement on Tariffs
and Trade to administer the program consistent with international
trade rules and we are confident we can do so. We have ample time to
consider our options and will be consulting closely with the
industry and the Congress.''
   The quotas, which vary from time to time, reduced U.S. imports of
sugar from $1.1 billion worth in 1982 to $400 million last year.
   The statements followed a meeting in Geneva on Thursday where the
U.S. representative joined delegates from 95 other governments in
the GATT Council to accept the report of an international panel that
ruled against the United States. The panel consisted of Poland,
Uruguay and Hong Kong. Under rules of the agreement, any single
member can block acceptance of a report.
   The United States has formally accused Japan, India and Brazil of
unfair trading practices, singling them out for early negotiations
to reduce barriers, and could have been embarrassed had it resisted
the panel report.
   Rep. Arlan Stangeland, R-Minn., who represents the country's
biggest sugar beet district, said Hills had not yet told members of
Congress what the U.S. options are.
   ``I think we should fight a little harder and defend the law,''
he said in an interview.
   He said Australia, which brought the original complaint before
the GATT Council, protects its sugar growers with a high tariff that
the United States cannot duplicate. The 12 governments of the
European Community subsidize their exports and the United States
could do that, he added.
   Thomas Hammer, president of the Sweetener Users Association, said
the U.S. government should increase its imports and lower its price
for sugar, which is twice the world price.
   ``The bitter irony is that American consumers are forced to pay
$3 billion a year to finance a program that violates international
trade laws,'' he said in a statement.
   The U.S. country-by-country quotas are set so that the government
does not have to lay out any money to buy up sugar surpluses from
domestic producers. The limitation on supply keeps prices high _
about 22 cents a pound to farmers currently compared with a world
price of about 11 cents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
