<DOCNO> AP890623-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2131EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-UtahFusion     06-23 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Utah Fusion,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Los Alamos Researchers Find Tritium In Duplication Of Utah Fusion
Experiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Alamos National Laboratory researchers
have discovered tritium, a byproduct of nuclear fusion, in
duplicating the University of Utah's purported breakthrough in
producing cold fusion.
   Edmund K. Storms, a staff member of the Department of Energy's
New Mexico lab, said he and another researcher, Carol Talcott, found
tritium in ``significant amounts,'' 4,000 counts per milliliter, in
two cells, the Deseret News reported Friday.
   On March 23, Utah chemist B. Stanley Pons and a British
colleague, Martin Fleischmann, announced they had sustained a
nuclear fusion reaction immersing rods of paladium inside platinum
coils in deuterium-rich heavy water.
   The two researchers said the experiment produced up to 100 times
the energy needed to produce the reaction.
   ``Tritium can only be produced through a fusion reaction,'' said
Storms, who began his experiments shortly after Pons and Fleischmann
made their announcement three months ago.
   ``We are trying now to understand really what environment must
exist in the electrodes to allow this to happen,'' Storms said.
   About a dozen labs around the world have reported finding tritium
in their fusion experiments, but Los Alamos is the first government
laboratory to do so.
   The news was met with jubilation by another fusion researcher.
   ``This result is of fantastic importance because tritium
absolutely proves fusion. If you get tritium, there is fusion
occurring,'' said John O. Bockris, a professor of chemistry at Texas
A&amp;M University.
   Three labs at Texas A&amp;M have duplicated major aspects of the
Pons-Fleischmann experiments, including small amounts of excess
heat. In one lab, researchers have seen the neutrons and large
amounts of tritium.
   ``This (Los Alamos) result, which confirms ours precisely, is of
immense, world-influencing importance,'' Bockris said. ``It's the
greatest news we have had since the 23rd of March.''
   Bockris is convinced that the Los Alamos' confirmation will
soothe the controversy that has raged in scientific circles since
the Pons-Fleischmann announcement. The experiment has been generally
derided by physicists, who contended Utah may have achieved an
unknown chemical reaction, but not fusion.
   A spokesman at Los Alamos also was cautious.
   ``The marvelous thing about science is the checks and balances
that now will enter the picture. This work must not only be
reproduced and confirmed, but also peer reviewed and published,''
said Jeff Schwartz.
   ``And quite frankly, we are unable to say if the research will
indeed withstand the scrutiny of the historic, traditional process.
But as an institution, our credibility demands that the process go
forth. We all agree on that,'' he added.
   Storms acknowledges that while he is ``optimistic,'' about his
findings, he hasn't solved the mysteries behind cold nuclear fusion.
   ``We are presently trying to reproduce that phenomenon, but so
far have been unsuccessful,'' Storms said. ``It (the tritium) gives
us some optimism, but until we are able to reproduce it we are
really not much further ahead.''
   Los Alamos is currently collaborating with Texas A&amp;M and Brigham
Young University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-BrilabConvictions     06-23 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brilab Convictions,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Brilab' Convictions Overturned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McHALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court Friday overturned the
racketeering convictions of Gov. Buddy Roemer's father and reputed
mobster Carlos Marcello.
   Charles E. Roemer II, commissioner of administration under former
Gov. Edwin Edwards, and Marcello were convicted in 1981 of
conspiracy to violate federal racketeering laws in a sting operation
aimed at bribing state officials.
   Roemer served 15 months of a three-year prison term. Marcello,
given a seven-year sentence and facing a 10-year term for trying to
bribe a federal judge in Los Angeles, remains in prison. Three
others were acquitted after an 18-week trial.
   A three-judge panel of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals,
which initially upheld the convictions in 1981, ruled unanimously
Friday that the convictions could no longer stand because the law
the men allegedly violated _ conspiracy to commit mail fraud _ later
was altered by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Roemer, 67, said from his home in Baton Rouge that the experience
was personally devastating.
   ``What did it cost me? Does that count the heart attack and the
health problems that were the result of that? Does it count what my
children and 17 grandchildren went through, and my wife? I was worth
$12 million or $15 million and I took bankruptcy.
   ``Four million dollars went in expense for the trial and
preparation and I lost 10 years of my life. What do you think it
cost me?''
   Roemer's son, Gov. Buddy Roemer, fought back tears when a
reporter told of the decision. ``I'm very happy,'' said the
governor, who stopped for a moment to regain his composure.
   ``I'm sorry. Let me try again ... I'm real pleased and happy. He
(the elder Roemer) has had a real hard time, in many ways unfairly.
He took the bad times like a man.''
   Marcello, 79 and in poor health, is at the Federal Correctional
Institution in Rochester, Minn., where Assistant Warden John Chreno
said Marcello ``has been under constant physicians' care.''
   In the sting, undercover FBI agents posed as crooked insurance
executives. They were convicted of taking part in a scheme to win a
multimillion-dollar state group insurance contract through bribery.
   The government said Marcello and Roemer believed they would split
a commission of $87,000 a month.
   The prosecution alleged they conspired to deprive citizens of
honest government. This latest appeal was based on a Supreme Court
opinion that the mail fraud law is designed to protect money or
property rights _ not intangible rights such as the right to good
government.
   ``The record in this case inexorably leads to one conclusion: the
mail and wire fraud charges were tried as intangible right
offenses,'' the 5th Circuit said.
   ``The indictment charged a scheme to defraud citizens of honest
government, the prosecutor described it as such, and the judge
instructed the jury that it could convict upon finding the existence
of a scheme as charged in the indictment.''
   The FBI had code-named the operation ``Brilab,'' short for
bribery-labor.
   ``I'm sure to Mr. Marcello it's a very significant event but to
the government it's purely academic at this stage,'' said U.S.
Attorney John Volz, who prosecuted both men. ``Both defendants have
served their sentences from that case.''
   Edwards, who dropped his bid for a fourth term after finishing
second to Buddy Roemer in the state's open primary _ said he was
glad for Roemer but expressed outrage at Volz's remark.
   ``I'm very pleased, because there's no doubt in my mind that this
was a political prosecution to begin with,'' said Edwards, reached
at his home in Baton Rouge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2209EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FlagBurning 2ndLd-Writethru a0749 06-23 0427</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Burning, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0749,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Bill Aimed At Circumventing Flag Decision</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 4-5 bgng: ``Biden's measure,'' to detail provisions
of the amendment and point out lack of explanation.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Friday passed legislation aimed
at making desecration of the flag unlawful.
   The aim of the amendment, approved by voice vote without dissent,
is to circumvent the effect of a Supreme Court decision earlier in
the week which held that destruction of the flag is protected by the
First Amendment guarantee of free speech.
   ``I'm confident it's constitutional,'' Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del.,
chairman of the judiciary panel and a leading congressional liberal,
told his colleagues. Biden's measure was tacked onto an unrelated
child care bill.
   Biden's measure, which adds a new section to federal law dealing
with defacing U.S. property, makes it a misdemeanor to burn, trample
on, throw down or otherwise deface the flag.
   Biden did not explain how the provision could be constitional
while similar provisions of existing federal law, under the Court's
decision Wednesday, would not be. There was no one in his office
after the Senate session, and no answer at Biden's home.
   Earlier, House Speaker Thomas S. Foley said that while lawmakers
are outraged by the high court decision of Wednesday, changing the
Constitution should be viewed with caution.
   Foley, D-Wash., said that ``nobody in the House supports flag
burning. Everyone condemns it and believes that there is ... no
justification for the burning and disrespect to the American flag.''
   But he said he would ``be extraordinarily slow to amend the First
Amendment to the Constitution'' which is ``at the heart of our
constitutional liberties and freedom.''
   About 10 lawmakers have already introduced constitutional
amendments in the wake of the decision, Foley said. But any such
amendment should be the subject of lengthy hearings and discussion
in Congress, he said.
   It was possible the House would consider next week a resolution
similar to the one passed by the Senate this week expressing
opposition to the view of the court.
   Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, a senior Republican on the House
Judiciary Committee, said he was exploring ways of getting around
the decision without a constitutional amendment, possibly by taking
away from the Supreme Court jurisdiction over lawsuits on flag
desecration.
   ``I think the mood of the House is to do something effective and
not just pass resolutions condemning the burning of the flag,'' he
said. A new law would be simpler than a constitutional amendment, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
