<FIRST>u w AM-NuclearHealth 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0362</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Health, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0726,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Department Agrees to Release Records of Nuclear Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Adds 5 grafs more detail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy will allow outside
researchers to examine health records of workers who have been
exposed to radiation at government nuclear projects, the agency
announced Friday.
   The records, which date to the Manhattan Project atomic bomb
experiments of the early 1940s, are considered the largest body of
information on the effects of radiation exposure.
   Records on some 600,000 workers from about 50 government
facilities will be opened for scientific scrutiny.
   The National Academy of Sciences has been given a $297,000 grant
to determine how to make the data public without violating privacy
laws or agreements with state health agencies.
   Spokesman Jeff Sherwood said the agency hoped the records would
be open by fall.
   Energy Secretary James Watkins said in a letter to Sen. John
Glenn, D-Ohio, that he had ordered the department to establish a
national repository for ``all epidemiologically relevant information
on DOE workers.''
   Glenn was one of several lawmakers who had pressed for release of
the data.
   Under questioning at a February House hearing, Troy Wade,
assistant secretary for defense programs, said he didn't know any
reason why the information couldn't be released.
   In addition to information on facilities in his own state, Glenn
has asked the Energy Department for detailed information on the
exposure of workers at the Hanford nuclear reservation in Washington
state, and in his letter Watkins said the department was researching
the answers and letting it be reviewed by department lawyers
``because of ... ongoing litigation'' there.
   The committee Glenn heads also has asked the department to
explain why its epidemiological studies of workers exposed to
radiation did not include workers at the Nevada Test Site and the
Idaho National Engineering Laboratory.
   Some have argued that workers at those sites may have been
exposed to more radiation than any others in the government's
nuclear weapons complex.
   There were above-ground nuclear tests at Nevada until the early
1960s, and Energy Department documents have shown that between 1957
and 1963 there were intentional atmospheric releases of radioactive
gases from the Idaho lab.
</TEXT>
