<FIRST>r i AM-Netherlands-Kidnap     06-23 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Netherlands-Kidnap,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kidnapped Army Officer Apparently Killed by Police Bullet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARNHEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A kidnapped army colonel killed during
a shootout between police and the abductor apparently was hit by a
police bullet, a spokesman reported Friday.
   Dutch army Col. Karel van de Kieft, 56, was slain Thursday when
police intercepted his car about two hours after he had been
kidnapped by Stefan Kroger, a 33-year-old West German from Hanover
who had fled from a German prison.
   The gunfight occurred after police blocked the car in a service
station on the Arnhem-Utrecht freeway.
   Van de Kieft was killed by a shot in the head but Kroger was not
injured.
   ``According to preliminary findings, he (van de Kieft) was
probably hit by a bullet fired by police,'' said police spokesman
Bert Albers. He reported investigators have not determined the
motive for the abduction and said Kroger is still being questioned.
   At one point during a standoff between Kroger and the police,
Kroger demanded a ransom of one million guilders ($454,000) and 100
grams, or about 3{ ounces, of heroin.
   Television tapes showed policemen with UZI submachineguns
charging toward van de Kieft's Ford Escort from a distance of about
45 feet. The colonel could be seen in the driver's seat slumped
behind the wheel.
   Police said Kroger had a handgun but Albers would not say what
type or caliber.
   Albers said the number of shots fired by police and by Kroger is
still unclear.
   A preliminary autopsy report concluded the colonel ``was killed
by a police bullet, but it has not yet been firmly established,''
the spokesman added.
   He said Van de Kieft was on his way to work when Kroger forced
his way at gunpoint into the colonel's car about 12 miles north of
Arnhem.
   West German authorities reported Kroger had been jailed in
Braunschweig and failed to return from a one-day prison furlough,
according to Albers.
   He said West German officials are preparing an extradition
request for Kroger in connection with an armed robbery in
Braunschweig in which a 70-year-old man was seriously injured.
   Albers said if Kroger is convicted of a crime in the Netherlands
he would have to serve the sentence here before he would be
extradited to West Germany.
</TEXT>
