<DOCNO> AP890623-0199 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 2046EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DigestBriefs 1stadd a9910 06-23 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Digest Briefs, 1st add, a9910,0626</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court on Friday refused to shut
down the billion-dollar dial-a-porn industry, thwarting an attempt
by Congress to shield children from sexually oriented telephone
messages.
   The court said in its unanimous decision that Congress went too
far last year when it passed a law banning all sexually oriented
phone message services.
   Only obscene messages _ and not messages that merely are
``indecent'' _ may be outlawed, the court said. It said a blanket
ban would violate free-speech rights.
   ``The case before us today does not require us to decide what is
obscene or what is indecent,'' said Justice Byron R. White, writing
for the court.
   A phone conversation, like an explicit movie or centerfold in an
adult magazine, may or may not be obscene, a designation that must
be decided by local juries on a case-by-case basis.
   Material deemed to be indecent rather than obscene is protected
under the Constitution.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KINSHASA, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi left
for home on Friday to implement a cease-fire that will end 14 years
of civil war with Angola's Marxist government.
   The leader of the U.S.-backed rebels and Angolan President
Eduardo dos Santos signed the truce accord and sealed it with a
handshake late Thursday at a special African summit to promote peace
in Angola.
   ``I was not born to make war at all cost,'' Savimbi said before
leaving to carry word of the cease-fire to his forces. ``Even if I
have made war until now for precise reasons, and even if these
reasons cease to exist, I will always remain, in my skin, a citizen
of Angola.''
   Shooting was to stop at midnight Friday (7 p.m. EDT). Savimbi
told the Zairean news agency he is prepared to work ``without
preconditions'' with dos Santos' government.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This school district boasts it has slashed
its dropout rate in half by offering students alternatives such as
day care centers, vocational training for the disabled and night
classes for working teens.
   The key, said Quincy school officials, is giving potential
dropouts offers they can hardly refuse and lavishing attention on
students at risk of dropping out.
   ``The secret is, a kid can't drop out without going through a
long program of help-providers,'' said Schools Superintendent Robert
Ricci on Friday.
   ``It's nothing that hasn't been done. But most districts aren't
that flexible,'' Ricci said. ``There's a blueprint here for urban
districts.''
   Ricci calculated the dropout rate by following a group of
students from ninth grade through the day they should graduate. The
traditional method is to compare senior classes from year to year.
By tracking incoming ninth-graders, the schools can more accurately
assess whether the programs are working, experts said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than a third of the Dallas Cowboy Cheerleaders
walked off the squad to protest skimpier uniforms, saying they also
were asked to act as hostesses at parties, fraternize with the team
and appear in beer commercials.
   Meanwhile, beauty contestants in the Miss Texas USA 1990
competition this weekend will walk barefoot down the ramp in their
swimsuits and shed the traditional spike high heels in an effort to
look more wholesome, organizers said.
   The Cowboys' new owner Jerry Jones, calling the 37 cheerleaders
``the pick of the litter,'' said Friday he's hasn't changed any
rules or policies. He would not comment when asked if there had been
a misunderstanding.
   ``Thos girls in the past and these girls now are wonderful
women,'' Jones said at a news conference after cheerleader Director
Debbie Bond resigned, taking all 14 veteran cheerleaders with her.
</TEXT>
