<FIRST>a i PM-London-LateNight Adv27   06-23 0765</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-London-Late Night, Adv 27,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs June 27 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Late-Night Dining Spots Hard to Find in London</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You've just been to the theater and want a
leisurely, late-night meal in Europe's largest city and a world
cultural capital. Easy, right? In London, not necessarily.
   ``The other night after the show, we were trying to find a place
to eat, and there was no place to go,'' said Ann Crumb, the American
star of Andrew Lloyd Webber's new smash musical, ``Aspects of
Love,'' at the Prince of Wales Theater.
   The places that serve up to midnight or later are few. They are
led by the American-owned Orso and Joe Allen in Covent Garden, both
frequented by theater people, and an array of Chinese restaurants in
Soho that stay open until the wee hours.
   Elsewhere, the choices are slim. Up to 11 p.m., London is abuzz
with activity. Then, suddenly, it becomes a graveyard of upended
restaurant chairs, littered sidewalks and lost souls torn between
that elusive last drink and the last bus home.
   Only Soho and Covent Garden are alive past midnight.
   ``It's totally antiquated and stupid,'' said Drew Smith of the
Consumers' Association and a food writer and critic for The Guardian
newspaper.
   `I think it's very unfortunate that in a major international city
you don't have the late-night restaurant service that should go with
it.''
   But London's attitude toward late-night dining is symptomatic of
life as a whole. The English generally call it quits early. Many bus
routes are suspended after rush hour, the subway stops soon after
midnight, the law requires pubs to serve last drinks at 10:50 p.m.
BBC-TV goes off the air around midnight, although the two commercial
networks operate all night.
   ``So much of it has to do with the style of living here,'' said
Richard Polo, the American restaurateur who manages Joe Allen and
Orso. ``You can go to Paris at 1 a.m. and see restaurants full of
people; London's not like that.''
   Polo came to London in 1977 to open Joe Allen here following its
success in New York. Its more upmarket sister establishment, Orso,
opened in 1985, and Polo says both do about one-quarter of their
daily business after the curtain falls. Last orders at Orso are at
12 Midnight; at Joe Allen, 12:45 a.m.
   Theater curtains rise in London at 7:30 and 8 p.m. and fall
between 10 and 11 p.m.
   Englishman Peter Ward, who manages the central London restaurants
Inigo Jones and the newly opened Burt's, says the problem is in the
national temperament.
   ``We're not an eating-out society,'' he said. ``Continentals and
New Yorkers together are much more serious eaters than British and
the Londoners.''
   ``The moment it's curtain down, people are on their way back to
Croydon or Brighton,'' Ward added. ``There's less of the joy in the
social gathering of eating. Here, it's a chore and a necessity.''
   Geography and the law play a part. Where New York's Manhattan and
Paris are relatively compact, London's urban sprawl makes it
impractical to walk home from a post-theater meal. Those who miss
the last subway have no way home except in relatively expensive
taxis or irregular night buses.
   Places wanting to serve late face a morass of legal red tape. The
Extended Hours Order covers restaurants open until 1 a.m. and the
Special Hours Certificate allows for openings up to 2 a.m. or, in
central London, 3 a.m., provided there is music and dancing.
   David Lavendar, a London lawyer who specializes in licensing
issues, said the law allowed ``a wholly artificial restriction on
hours.''
   ``In France, you must close half an hour out of every 24, and
that's for cleaning,'' said Lavendar. ``Here, a publican can be
prosecuted for leaving a drink on the table at 11:21 p.m.''
   Jeremy Rounds, food critic of The Independent newspaper, also
deplores this state of affairs, but believes London isn't unique.
   ``I'm always surprised in America by how early America closes
down,'' he said. ``Try getting a meal late in Atlanta.''
   ``The very best places at an international level are the sorts
that in other capitals wouldn't be open late either,'' he added.
   ``Dewy-eyed young men have been telling me for years there's
nowhere to eat late in London,'' said Peter Boizot, proprietor of
the Pizza Express chain and chairman of the Soho Restaurateurs'
Association, which has more than 50 member eateries.
   ``But in my experience,'' he said, ``the ones that have opened
are not that well-frequented.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs June 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
