<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1457EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Bed-Stuy Adv26   06-23 1005</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Bed-Stuy, Adv 26,1033</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, June 26 and Thereafterp</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-AP Arts: Lee</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bedford-Stuyvesant: A Movie Grows in Brooklyn</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A grim abandoned building now stands on
Stuyvesant Avenue, the defining boulevard of Brooklyn's historic
Bedford-Stuyvesant, where Sal's Famous Pizzeria squeezed racial
tensions to a tragic head in Spike Lee's explosive new movie, ``Do
the Right Thing.''
   The Korean grocery that faced Sal's across the street is also
gone, removed from the lot of Constance Newkirk, one of the
neighborhood's senior residents. She stood before her home on the
corner of Quincy Street and Stuyvesant Avenue one recent sunny day,
reminiscing about the brief upheaval last May when the celebrated
filmmaker and his crew invaded the area with its movie magic.
   ``I got to know quite a few of them,'' Newkirk said. ``I wanted
to know what was going on. I met Spike and the fellows that were
building. They had to take measurements for my house, corners,
windows and everything.
   ``They built the pizza parlor across the street. They had all the
equipment, anything you would need to make pizza. They came in big
trucks, brand new ovens, ice machines, soda fountains, tiffany
lights, pictures, the whole works.''
   Lee, whose award-winning thesis work for New York University Film
School also took place in Bedford-Stuyvesant, chose one of the
nation's oldest black communities as the location for ``Do the Right
Thing.''
   The action takes place during a sweltering summer in and around
Sal's Famous Pizza, run by an Italian (Danny Aiello) in a
lower-middle-class section of Brooklyn's largely black
Bedford-Stuyvesant. Tensions of family, race, friendship and love
run high. Tensions between Sal's hothead and racist son, Vito, and
an angry black, Radio Raheem, lead to the Raheem's murder by police
and the destruction of the pizza parlor.
   Bedford-Stuyvesant's reputation has fallen on bad times in recent
years, but in fact, this most populous of urban black communities
contains some of New York City's most ornate brownstones, some of
them designated landmarks. Many of the dwellings have been owned by
middle-class black families for generations. And affluent black
professionals live close to some of the city's toughest blocks.
   Newkirk has seen her neighborhood change dramatically,
remembering the lush trees that once lined the block and the lovely
gaslights that turned on at dusk. But hard economic times and drugs
have affected her community; a crack house on the block was closed
before production on the film started.
   Still, Newkirk, who has lived in the same house for over 50
years, can not recall any incident like the race riot that comes at
end of ``Do the Right Thing.''
   ``It's a peaceful neighborhood, definitely, considering with the
crack and everything,'' she said. ``On the whole, this place is
pretty quiet _ no robberies or shootings. We have very little
trouble.''
   During all the years Newkirk has lived on Stuyvesant Avenue,
Edward Alexis Connors has been her neighbor. He proudly described
Newkirk's home as a local landmark, built more than a century ago,
and agreed that the block is a peaceful one, with little trouble
from kids or police.
   ``We make it peaceful,'' Connors said. ``We don't turn the other
cheek. We had some static but we handled it. We have a good police
force and an excellent fire force.''
   The nearest pizzeria, C&amp;M Pizza, is a few blocks away on
Broadway, a heavily commercial street. Matt, the store's owner for
12 years, is an Hispanic who has never experienced the troubles with
local black kids as Sal did in ``Do the Right Thing.''
   In the movie, a black nationalist named Buggin Out (Giancarlo
Esposito) incites a violent confrontation when he demands that Sal
include famous blacks on his ``wall of fame'' instead of the
Italian-Americans whose photographs paper the wall. Sal refuses,
insisting that it's his pizzeria and he's Italian.
   ``You get a hard time any place you go, but I've had no racial
problems,'' said Matt, who asked that his last name not be used.
``You get crack dealers, but who doesn't? I don't allow that in
here. They go out in the street.''
   Jo Rob Turner, 31, and Justice Carter, 29, have lived in
Bedford-Stuyvesant most of their lives. They sipped Cokes and talked
about their neighborhood while sitting at a table at C&amp;M.
   ``Blacks, Puerto Ricans and Orientals hang out together,'' Turner
said. ``There are a lot of interracial couples, more than in the
'60s and the '70s.
   ``White folks come here without being bothered. You notice? It's
not something that happens every single day, but ain't you walkin'
lovely?''
   ``The media makes it more extreme,'' Carter said. ``Everybody
seems OK. You don't see that much racial stuff as before.
Everybody's trying to get along. There's been a lot of acceptance of
minorities.''
   The neighborhood in Lee's movie consists of blacks, Hispanics,
Italians, Koreans and a white bike-riding ``urban pioneer'' played
by John Savage.
   Carter and Turner agreed that crack is Bedford-Stuyvesant's
greatest problem.
   ``Crack has altered lives in phenomenal ways,'' Turner said.
``That is the worst, baddest drug that ever hit the market. I've
seen kids, 11 or 12 years old, eating out of vials of crack.''
   ``The first time you take that puff, you're off to a race,'' said
Carter, who talked of the absence of drugs in the movie. ``The story
was about racism, and that was going to sell.''
   Turner said ``Do the Right Thing'' could help outsiders
understand life in Bedford-Stuyvesant, but quickly added that a film
can never replace first-hand knowledge.
   ``That's a blessing and a curse,'' he said. ``A blessing because
some of the things that we've encountered, we can't believe we
actually got through it. ``But it also makes you're blind to one
side. There's book knowledge and street knowledge and you've got to
walk the streets. You've got to want to know, and that's the only
way to better understanding.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
