<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     06-23 0805</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0846</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy expanded at a 4.4 percent
annual rate in the first three months of the year.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday the gross national product,
the country's total output of goods and services, rose at the
fastest rate in more than a year during the first quarter.
   More than half of the increase resulted from a statistical
rebound from last year's drought.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has ordered tighter screening of
cassette recorders, lap-top computers and other electronic devices
on some international flights, but rejected calls to ban all such
items from airliners.
   Relatives of some of the 270 people killed in the December
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over Scotland had called for the ban
after investigators said plastic explosives concealed in a radio
cassette player destroyed the plane.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner said Thursday a ban would
unduly inconvenience passengers and would not likely be imposed by
other nations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Wall Street Journal, the nation's first
national newspaper, is 100 years old.
   The nation's largest newspaper, with 2 million circulation, will
celebrate its centennial with a special edition Friday.
   A series of birthday bashes held this week cannot obscure the
challenges the paper faces as it heads into its second century:
Circulation has slipped, advertising revenue is down and new
competition has emerged for both readers and ad dollars.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British conglomerate Hanson Trust PLC has made a
$4.8 billion buyout offer for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   The offer came two months after the mining giant escaped a
hostile takeover attempt by another suitor.
   Gold Fields quickly advised shareholders not to accept the bid
but indicated it was willing to talk with Hanson, which owns
businesses operations ranging from brewing to brickmaking in Britain
and the United States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. partners of the accounting giants Arthur
Young &amp; Co. and Ernst &amp; Whinney have voted overwhelmingly in favor
of a previously announced proposal to merge the firms.
   The merger plan, which will be submitted to partnerships abroad
over the next few months, would create the world's largest
professional services firm, to be known as Ernst &amp; Young.
   The new firm, which will be based in New York, is expected to
begin merged operations by Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domino's Pizza Inc. says it plans to stop
hiring employees under 18 although current workers can stay.
   The decision came after Florida parents complained about layoffs
following an earlier directive to re-assign or fire drivers under 18.
   Domino's has come under fire recently for a series of fatal
accidents involving delivery people. Spokesman Ron Hingst said
Thursday Domino's will recommend that its stores not hire people
under 18 for driving or non-driving jobs in the future.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines and Delta Air Lines have
dropped plans to merge their computer reservation systems because
the Justice Department threatened to sue to block the $2 billion
joint venture.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said in a statement announcing
the department's intention to file a civil antitrust suit that a
merger would bring higher fares and poorer service.
   Delta spokesman William Berry announced that the two carriers had
given up trying to merge their computer. ``We decided it would take
too much time to fight this in court,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. said it has stopped using
animals in its product safety tests, becoming the first major
cosmetics maker to do so.
   Animal rights activists praised Avon and said they hoped the
decision would encourage other companies to completely halt animal
testing.
   The beauty products company said it will rely on alternative
non-animal methods, harmless tests on people and an extensive
computerized data base containing information on the safety of
ingredients that previously have been examined.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has endorsed a Democratic child-care
package providing low-income parents with subsidies and tax credits,
defeating first a White House-backed alternative based almost
entirely on tax relief.
   The Democratic leadership's victory in the showdown left its
multibillion-dollar plan as the centerpiece of the Senate's
child-care legislation.
   Under an agreement between the parties, the debate continued
Thursday on a number of proposed amendments, with Republicans
seeking to tack parts of their defeated tax-credit plan onto
Democratic measure.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rallied after a three-session slide, recovering
most of its losses. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials gained
17.26 points to close at 2,482.17.
   Bond prices rose despite a decline in the dollar against major
currencies.
   Also Thursday, sugar futures prices surged; corn and soybean
futures wilted as rain arrived in Iowa; coffee futures rallied; and
energy, precious-metals and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
</TEXT>
