<FIRST>r f PM-SuperGas Bjt   06-23 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Super Gas, Bjt,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Performance for a Price: 100-Octane `Super Juice' Gas Back at the
Pumps</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gas-guzzling dinosaurs graze
alongside the most modern machines at Margaret Crane's mini-mart,
their owners lining up for the privilege of paying $2.59 cents for a
gallon of gas.
   But what a gallon of gas it is _ unleaded, 100-octane racing fuel
_ super juice for the almost-extinct ``muscle cars'' of the 1960s
and the sports cars of tomorrow.
   ``I had one man come in here with a beautiful sports car and he
said his car deserved it. Some (other) man just put in $44,'' said
Ms. Crane, manager of the Unocal 76 station in this well-to-do
suburb north of Chicago.
   ``I thought when I first got it, at $2.59 I'd never sell it.''
   But after two months of offering the gas, she noted, ``They don't
seem to mind about the money.''
   Stuart Cannes, Unocal's manager of racing-product sales, said the
gasoline is available at about 450 service stations nationwide,
including some two dozen in Illinois.
   ``Performance is back in vogue,'' Cannes said. ``There's no other
product that a customer with a 70,000-dollar automobile would put in
his gas tank.''
   Ms. Crane said most of her buyers are people in their 20s and 30s
who own late-model Porsches, Corvettes, Camaros, Trans Ams and
motorcycles, or the muscle cars of an earlier era _ GTOs,
Roadrunners and Chargers.
   Most buyers mix the racing gas with a lower octane gas _ about 92
or 93 for super-unleaded _ and come out with an average of 96
octane, Cannes said. Most cars run on 87-octane gasoline.
   Cannes said a higher octane level helps a ``high-performance
engine run to its peak performance.''
   But he also said that Los Angeles-based Unocal is not encouraging
drivers to push their cars beyond speed limits, or to race through
the streets.
   Dick Tippie, director of transportation safety for the
Chicago-based National Safety Council, said the council would be
opposed to any kind of product that might encourage people to speed
or drive recklessly.
   ``It may not be promoting it, but it's one of those things that
might lead, especially the younger driver, to think he could operate
a vehicle differently than he could under normal circumstances,''
Tippie said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time Bjt   06-23 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time, Bjt,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paramount Seeks Dismissal of Time Suit on Hostile Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the latest legal salvo in the fight for the
magazine and cable giant Time Inc., Paramount Communications Inc.
asked a federal court to dismiss a suit that could block its $10.7
billion takeover bid for Time.
   Paramount, a publisher and movie and TV producer, also asked the
U.S. District Court here to block Time's $14 billion tender offer
for Warner Communications Inc., a film and records company.
   Paramount made those requests Thursday in response to a suit Time
filed last week in an effort to thwart Paramount from proceeding
with its offer.
   Time and Warner are locked in combat with Paramount over how to
create one of the world's largest communications companies. Time and
Warner proposed a merger, but Paramount showed up with an uninvited
offer for Time.
   Their two-week-old fight has moved in recent days to the courts.
   On Wednesday, Paramount asked the Delaware Chancery Court to
block the Time bid for Warner. A hearing on that case has been set
for July 11.
   In response to Time's federal suit on Thursday, Paramount struck
back at suggestions that its takeover of Time would damage the
journalistic integrity and independence of Time's publications.
   It said Time failed to disclose enough information about legal
problems Warner executives faced in the 1970s and early 1980s.
   Time and Warner called Paramount's filing an ``act of
desperation.''
   In consolidated trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Time fell
$1.87{ a share to $155.37{, Warner rose 62{ cents a share to
$59.12{, and Paramount lost 75 cents a share to $58.50.
   Time had agreed in March to merge with Warner in a stock swap,
but amended that plan last week to provide for a $70-a-share tender
offer for Warner.
   In announcing the new deal, Time rejected Paramount's
$175-a-share offer for all of Time's shares and filed suit in U.S.
District Court in New York to block Paramount from proceeding with
its offer. It said Paramount had made false and misleading
statements in pursuing Time.
   In response, Paramount counterclaimed on Thursday that Time had
made ``misleading statements and material omissions designed to
deceive Time stockholders'' in its offer for Warner.
   It said that by agreeing to the deal with Warner, Time ``is
forcing upon its shareholders a transaction whereby Time's
`integrity' and financial future will fall under the control of
Warner, whose executives in the recent past have been the subject of
criminal investigation, prosecution and in some cases conviction.''
   Among other things, Paramount cited the 1977 federal
investigation into the operations of the Westchester Premier
Theater. Two Warner executives pleaded guilty and a third was
convicted on charges in connection with Warner's purchase of shares
in the theater.
   Paramount noted that Warner Chairman Steven J. Ross was involved
in the investigation. Ross was never charged with wrongdoing in the
Premier Theater case, however.
   Time said Paramount's filing ``is an act of desperation full of
stale accusations that do nothing to clarify the real issues we
raised in our suit.''
   Ross said the Paramount filing was ``deliberately designed and
intended to distract from the principal issues at hand by
resurrecting old and entirely irrelevant points that have long since
been thoroughly aired both in public and the courts.''
   In a separate development, Time's 82 percent-owned American
Television and Communications Corp. said the city of Casselberry,
Fla., had filed suit in U.S. District Court in Florida asking that
Paramount be prohibited from taking ownership of its cable TV
franchise there without necessary approvals.
   ATC said it was the first such suit by a city in which ATC is
operating.
   A spokesman for Paramount said the company has no intention of
acquiring any cable franchise without state and local approvals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 0141EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Journal-BirthdayParty     06-23 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Journal-Birthday Party,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journal Bash Draws Bush, Buckley, Bianca</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Journal-Centennial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George and Barbara Bush were there. So was
William F. Buckley Jr., Bianca Jagger, Peter Jennings and Steve Jobs.
   The Wall Street Journal threw itself a gala 100th birthday party
Thursday night, filling the glass atrium outside its glitzy
headquarters with 600 luminaries.
   Though the guests ranged from chiefs of Fortune 500 companies to
media personalities, the real stars of the dinner-dance were the
president and his wife.
   ``The six columns of The Wall Street Journal are as familiar as
coffee at our morning breakfast tables,'' Bush told the black-tie
crowd that filled the sprawling Winter Garden atrium at lower
Manhattan's World Financial Center.
   ``If anything catastrophic happened in the Winter Garden, the
Fortune 500 would be lucky to keep in just double digits,'' Bush
quipped.
   The guest list read like a Who's Who of the business and media
worlds: computer whiz Jobs, Ford Motor Co. Chairman Donald Peterson,
ITT Corp. Chairman Rand Araskog, CBS Inc. Chairman Lawrence Tisch,
``60 Minutes'' anchor Mike Wallace, ABC anchor Jennings, and
Washington Post Co. Chairwoman Katharine Graham, among others.
   The entertainment agenda ranged from jazz great Lionel Hampton to
rocker Chuck Berry and blues singer Buster Poindexter.
   The guests also included 52 Journal readers _ one randomly
selected from each state _ and a reader each from Europe and Asia,
representing the paper's European and Asian editions.
   Rank-and-file Journal employees were not invited, but will have
39 picnics July 8 _ the actual date of the centennial _ at cities
across the country.
   In his remarks, Bush praised the financial daily as ``one of
America's most trusted publications.''
   ``A reputation like that can only be earned by adherence to your
founders' pledge to always have the news `honest, intelligent and
unprejudiced,'' Bush said.
   Bush also praised two Journal reporters, John Fialka and Alex
Kotlowitz, for organizing fund-raising efforts for needy people they
wrote about.
   Fialka, after writing in 1986 about the plight of poor retired
clergy, helped found an organization called SOAR _ Support Our Aging
Religious _ that has raised more than $1 million to aid 30 different
orders.
   Kotlowitz in 1987 chronicled the turbulent life in a gang-ridden
Chicago housing project of 12-year-old Lafayette Walton. Last
summer, Bush said, ``they passed the hat at the Journal and gave
Lafayette and his brother a season of peace in the woods of a
Wisconsin boy's camp.''
   ``These are the works of men and women who know that prosperity
without purpose means nothing,'' said Bush, who urged corporate
chieftains at the banquet to join the community service crusade Bush
announced earlier Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
