<FIRST>r f PM-Princeton-Newport     06-23 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Princeton-Newport,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Trader Testifies About Stock Deals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials at Princeton-Newport Partners LP bought
and sold stock to generate tax losses and then instructed employees
on how to cover up the transactions, a former trader has testified.
   ``Princeton-Newport was parking securities to generate short-term
capital tax losses for the partners,'' William Hale said Thursday at
the racketeering trial of five Princeton-Newport officials and a
former trader at Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Hale said the practice was widespread at the investment firm from
late 1984 until 1986 when he was fired.
   The government alleges that the defendants engaged in a
widespread tax fraud scheme through the securities transactions.
Neither of the firms is on trial.
   Hale's testimony focused on Paul Berkman, a Princeton-Newport
partner who was his immediate boss. He said Berkman instructed him
on ways to cover up the parking of securities.
   ``Berkman told me on buybacks to break them up to camouflage the
buybacks in case of audit,'' said Hale, who worked in the trading
room at Princeton, N.J. The company also had offices in Newport
Beach, Calif.
   Hale said he was told to change the price when buying back the
securities. ``Raise some, lower some to make it equal out,'' he said.
   ``Berkman said the IRS did not have the manpower to look over the
thousands of transactions at Princeton-Newport and see a pattern or
to figure out what was happening,'' Hale testified.
   He was asked by Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Hansen whether
others spoke to him about the parking of securities.
   ``Just about everyone,'' he said and named four other defendants:
traders Jack Z. Rabinowitz and Charles M Zarzecki; Princeton-Newport
comptroller Steven B. Smotorick; and former Drexel trader Bruce Lee
Newberg.
   The sixth defendant is James Sutton Regan, a Princeton-Newport
managing partner.
   The case overlaps with the government's indictment of former
Drexel financier Michael Milken, who headed the firm's junk bond
department.
   Hale said officials of Princeton-Newport had arrangements to park
securities at Drexel, Merrill Lynch and Akroyd &amp; Smithers Securities
Inc. No employees from Merrill Lynch or Akroyd &amp; Smithers have been
charged in the case.
   He also testified that he wrote down all the parking transactions
on a piece of paper which he kept on his desk for other workers to
see. Hale said he and the other employees called the list ``the
parking lot.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
