<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern Bjt   06-23 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, Bjt,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to restore Bjt slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>House Minority Whip Asks Skinner to Enter Eastern Bankruptcy Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressmen asked Transportation Secretary
Samuel Skinner to enter the Eastern Airlines bankruptcy case out of
``urgent'' concern that the carrier's restructuring could lessen
airline competition.
   In a letter Wednesday to Skinner, House Republican Whip Newt
Gingrich of Georgia and Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., expressed
concern that antitrust issues have not been addressed adequately in
the Eastern bankruptcy proceedings.
   The letter also stated the two were worried that the plan by
Eastern parent Texas Air Corp. to rebuild the airline as a smaller
carrier and sell $1.8 billion in assets could reduce Eastern's
competitiveness.
   ``Our concern is urgent because it appears likely that Eastern
Airlines will be sold off in pieces, resulting in less than a fully
integrated competitive carrier,'' Gingrich and Campbell wrote
Skinner.
   A copy of the letter was obtained by The Associated Press.
   On Thursday, U.S. Rep. Glenn Anderson, chairman of the aviation
subcommittee of the House Public Works and Transportation Committee,
announced that his panel will hold a hearing next week on Eastern's
condition and ``the prospects for its restoration as a major
carrier.''
   Gingrich and Campbell said they especially were concerned that
Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo had an interest in not building up
Eastern as a competitor to Continental Airlines, Texas Air's other
main subsidiary.
   ``We are troubled that Mr. Lorenzo has more than one interest as
he offers the piecemeal sale of Eastern, and no party before the
bankruptcy judge represents the antitrust interest of the United
States,'' the letter read.
   ``We respectfully request that you make this decision quickly, as
the assets of Eastern are so rapidly being depleted that its
viability as a competitor on any routes may soon be in question.''
   Skinner hasn't responded to the letter, DOT spokesman Hal Paris
said Thursday.
   Miami-based Eastern has been under bankruptcy protection from
creditors since March 9, five days after the Machinists union struck
the carrier and was joined in the crippling walkout by pilots and
flight attendants.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland so far has allowed
Eastern to sell its Northeast shuttle service to developer Donald
Trump for $365 million. He also has approved Eastern's $277.5
million sale of 15 planes and six engines to an aircraft leasing
company.
   On Thursday, Eastern announced a deal to sell the last three
planes of its Boeing 727-100 fleet for $9 million to Express One, an
aircraft company based in Dallas. The proposed sale still must be
approved by Lifland.
   Eastern also has reached agreement to sell its eight Philadelphia
gates, 16 jets and other assets to Midway Airlines for $206.5
million. Skinner also has not approved that deal.
   Under Skinner, the Department of Transportation recently has
taken several steps to discourage actions it sees as possibly
inhibiting competition in the deregulated airline industry. For
example, he has warned 28 U.S. airlines that he would stop the
buying and selling of international routes when it affects
competition.
</TEXT>
