<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     06-23 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Sinks, Gold Drifts Downward</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar sank lower this morning in nervous
European trading.
   Gold prices also drifted downward.
   European dealers said the currency market had not recovered its
equilibrium following a volatile swing late Thursday. The dollar
dived after a false rumor that President Bush had been shot.
   ``Everyone is very, very nervous today,'' said a trader at a
large bank in Frankfurt, West Germany. ``People are not sure about
anything. I think it will be either very volatile today, or nothing
will happen.''
   ``We're certainly not going to see the dollar up over 2.0 marks
in the short term. For the moment it needs to find a new base level
before it can move back up again,'' said a trader in Milan, Italy.
   ``We're not going to see much buying today, and those selling are
mostly cleaning up positions,'' said another dealer in Milan.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell to 140.35 Japanese yen, down 1.05 yen
from Thursday. Later in London, the dollar traded at 139.94 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with Thursday's late
rates, included: 1.9520 West German marks, down from 1.9590; 1.6825
Swiss francs, down from 1.6860; 6.6250 French francs, down from
6.6325; 2.2058 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2005; 1,418.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,418.50; and 1.1912 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1925.
   The British pound cost $1.5565, compared to late Thursday's
$1.5525.
   Gold opened in London at $370.10 a troy ounce in London, the
major market, up from $369.75 late Thursday. At midmorning, the
city's five major gold dealers fixed a recommended price of $369.50.
   In Zurich at noon, gold traded at $369.50, down from $370.60 late
Thursday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold dropped 86 cents an ounce to close at
$369.63.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at $5.30 a troy ounce,
compared to $5.34 late Thursday.
</TEXT>
