<FIRST>r f BC-Gateway     06-23 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Gateway,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wasserstein Perella Raises Bid for British Retailer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group led by U.S. financiers Wasserstein Perella
&amp; Co. sweetened its offer for Gateway Corp. PLC to $3.29 billion
Friday after an increase in its bid a day earlier failed to draw
significant support from the British retailer's shareholders.
   The new offer, at $3.69, or 237 pence, a share, tops the $3.66,
offered Thursday. With 890 million Gateway shares outstanding, the
bid values the company at a total of $3.29 billion.
   A rival bidder, Isosceles PLC, is offering $3.59 a share or a
total of $3.19 billion.
   The Wasserstein Perella group, which includes the Great Atlantic
&amp; Pacific Tea Co., is trying to rescue Britain's third largest food
retailer from its two-month old takeover fight against Isosceles.
   However, the Wasserstein Perella group had succeeded in gaining
control of only 3.3 percent of Gateway shares by the close of
trading Thursday.
   Isosceles, backed by a number of Gateway shareholders and
managers, said early Friday it owns or has received acceptances for
44.9 percent of Gateway shares.
   Wasserstein Perella and A&amp;P have indicated that if their takeover
succeeds they would keep much of Gateway intact, except for its
Herman's sporting goods chain in the United States, which would be
sold. Gateway controls about 11.4 percent of the $54.57 billion
British grocery market.
   Isosceles planned a more radical reorganization and intended to
sell off Gateway food stores.
</TEXT>
