<DOCNO> AP890623-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1011EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-US-GATT     06-23 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-US-GATT,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>United States Announces Change in Import Taxes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has said it will introduce new
legislation to reduce the tax on petroleum imports and lift a
controversial customs surcharge, a spokesman for the organization
which sets world trade rules said Friday.
   Investigation panels of the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade ruled more than a year ago that the so-called tax and the
customs user fee violated international trade law.
   U.S. deputy trade representative Rufus Yerxa told negotiators at
a GATT council meeting that legislation was before the U.S. Congress
to equalize treatment of imported and locally produced petroleum,
the GATT spokesman said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   This would amend a 1986 law which imposed a tax of 8.2 U.S. cents
on domestically produced petroleum and 11.7 cents on imported
petroleum, prompting complaints from Canada, Mexico and the European
Economic Community.
   Proceeds from the tax were intended for a ``superfund'' to
finance a harzardous waste cleanup program.
   Yerxa also said the United States would modify a surcharge levied
to cover import processing costs, according to the spokesman who was
at the closed meeting that ended late Thursday night.
   A GATT panel in 1987 backed a complaint by the European Economic
Community and Canada that the customs user fee of 0.17 percent of
the value of the basic product was a trade barrier because it earned
the United States more revenue than the real cost of import
processing.
   The GATT council meeting also agreed to give South Korea more
time to consider the findings of new panel reports against its
restrictions on beef imports, the GATT spokesman said.
   In separate complaints raised by the United States, Australia and
New Zealand, the investigation panels ruled at the end of April the
restrictions on imports were not justified on balance of payment
grounds.
   Under the rules of the 96-nation trade organization, less
developed countries are allowed to keep import restrictions to
protect their balance of payments.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
