<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-HollyFarms 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holly Farms, 1st Ld-Writethru,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judges OKs Tyson Purchase Deal For Holly, Tyson Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with Judge approving tentative agreement.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware judge approved today a tentative
agreement allowing Tyson Foods Inc. to buy Holly Farms Corp. for
$1.4 billion, a lawyer for Tyson said.
   The agreement, filed by lawyers for Tyson, Holly Farms and
ConAgra Inc., requires approval of the Holly Farms board of
directors, which is meeting in New York today, said Jim Blair, chief
legal counsel for Tyson.
   ``It sets the stage for a three-party settlement. I'm cautiously
optimistic,'' Blair said.
   Blair said the proposed agreement requires Tyson to pay ConAgra
$50 million to withdraw from the bidding for Holly Farms. The buyout
will cost Tyson about $1.4 billion, Blair said.
   Tyson has been trying to buy Memphis-based Holly Farms since
October while Holly Farms has been trying since November to merge
with ConAgra, based in Omaha, Neb.
   The Springdale, Ark.-based Tyson raised its tender offer for
Holly Farms stock to $70 a share Tuesday, and on Thursday, Holly
Farms directors announced they had begun new talks with Tyson and
ConAgra.
   ``The transaction being discussed would involve termination of
the Holly Farms merger agreement with ConAgra, settlement of all
litigation between the parties and an acquisition of Holly Farms
Corp. by Tyson Foods at $70 per share in cash,'' a Holly Farms
statement said.
   Directors of Holly Farms had rejected Tyson's previous offers and
announced two merger attempts with ConAgra. Holly Farms shareholders
rejected the first attempt in April, and Holly Farms announced the
second one in May.
   The latest merger proposal would have been accomplished through a
stock swap worth about $68 a share to Holly Farms shareholders.
Stockholders of the two companies had been expected to vote on that
proposal next month.
   Tyson began the bidding for Holly Farms last October with a cash
and stock-swap proposal worth $49.50 to Holly shareholders.
   Tyson has filed suit in Delaware _ where Holly Farms is
incorporated _ accusing the Memphis-based company of wrongly
favoring ConAgra at Tyson's expense. Tyson has asked for $500
million in damages.
   John McMillin, a market analyst for Prudential-Bache in New York,
said Tyson's decision to raise its offer from $63.50 to $70 may have
made the difference in the takeover attempt.
   ``It's been a difficult courtship between Tyson Foods and Holly
Farms, but I think they're going to get married,'' McMillin said.
   Tyson Foods processes more than 16.5 million chickens a week,
while Holly Farms is a diversified company heavily involved in fresh
fryer sales. ConAgra is a diversified company specializing in food
and agricultural services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
