<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-23 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Rise On Easing Rain, Brazil Worries</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were slightly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade
following reports of lighter-than-expected rainfall overnight in the
western Corn Belt.
   The light buying followed a steep sell-off of corn and soybean
futures Thursday on expectations that the fairly heavy showers that
hit western Iowa on Wednesday night and Thursday would spread
undiminished across the Midwest.
   The soybean market saw some additional buying on worries that the
international marketplace is beginning to feel the pinch of a
producer-led disruption of soybean business in Brazil, the world's
second-largest soybean source.
   ``Some of the processors are saying they may have to declare
force majeur on some shipments,'' meaning they cannot meet their
commitments, said Dale Gustafson, a grain market analyst in Chicago
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Brazilian soybean producers halted sales of soybeans and began
blocking soybean traffic about two weeks ago in a bid to push their
government toward economic reforms.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.99} a bushel; corn was }
cent to 1{ cents higher with July at $2.62{ a bushel; oats were \
cent to 1 cent higher with July at $1.58 a bushel; soybeans were 5
cents to 7\ cents higher with July at $7.30 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were modestly lower while pork futures were
slightly higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent to .40 cent lower with August at 69.85
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent to .28 cent lower with
August at 81.02 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to .35 cent
higher with July at 49.55 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.03 cent to .23 cent higher with July at 33.90 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
</TEXT>
