<FIRST>r f BC-Schering-Unilever     06-23 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Schering-Unilever,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schering-Plough Selling Cosmetics Companies to Unilever</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Schering-Plough Corp. announced Friday the
sale of its cosmetics companies in Britain and West Germany to
Unilever NV for about $120 million.
   Schering-Plough announced its intention to sell Rimmel
International Ltd., of London, and Chicogo GmbH, of Dusseldorf, in
April. The two cosmetics companies, which employ 715 people, had
sales last year of about $75 million, according to a written
statement from Schering-Plough and Unilever.
   The sale does not affect Schering-Plough's Maybelline North
America cosmetics business.
   The agreement needs government approval and is expected to be
completed before January.
   Rimmel markets color cosmetics under such trademarks as Rimmel
and Sensiq. Chicogo's brand names are Chicogo and Ellocar.
   ``The purchase of the Rimmel and Chicogo businesses will
significantly enhance Unilever's position in the European color
cosmetics markets, lifting it to second place in value terms,'' said
Michael Perry, director of personal products operation for Unilever,
based in London and Rotterdam, Netherlands.
   Unilever makes consumer and packaged goods _ mainly foods,
detergents and personal care products _ and sells color cosmetics
under the Cutex name in North America. Schering-Plough is a research
company that develops, makes and markets pharmaceutical and consumer
products.
</TEXT>
