<DOCNO> AP890623-0231 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1613EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv26   06-23 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 26,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Monday June 26</HEAD>
<HEAD>More Dollars, Fewer Equities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An important but often ignored consequence of
mergers and takeovers in recent years has been a steady shrinkage in
the amount of corporate stock available for trading.
   It is just one of several important changes in the anatomy of the
stock market that make it a very different beast than that of two
decades ago.
   In just five years, from 1984 through 1988, a total of $369
billion of U.S. equities was removed from the trading arena, an
average of $74 billion a year, in contrast to the previous 15 years,
when the total rose at $9 billion a year.
   The figures, obtained from Wright Investors' Service, Bridgeport,
Conn., show the trend has significantly reduced the variety of
investment options and created a classic supply-demand imbalance
that has tended to push up prices.
   In Wright's opinion, the relative shortage of marketable equities
is an important prop under the current level of stock prices. Still,
it adds, that prop is not unshakeable, and it forecasts a price
decline later this year.
   Another fundamental change in the market has been the long
evolution from individual to institutional ownership.
   Wright's figures show that the enormous growth of pension and
mutual funds is not the sole reason for the dominance of
institutions. Simultaneously, it observes, individual activity has
been falling sharply.
   In fact, the Wright analysis shows individual investors cashed in
$500 billion of blue chip stocks during the five years from 1984
through 1988. In 1988 alone, it says, household stock holdings
shrank by $105 billion, and in the first quarter of 1989 the exodus
rose to an annual rate of $157 billion.
   For every sale there must be a buyer, of course, and in recent
years the buyers have been institutions. Recent patterns of activity
show, however, that unusual changes also have been occurring within
the institutional body.
   In the five years through 1988, for example, equity mutual funds
increased their holdings by $48 billion, but last year they returned
$16 billion to the market and they continued to be sellers right
through 1989's first quarter.
   According to Wright, the only major sector which has consistently
added to equity holdings of late is state and local government
retirement funds. In the five years through 1988, these funds were
net buyers of $108 billion of stocks.
   The reason why stocks in recent months seem to have fallen into
disfavor isn't at all clear, except for the likelihood that the
yield on bonds convinced some portfolio managers that bonds were the
better risk.
   That explanation, however, doesn't help at all in clarfiying why
portfolio managers for state and local government pension funds
found equities attractive while their counterparts in private-sector
funds were net sellers.
   Who, then, has been supporting the market? Wright concedes that
foreign investors were important buyers during the price runup of
the 1980s. But even foreigners were sellers in the months following
the late-1987 market crash.
   It isn't totally clear whether foreigners are still selling to
this day or whether they have, instead, reverted to their old buying
habits, but in the first quarter they unloaded $l.6 billion of U.S.
equities.
   While statistics such as these _ plenty of sellers but few buyers
_ suggest a mysterious source of support for the current level of
prices, there is one prop that is delineated clearly and precisely.
   It is this: A growing supply of money and a shrinking supply of
equities tend to exert an upward force on prices. Whether that force
is sufficient to maintain current price levels, however, is not
nearly so clear.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Monday June 26</NOTE>
