<FIRST>u f PM-SpendingBill 2ndLd-Writethru   06-23 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spending Bill, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Passes Bill Averting Disruption of Veterans' Care</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new to include Fitzwater quote. picks up 3rd graf
pvs, The emergency.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House today sent to President Bush an
emergency spending bill that averts the threatened disruption of
health care for veterans and other programs.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said ``we're very
pleased'' with the legislation and said Bush looked forward to
signing it.
   The $3.5 billion fiscal 1989 supplemental appropriations bill,
approved by the Senate Thursday night, passed the House 318-6.
   The emergency legislation was delayed for weeks, mostly because
of a battle over adding more money for anti-drug programs.
   In a compromise struck Thursday, House Democrats dropped their
plan to add $821 million for drug programs.
   The White House had threatened to veto the bill if the drug money
were included, saying federal agencies already had all the money
they could spend this year.
   The new version would add just $75 million for the anti-drug
effort, with that money coming from deferring spending on two other
programs until fiscal 1990. The revised bill was cleared in meetings
with White House budget director Richard Darman on Thursday.
   ``This could free up the logjam so the veterans programs and
other funding emergencies can get their money,'' said Sen. Robert C.
Byrd, D-W.Va., chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee.
   Byrd said he contributed to the compromise by halving the bill's
allocation for one of his pet projects, replacement of a $75 million
radio-telescope in his home state, delaying the rest of the money
for that project until next year. The rest of the money for the drug
programs would come from deferring some agriculture spending.
   On Wednesday, the House killed an earlier version of the bill
which was opposed by Republicans and conservative Democrats. Anxious
about leaving veterans' programs threatened over the Fourth of July
holiday, congressional leaders discussed a temporary bill to delay
final action until next month but the White House balked at further
delays.
   Under congressional rules, the bill is supposed to provide money
only for ``dire emergencies,'' but it actually covers a broad swath
of spending programs.
   The largest single item is $1.2 billion for the Department of
Veterans Affairs to cover a shortfall in money for medical care,
compensation and pensions, and in other areas.
   Thousands of veterans would be denied health care without the
extra funding this year, according to the administration.
   The bill would add nearly $900 million to the federal guaranteed
student loan program, $342 million to cover the cost of fighting
last year's widespread forest fires, and $423 million for foster
care and adoption.
   The food stamp program would be increased $225 million, aid to
the unemployed $90 million, and refugee assistance 100 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
