<FIRST>r f AM-MortonThiokol     06-23 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Morton Thiokol,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stockholders Approve Operations Split</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morton Thiokol Inc. stockholders Friday approved
splitting the company's operations, returning the Thiokol name to
its aerospace division and creating a new chemicals, airbags and
salt business named Morton International Inc.
   Ballots representing 76 percent of the company's 47.6 million
outstanding shares were cast in the election, with about 60 percent
of outstanding shares favoring the split and 15.4 percent opposed.
   ``We are pleased to have received stockholders' approval and plan
to move forward to complete the transaction,'' said Charles S.
Locke, chairman and chief executive officer of Morton Thiokol Inc.
   He said the split would take effect July 1.
   The new Thiokol Corp. will continue to operate under the existing
Morton Thiokol board of directors, with Morton Thiokol stockholders
receiving a share-for-share distribution of Morton International.
   Thiokol Corp. was the name of the missile company that was
acquired in 1982 by Morton Norwich. The merged company was called
Morton Thiokol Inc.
   Locke said the combined market values of the stock of the two
companies will equal or exceed the present value of Morton Thiokol
stock.
   Officials said Morton International will be headquartered in
Chicago _ current home of Morton Thiokol _ and will have $1.1
billion in annual sales and assets of $800 million. It will deal in
specialty chemicals, salt and inflatable restraint systems known as
airbags.
   Locke will be chairman and chief executive officer of Morton
International.
   The new Thiokol Corp. initially is to be headquartered in Ogden,
Utah, although other cities are under consideration, officials said.
   U. Edwin Garrison, president of Morton Thiokol's Aerospace Group,
was named in April to become president and chief executive officer
of the new Thiokol Corp. by Morton Thiokol's board.
   Thiokol will employ about 12,000 people, with about 8,000 people
at the Wasatch Operations west of Brigham City in northern Utah,
where space shuttle rocket motors and other strategic and tactical
missile systems are manufactured.
   After 2{ years redesigning the shuttle motor blamed for the 1986
explosion of the Challenger space shuttle, Morton Thiokol declined
to bid on the NASA contract for a new generation of boosters.
   Net sales in the aerospace division increased 14 percent in the
first nine months of fiscal 1989 to $871.5 million from $766.4
million.
   Company officials said Morton International would have annual
sales approaching $1.5 billion, with assets of $1.4 billion and more
than 8,000 employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
