<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1402EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-ChildCare 4thLd-Writethru f0129 06-23 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Child Care, 4th Ld-Writethru, f0129,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dems Add Compromise But White House Says `No Deal'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 8 grafs new with Bentsen amendment passing; picks up at
pvs 7th graf, Thursday's debate; Also on general news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats today revised their child-care
bill to add a provision sought by the White House, but the
administration said the package remained unacceptable and was ``a
candidate for a veto'' by President Bush.
   An amendment, approved 54-45, added a third element to a
tax-credit package that already includes upfront money to help poor
families pay for child care and a new credit to help them pay for
children's health insurance.
   The new element, an expansion of the earned income tax credit for
low-income parents with children under age 5, was part of an
alternative Republican child-care package defeated Thursday.
   But Republicans scoffed at the compromise effort, led by Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas. White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
the gesture was not enough to sway the administration's opposition
to the bill, a revised version of the Act for Better Child Care,
known as ABC.
   ``The ABC bill in any combination is a candidate for a veto,''
said Fitzwater, who did not say outright that Bush would veto it.
   Bentsen, angered that Republicans would not accept his overture,
said the GOP was refusing to give ground.
   ``I offer this amendment in a spirit of compromise,'' he said.
``The president of the United States can't have it all.''
   Their attempt at compromise spurned, the Senate's majority
Democrats then moved to clear a long list of amendments in hopes of
forcing a final vote on the package later today. However, approval
of Bentsen's measure appeared likely to trigger lengthy debate on
the amendments, delaying the wrapup vote.
   Thursday's debate concluded just before midnight with Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine warning that a two-week
recess scheduled to begin today would be put on hold unless work on
the child-care plan is finished.
   Many of the GOP amendments adopted Thursdsay made no major
changes and were accepted by the sponsors of the legislation.
   Also winning approval were two amendments dealing with the
earnings limit faced by certain Social Security recipients. One
exempted all child-care related earnings from the cap; the other
raised the cap by $1,200 a year.
   With House action on child care just beginning, Senate Democrats
say their proposal will now likely serve as the framework for the
plan that ultimately clears Congress.
   Republicans said that with action still on hold in the House, the
Bush administration has time to seek further compromise.
   GOP lawmakers failed 56-44 in their attempt to kill the
Democratic plan in favor of a White House-backed approach keyed to
tax credits. The Senate then voted 63-37 to accept the broader
Democratic plan in principle, leaving the final vote until later.
   Republicans argued the Democrats' version would create new
bureaucracies and limit parental choice because the legislation
recommends that states adopt minimum standards for child care.
   ``Child care is a family issue,'' Senate Republican leader Bob
Dole of Kansas said. ``It's a family issue, not a government issue.''
   But the principal author of the measure, Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., said some state regulation of child care is necessary.
   ``If your car and your pets are given certain protections by
state licensing agencies, we think your children deserve no less,''
Dodd said. He also disputed the GOP assertions about parental
choice, noting that 70 percent of the $1.75 billion in subsidies
authorized for fiscal 1990 would have to be paid to parents.
   In addition to the $1.75 billion subsidy authorization, the
Democrats' plan creates a new tax credit of up to $1,000 to help
low-income parents buy health insurance for their children. It also
would make refundable in advance 90 percent of the existing
dependent care tax credit, a step designed to provide cash to
low-income parents who otherwise cannot take advantage of the
credit. Bentsen said his revised tax-relief package still would cost
the government about $10.5 billion over five years.
   The defeated GOP plan also allowed poor families to get the
dependent care credit up front. Its other major element was the EITC
expansion.
   The amendment exempting child-care earnings from the Social
Security earnings cap was sponsored by Sen. William Roth, R-Del.
   The other, offered by Bentsen, increased the overall earnings
limit currently applied to Social Security recipients age 65 to 69.
They lose $1 in benefits for every $2 in outside income over $8,800.
The amendment would raise the earnings threshold to $10,560 and
lower the rate of benefits loss to $1 for every $4 earned.
</TEXT>
