<FIRST>r f BC-Texaco     06-23 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Texaco,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco To Redeem $966 Million In Debentures Ahead Of Maturity Dates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. said Friday it plans to
retire almost $1 billion in debt securities ahead of scheduled
maturity dates in a further effort to improve the company's
financial footing.
   Texaco earlier this year completed a major financial
restructuring, including the sale of $7 billion in assets, nearly a
year after emerging from Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
   The company has said it would use proceeds from the asset sales
to reduce debt.
   The following three debt issues are scheduled to be redeemed on
Aug. 31:
   _$500 million of 13 percent notes due Aug. 1, 1991, issued by
Texaco Capital Inc., to be redeemed at par plus accrued interest.
   _$307 million of 11~ percent convertible subordinated debentures
due May 1, 1994, issued by Texaco Capital N.V., to be redeemed at
104 percent of the $1,000 face value plus accrued interest;
   _$159 million of 11} percent convertible subordinated debentures
due May 15, 1994, issued by Texaco Capital N.V., to be redeemed at
104 percent of the $1,000 face value plus accrued interest.
   Redemption of the $466 million in convertible subordinated
debentures represents the final amount outstanding of $1.5 billion
in those securities Texaco issued in 1984. Holders of the other
$1.034 billion of similar issues previously had converted them into
20.7 million shares of the company's stock, Texaco said.
   Early retirement of the corporate securities will further
strengthen Texaco's financial position and improve profitability and
shareholder value, said company President James W. Kinnear.
   As of the end of March 1989, Texaco, the third largest U.S. oil
company behind Exxon Corp. and Mobil Corp., had reduced its debt to
$7.1 billion from $10.8 billion in April 1988. The company said
earlier this year that it hoped to cut it back to $6.5 billion by
the end of the year.
   Texaco did not say how much it would save through the early
retirement of the notes and bonds, but indicated the savings would
be ``pretty significant,'' given the high interest rates.
   ``This is what's behind it. This is high-cost debt,'' said
spokeswoman Anita Larsen.
</TEXT>
