<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-23 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Surge On Brazilian Supply Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed with strong gains
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid fears that a producer-led
halt to Brazilian soybean sales is beginning to squeeze supplies on
the world market.
   Wheat and oat futures retreated while corn was narrowly mixed.
   Brazilian soybean growers stopped selling their crops to
processors about two weeks ago to protest government economic
policies.
   Now rumors are spreading that some Brazilian soybean crushers
will be forced to delay shipments of soybean meal and oil to their
European trading partners.
   If those shipments are delayed, demand and prices for U.S.
soybeans are likely to rise.
   ``It is very much an uncertainty,'' said Cathy Leow, an assistant
vice president and grain-market analyst with Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``And because we don't have much stocks of old-crop beans in
Midwest, it's a very explosive situation for the nearby contracts,''
those for delivery in July and August.
   At the close, soybeans were 2 cents to 9{ cents higher with July
at $7.30 a bushel; wheat was unchanged to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.97{ a bushel; corn was 3 cents
lower to { cent higher with July at $2.62\ a bushel; oats were 4\
cents to 4{ cents lower with July at $1.52{ a bushel.

</TEXT>
