<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1717EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Bass     06-23 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Bass,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain's Largest Brewer, Bass, Announces Restructure Plans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bass PLC, Britain's largest brewer, is to split its
pub and brewing operations into two divisions in an apparent
response to recent recommendations by antitrust authorities.
   Bass said Friday its new Inns and Taverns unit would be
responsible for the retail operation of Bass-managed pubs, together
with the administration of and sales to its tenanted pubs.
   Meanwhile, the Bass Brewers division will take charge of
wholesaling the company's different brands, a statement said.
   A Monopolies and Mergers Commission report on the brewing
industry has recommended no company with brewing interests should
own more than 2,000 pubs. The brewers are negotiating with Trade
Secretary Lord Young on the recommendations.
   If the main proposals are implemented, Bass will be better placed
to sell off either division if necessary, analysts say. The
restructuring, which the company says will give it the basis for
flexibility and continued growth, is to be implemented in October.
</TEXT>
