<DOCNO> AP890623-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1957EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-SteelTalks     06-23 0291</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Talks,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inland Terms Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative contract settlement between the
United Steelworkers and Inland Steel Co. offers nearly 12,000 union
members an immediate bonus of $500, $1.50 in base wage increases and
higher incentive pay.
   USW officials released the details of the four-year pact Friday.
   Handbills distributed at plant gates at Chicago Friday morning
said the offer includes the bonus and a 75 cent rise in base wages
on Aug. 1, the day the contract will take effect if ratified by the
rank-and-file.
   The next raise would come Jan. 1, 1991, when base wages would
increase by 50 cents and the incentive rate by 25 cents per hour.
   A year later, base wages would rise by 25 cents and the incentive
rate by 50 cents per hour, and on Jan. 1, 1993, the only increase
would be a 25 cent-per-hour boost in the incentive rate.
   The incentive system pays workers a portion, typically 35
percent, of the incentive rate. Most Inland workers are on incentive
pay. They will get the $1.50 base wage increase plus 35 cents of the
$1 hike in the incentive rate.
   In addition, Inland is offering to restore the one week of
vacation the workers gave up in the 1986 talks.
   Pensions will be improved so that the minimum payment for those
with 30 years' service will be $1,000.
   District 31 Director Jack Parton, who led the union negotiating
team, called the new pension plan the best in the steel industry.
   Inland originally wanted the right to schedule workers for a
12-hour work day, Parton said. The company also wanted the employees
to help pay medical insurance premiums. Both demands were withdrawn,
Parton said.
   The agreement was reached Thursday in Chicago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
