<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1633EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAWConvention     06-23 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAW Convention,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAW Triennial Convention Winds Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber
on Friday moved the head of the union's Ford Department to
leadership of the General Motors Department as part of a shuffle of
vice presidents.
   Bieber announced the assignments after the 1 million-member
union's weeklong triennial constitutional convention ended with the
delegates' approval of a 135-page book of resolutions on labor,
social and political issues.
   Bieber said Vice President Stephen Yokich would move from
directing the union's Ford Department to the GM Department,
succeeding retired vice president Donald Ephlin. Succeeding Yokich
will be newly elected Vice President Ernie Lofton.
   Another new vice president, Stan Marshall, will take over the
union's Chrysler Department, following Marc Stepp, who also retired.
Vice President Odessa Kommer, the union's most senior vice
president, will remain in charge of a variety of smaller departments.
   Each of the assignments was expected.
   In addition to the general assigments, Yokich will be responsible
for the Skilled Trades Department. Marshall also will take over
direction of the union's organizing efforts, a task previously
handled by Yokich.
   ``I think we had a tremendous convention,'' Bieber said. ``I
think we go out of this convention very strong and united.''
   The union still is hearing the strongest voices of internal
dissent since Walter Reuther solidified his contol of the UAW in the
mid-1930s.
   The New Directions movement has proved to be a thorn in Bieber's
political side, loudly opposing many of his efforts, including
establishment of joint labor-management programs in factories.
   Despite the opposition, Bieber called the convention a ``huge
political success.''
   New Directions never had the support of more than 20 percent of
the delegates as it lost each of its major convention battles. But
the movement has vowed to become better organized and to return
stronger when the UAW holds its next constitutional convention in
1992 at a site yet to be chosen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
