<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Week'sBusiness     06-23 0825</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Week's Business,0855</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 24</HEAD>
<HEAD>$adv 25</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions June 24-25</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hooker and Integrated Resources Nursing Financial Headaches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two companies teetering under the weight of
burdensome debt loads got crutches this past week to support their
financial footing.
   The severity and causes of the difficulties confronting Hooker
Corp. and Integrated Resources Inc. differ. But in both cases, the
prospect for survival is uncertain and the companies must swallow
some stiff medicine if they are to pull through.
   Cash-strapped Hooker, an Australian property and retail concern
that owns department stores and shopping centers in the United
States, tentatively won a loan repayment reprieve from its bankers
on Friday. The banks also agreed to keep credit lines open.
   To persuade its lenders to go along with a temporary halt on
repaying principal on its loans, Hooker had to hand over power to
them, giving the banks a say in its debt-reduction scheme.
   Five of Hooker's major lenders will work with the company and its
financial advisor on a program of asset sales and other measures to
prune debt that has grown to $1.5 billion.
   Among the assets put up for sale are the Forest Fair Mall in
Cincinnati, the Richland Fashion Mall in Columbia, S.C. and Thornton
Town Center outside Denver. Investment partners are being sought to
take stakes in Hooker's department stores including B. Altman &amp; Co.,
Bonwit Teller, Sakowitz and Parisian and in its planned shopping
center developments.
   Hooker Chairman George Herscu, who owns 53 percent of the
company, did not attend the meeting with Hooker and its bankers in
Sydney, Australia, Friday. His absence stirred speculation about his
future role at Hooker.
   Under Herscu's direction, Hooker became a presence in the
American retailing scene by snapping up strings of established
stores and extending them into malls that Hooker built.
   The company mainly blames high Australian interest rates, which
hurt real estate operations in that country, for causing its current
cash crunch, a condition Hooker says is temporary. Sluggish retail
sales in the United States also have contributed to its troubles,
Hooker says.
   But retail industry analysts say Hooker's wounds are partially
self-inflicted and may be slow to heal.
   In developing shopping sites, the company has paid too much
attention to real-estate ambitions and not enough to basic
merchandising considerations, analysts say. Stores were opened where
they weren't needed and upscale stores were brought to areas in
which inhabitants were more at home in discounters.
   During Hooker's convalescence, the company may be rethinking its
philosophy of linking property development to retail expansion,
analysts say.
   Integrated Resources, which transformed itself from the nation's
biggest seller of tax shelter investments into a financial services
company after the 1986 tax revisions rendered its business virtually
useless, also is doing some self-examination.
   After a sudden threat of disintegration due to a cash shortage,
Integrated started pulling itself together last week and announced a
major overhaul of its operations and measures to cope with its
liquidity needs.
   A lack of liquidity had caused the company to default on $955
million in debt, setting in motion a scramble to steer clear of
bankruptcy court.
   The company now is eplacing short-term debt with fresh
borrowings, has pledged almost all of its $7.8 billion in assets as
collateral on the new borrowing, and intends to curtail operations
and to slash operating expenses by $40 million a year.
   Arthur Goldberg, Integrated's president, said the steps should
allow the company to continue as a viable player in financial
services.
   Wall Street apparently has its doubts; Integrated stock was still
languishing late Friday at around $6 a share, down from about $15 a
week earlier and $40 in 1986.
   Integrated may be heading for another reincarnation.
   Texas investor Robert Bass reportedly is attracted to
Integrated's network of financial consultants who sell investments
ranging from insurance to real estate. A Bass-led group may be
willing to pump much-needed funds into Integrated if they could
obtain an equity holding in the company.
   In other business news this week:
   _Paramount Communications Inc. sweetened its hostile tender offer
for Time Inc. to $200 a share, or about $12.2 billion, from $175 a
share, or $10.7 billion. Paramount, a publisher, movie and TV
producer, is hoping to thwart Time's proposed $14 billion
acquisition of Warner Communications Inc.
   _In other long-running takeover sagas, Holly Farms Corp. agreed
to a $1.4 billion takeover bid from Tyson Foods Inc. If approved by
Holly's board, the plan would end a lengthy hostile takeover fight
between two of the nation's biggest poultry processers.
   Prime Computer Inc., meanwhile, chose a friendly partner to fend
off unwanted suitor MAI Basic Four Inc. Prime picked a takeover
proposal valued at over $1 billion from New York investment firm of
J.H. Whitney &amp; Co.
   _The Wall Street Journal celebrated its 100th birthday at a
lavish gala attended by President and Mrs. Bush, plus hundreds of
other luminaries.
</TEXT>
