<HEAD>Top-Rated Hotel Sold for Reported $101 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kapalua Bay Hotel, one of Hawaii's top-rated
hotels, has been sold to a consortium of investors for a reported
$101 million.
   KBH Co., which purchased the hotel for $26 million in 1985, did
not identify the buyers in a brief statement Thursday.
   But The Honolulu Advertiser quoted a hotel industry executive
saying the group included Tokai Kanko, a company that operates
hotels and restaurants in Japan, and the sale price was $101 million.
   Kapalua Bay spokesman Mark Rolfing said no changes in personnel
or the style of management at the 194-room hotel were apparent.
   KBH acquired the hotel from Maui Land &amp; Pineapple Co., which owns
the 750-acre Kapalua Resort in West Maui.
