<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     06-23 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Declines; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar continued its recent retreat against
most major currencies Friday as selling momentum carried over from
previous sessions.
   Gold prices posted gains in the United States after a mixed
performance overseas. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
bid of $377 for a troy ounce of gold bullion at 4 p.m. EDT, up from
Thursday's late bid of $370.25.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar has been sagging due to
a lack of interest in buying the American currency at a time when
central banks seem determined to keep it from moving significantly
higher.
   Central banks stepped into the market several times during the
week and sold dollars, pushing it down.
   Much of the intervention was aimed at supporting the beleaguered
British pound. Currency dealers have dumped sterling lately as
Britain's economic difficulties, including strikes by various labor
unions, have eroded confidence in the currency.
   Traders seemed to be selling dollars Friday in anticipation of
possible dollar declines in Asian trading over the weekend, analysts
said.
   The markets paid little attention to a Commerce Department report
that showed orders for durable goods _ expensive items that have a
lifespan of at least several years _ plunged 4.2 percent in May.
Traders said implications of the drop were uncertain because durable
goods estimates are frequently revised.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed at 140.35 Japanese yen, down from
141.40. In London late Friday the dollar traded lower at 138.50 yen
and it ended in New York at 138.85 yen, down from 139.30 Thursday.
   A British pound cost $1.5675 late Friday, more expensive for
buyers than Thursday's late $1.5525. The late New York quote for
sterling was $1.5645 compared to $1.5585 Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
rates, included: 1.9425 West German marks, down from 1.9515; 1.6660
Swiss francs, down from 1.6820; 1.19425 Canadian dollars, up from
1.19135; 6.6000 French francs, down from 6.6215; and, 1,410.50
Italian lire, down from 1,417.75.
   Late rates for the dollar in Europe compared to Thursday's late
levels were: 1.9390 West German marks, down from 1.9590; 1.6690
Swiss francs, down from 1.6860; 6.5790 French francs, down from
6.6325; 2.1850 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2005; 1,412.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,418.50; and, 1.1910 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1925.
   Gold prices rose sharply in New York and London but edged lower
in Zurich.
   At the end of London's trading day, gold was $8 an ounce higher.
The bullion market attributed the rise to the falling dollar and to
the influence of price changes in New York where gold rose when the
market opened, five hours behind London.
   Gold closed in London at $377.75 bid a troy ounce, up from
Thursday's closing bid of $369.75. It was gold's best level in
London since May 11 when it stood at $379.
   Gold closed in Zurich at a bid of $370, down from $370.60. In
Hong Kong, gold closed at $369.25 compared to Thursday's $369.50.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $378.50 a troy ounce, up from Thursday settlement
price of $371.
   Silver prices also finished mixed. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery settled at $5.330 a troy ounce, up from
$5.292 on Thursday. Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid of
$5.25, a troy ounce, down from $5.34.
</TEXT>
