<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1827EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AutoSales Bjt   06-23 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Big Three Report Auto Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of U.S.-built cars and light trucks sagged
9.8 percent in the June 11-20 period compared with brisk mid-June
sales last year. Analysts said automakers' enticements were losing
their allure.
   The novelty of sales incentives by General Motors Corp., Ford
Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. was wearing off in a saturated market,
said analyst David Healy of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   ``The rebates have shot their wad,'' Healy said. ``Americans are
still paying off too many cars they bought last year to go out and
buy too many more.''
   In addition, interest rates are higher and employment growth
slower than at this time last year, said analyst Harvey Heinbach of
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. in New York. ``We think this is causing consumer
confidence to be soft and customers to stay out of the showrooms,''
he said.
   U.S.-made cars and light trucks sold at an average daily rate of
39,392 during the period, down from a rate of 43,682 a day in the
comparable period in 1988.
   Car sales were down 10.9 percent. Light truck sales declined 8
percent for the period.
   For the year through June 20, car and truck sales lagged 3.7
percent behind those of last year. The average daily rate so far
this year was 38,016, down from 39,481 through mid-June 1988.
   For the year, car sales were down 5 percent and light truck sales
were down 1.4 percent from last year.
   Ford had the greatest decline in car sales and GM the greatest
slowdown in truck sales among the Big Three automakers.
   Ford said its mid-June car sales dropped 13.9 percent to an
average daily rate of 7,197 this year from 8,356 last year. Ford's
light truck sales for the period were down 6 percent.
   Ford's car sales were down 1.6 percent and its truck sales were
down 3.1 percent for the year.
   GM reported mid-June car sales dropping 8.6 percent to a daily
rate of 12,344 from 13,510 in the 1988 mid-June sales period. GM
truck sales for the period dropped 10.8 percent.
   That left GM car sales down 8.6 percent for the year and truck
sales down 1.9 percent.
   Chrysler said it sold an average of 3,380 cars a day in the
mid-June period, down 12.6 percent from 3,867 last year. Chrysler
said its light truck sales declined 5.8 percent for the period.
   For the year, Chrysler car sales were down 13.9 percent and truck
sales were down 0.3 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
