<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude futures prices leaped Friday amid reports
of ongoing problems in North Sea oil production and word that Norway
is renewing oil output curbs.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 41
cents to close at $19.71 a barrel after slipping a penny in the
previous session. Other contract months also advanced.
   Among refined products, heating oil for July delivery gained 0.87
cent to 49.49 cents a gallon. Other contract months were narrowly
higher.
   Unleaded gasoline prices also rose, with the July contract up
1.93 cents to 62.92 cents a gallon. Contracts after July showing
more modest gains.
   Analysts said oil prices got a lift early in the session from
reports that repair delays on oil production equipment would
continue to reduce output from the North Sea. Chevron Corp. also
confirmed that pipeline leaks this month shut down two of its North
Sea platforms, causing further production losses.
   Norway, meanwhile, announced Friday that it would continue to
withhold 7.5 percent in planned output for the remainder of the year
to support OPEC's efforts to raise world oil prices. The cut amounts
to 120,000 barrels per day, according to Nauman Barakat, analyst
with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Norway, a non-OPEC country, is Western Europe's second largest
producer after Britain.
   Traders said prices also got a boost from gasoline futures, which
continued to recover after a sell-off in the last few weeks.
</TEXT>
