<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     06-23 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Surges on Weakening Dollar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices surged more than $7 a troy ounce Friday on
New York's Commodity Exchange, capping that market's biggest weekly
move in nine months.
   Analysts cited the dollar's pronounced weakness as a major factor
in the rally, which boosted the spot price of an ounce of gold by
$13.40 in five days to $378.50.
   Silver and platinum futures prices also advanced.
   On other markets Friday, soybean and petroleum futures rose
strongly while livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Gold settled $7.10 to $7.60 higher with the contract for spot
delivery at $378.50 a troy ounce and the more actively traded August
contract at $381.80. Silver was 2.7 cents to 3.8 cents higher with
July at $5.338 a troy ounce.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, platinum futures settled
$12.90 to $14.10 higher with July at $516.60 a troy ounce, a
six-week high.
   Gold prices have not made as large a weekly move since the week
of Sept. 19, when prices dropped about $18 an ounce.
   ``This was some of the best action we've seen in a long time _ a
really nice finish to a nice week,'' said Craig Sloane, a metals
analyst with Smith Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co. in New York.
   Because gold is denominated in dollars on the world market, a
weakening of the dollar's value against other major currencies makes
gold cheaper overseas, which encourages foreign buying.
   A weaker dollar also makes U.S. goods cheaper overseas, which can
boost orders to U.S. manufacturers, potentially contributing to
inflation. Gold is perceived as an investment hedge against
inflation.
   Friday's rally followed a gain of more than $6 in the gold market
on Wednesday and pushed prices through some key points of
psychological resistance, which analysts took as a bullish sign.
   Soybean futures posted strong gains on the Chicago Board of Trade
amid fears of a global supply squeeze wrought by a producer-led halt
to Brazilian soybean sales.
   Wheat and oat futures retreated while corn was narrowly mixed.
   Brazilian soybean growers stopped selling their crops to
processors about two weeks ago to protest their government's
economic policies.
   Now rumors are spreading that some Brazilian soybean crushers
will be forced to delay shipments of soybean meal and oil to their
European trading partners.
   If those shipments are delayed, demand and prices for U.S.
soybeans are likely to rise.
   Soybeans settled 1 cent to 9} cents higher with July at $7.31 a
bushel; wheat was unchanged to 2} cents lower with July at $3.97{ a
bushel; corn was 3{ cents lower to } cent higher with July at $2.62
a bushel; oats were 4\ cents to 4{ cents lower with July at $1.52{ a
bushel.
   A reported reduction in North Sea crude-oil production helped to
boost energy futures prices on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 13 cents to 41 cents
higher with August at $19.71 a barrel; heating oil was .87 cent to
1.01 cents higher with July at 49.49 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was 1.18 cents to 1.93 cents higher with July at 62.92
cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in subdued trading ahead of the Agriculture
Department's monthly cold storage report.
   The report showed 143.8 million pounds of frozen pork bellies in
public warehouses as of June 1, well below the average pre-report
estimate of 147.8 million pounds. Analysts said pork-belly futures
may open higher Monday in reaction to the surprising report.
   Live cattle were .10 cent to .48 cent lower with August at 69.87
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .05 cent higher
with August at 81.12 cents a pound; live hogs were .20 cent lower to
.47 cent higher with July at 49.67 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .27 cent lower to .17 cent higher with July at 33.67
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
