<FIRST>u f AM-Apples-Bailout     06-23 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Apples-Bailout,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple States Seek Federal Bailout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YAKIMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressmen from all 50 states asked the
U.S. Department of Agriculture Friday to buy nearly 5 million boxes
of apples to help cut a huge surplus created by the Alar controversy.
   The request came in a letter, signed by 114 members of the House
of Representatives, to Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter, said
U.S. Rep. Sid Morrison, R-Wash., who represents a region growing
half the nation's apples.
   ``Apple industry estimates show that some 5 million to 7 million
boxes of apples valued at between $40 million and $56 million in the
current depressed market are now stalled in the world's distribution
pipeline as a result of the scare,'' Morrison said.
   The Natural Resources Defense Council, a private group, issued a
report in February saying eating apples treated with the chemical
growth regulator Alar increased cancer risk in children.
   The report's findings have been disputed, but the federal
government announced plans to ban Alar and consumer sales fell.
   An Agriculture Department program allows the emergency purchase
of $350 million to $500 million in farm products. Yeutter is being
asked to dip into that fund to bail out the nation's 20,000 apple
growers, who have estimated losses of well over $100 million in
sales as a result of the scare.
   The government could give the surplus apples to schools, prisons
and public assistance feeding programs, said Morrison. They could
also be used for production of ethanol or cattle feed, he said.
   An Agriculture Department spokesman in Washington, D.C., Clarence
Steinberg, said the agency has not discussed how it will respond to
the request.
   ``Certainly he's (Yeutter) responsive to congressional
interest,'' Steinberg said.
   Derl Derr, executive vice president of the McLean, Va.-based
International Apple Institute, said apple inventories were 41
percent above what they should be on June 1.
   That figure shows signs of increasing rather than decreasing as
the season progresses, Derr said.
   Apple growers have been complaining in recent weeks that
plummeting wholesale prices, down over 40 percent since the
controversy began in February, have not been reflected in lower
retail prices.
   They complain that discourages consumer sales and is helping
build up the surplus.
   The top grade of red apples produced in Washington, which grows
about half the nation's annual supply, remained at $7.50 to $8 per
box last week, according to the federal-state Market News Service.
That is about $2 below the cost of production.
   That has prompted some growers to suggest giving away apples to
the poor, rather than selling them at a loss, as a way to
demonstrate their plight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890623-0269 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     06-23 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Leases Three Planes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern-Maintenance, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikebound Eastern Airlines on Friday kept up the
flurry of transactions it calls part of its rebuilding plan by
delivering an L1011 widebody plane to Worldways of Canada and two
Boeing 727-200s to Avianca of Colombia.
   The short-term lease deals recently were approved by U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in New York and will give Eastern $900,000 over
four months from Worldways and $1.9 million from Avianca.
   ``We're moving ahead on our plan,'' said Eastern spokesman Robin
Matell, referring to Eastern's stated goal of paying off $900
million in debt and emerging from Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization as a smaller carrier after $1.8 billion in asset
sales, includings sales and leases of planes, airport gates and
routes.
   Matell said the company wouldn't release specific figures on the
total number of asset transactions accomplished so far. However,
deals either already approved by the bankruptcy court or submitted
for approval total nearly $900 million.
   Eastern's unions, who want a buyout of the airline as a whole,
have said they will challenge all asset sales.
   On Thursday, Eastern said it would ask permission to sell its
last two Boeing 727-100 jets to Express One of Dallas for $9
million. On Tuesday, Eastern said it wants to lease an Airbus A300
to Venezuela's Viasa for $1.4 million over four months.
   Miami-based Eastern last week announced a deal to sell eight
Philadelphia airport gates, 16 jets and other assets to Midway
Airlines for $206.5 million.
   Under Eastern's proposed rebuilding plan, it wants to cut its
pre-strike fleet of 255 aircraft to 157 planes, serving 77
locations, down from 102 before the strike that started March 4.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland must approve any asset
sales, but he already has approved the $365 million sale of
Eastern's Northeast shuttle service to developer Donald Trump. Last
week, he approved the $277.5 million sale of 15 planes and six
engines to an aircraft leasing company.
   Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization on March
9, five days after its pilots and flight attendants unions joined a
Machinists union strike that crippled the airline. While the unions
have vowed not to return to work under Texas Air Corp. Chairman
Frank Lorenzo and want Lorenzo to sell Eastern, Texas Air is moving
ahead with its own plan to make Eastern an airline about two-thirds
its pre-strike size.
   Eastern on Thursday filed a request with the bankruptcy court to
end its contract with the pilots union and allow the company to cut
pilots' pay and increase their work hours.
   Also on Thursday, Rep. Glenn Anderson, D-Calif., chairman of the
aviation subcommittee of the House Public Works and Transportation
Committee, announced that his panel will hold a hearing next
Thursday on Eastern's condition and ``the prospects for its
restoration as a major carrier.''
   Two congressmen earlier asked Transportation Secretary Samuel
Skinner to enter Eastern's bankruptcy case out of ``urgent'' concern
that the carrier's restructuring could lessen U.S. airline
competition.
   In a letter Wednesday to Skinner, House Republican Whip Newt
Gingrich of Georgia and Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., expressed
concern that antitrust issues have not been addressed adequately in
the Eastern bankruptcy proceedings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
