<HEAD>Eds: ADDS weekly price trends.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week.
   Wheat for delivery in July settled Friday at $3.97{ a bushel on
the Chicago Board of Trade, up from $3.94\ a week earlier; July corn
slipped to $2.62 a bushel from $2.62}; July oats dropped to $1.52{ a
bushel from $1.64{; and July soybeans dipped to $7.31 a bushel from
$7.33.
   Livestock futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange but
frozen pork bellies declined.
   August live cattle rose to 69.87 cents a pound from 69.50 cents;
August feeder cattle improved to 81.12 cents a pound from 80.97
cents; July live hogs rallied to 49.67 cents a pound from 48.20
cents; July frozen pork bellies fell to 33.67 cents a pound from
33.92 cents.
   Gold futures rose sharply on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   August gold rose to $381.80 a troy ounce from $368.80; July
silver rose to $5.338 a troy ounce from $5.305.
   Energy futures moved sharply higher on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for August delivery rose to
$19.71 a barrel from $18.58; July heating oil soared to 49.49 cents
a gallon from 45.71 cents; July unleaded gasoline rallied to 62.92
cents a gallon from 58.14 cents.
