<FIRST>u f AM-PersonalIncome Bjt   06-23 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Personal Income, Bjt,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Spending, Income Growth Slows in May</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer spending and income growth both slowed
in May to a lackluster 0.3 percent, the slowest pace since the fall,
the government said Friday in another indication the economy is
losing steam.
   Consumer spending represents two-thirds of the U.S. economy, and
analysts closely monitor fluctations in both spending and income as
a barometer of the economy's overall health.
   The gain in Americans' income to a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of $4.39 trillion was the slowest since September, the Commerce
Department said. The rise in personal consumer spending to an annual
rate of $3.44 trillion was the weakest since October.
   If the rising cost of living is factored out, both spending and
income actually declined in May. Economist Allen Sinai of The Boston
Co. called the report ``almost recession-like.''
   ``Consumer spending, adjusted for inflation, normally keeps going
up, so this is very weak,'' he said.
   However, economic consultant Michael K. Evans of Washington said
spending growth had paused temporarily because consumers were forced
to pay higher-than-expected tax bills in April and higher gasoline
and food prices in April and May.
   ``The average consumer got hit by a one-two punch,'' he said. ``I
think consumer spending will come back cautiously in the third
quarter. If I didn't, I'd be predicting a recession.''
   The May income boost followed stronger gains of 0.5 percent in
April and 0.9 percent in March. However, the Commerce Department
noted that the March rise was inflated by two special factors:
profit-sharing payments to auto workers and retroactive Social
Security checks. That made the April increase look smaller.
   April was also held back by a dip in farm payments, and that in
turn made the small May rise appear larger.
   ``If you take those numbers together, personal income is still
moving up, but at a more sedate pace. We're looking at an economy
that is slowing, which is what the Federal Reserve wanted,'' said
economist Lyle Gramley of the Mortgage Bankers Association of
America.
   The Fed has been fighting inflation with higher interest rates
since March 1988. It recently has allowed rates to come down a bit.
   Gramley, a former Fed member, said Friday's report likely
wouldn't cause the central bank to ease further now, but he said the
Fed may loosen its grip on credit another notch in a week or two.
   Disposable, or after-tax, income surged 1.4 percent in May after
falling 0.7 percent in April. Tax payments took a
larger-than-expected bite out of income in April and returned to a
more normal level in May.
   The personal savings rate, representing the percentage of
after-tax income saved by Americans, rose to 5.3 percent in May from
4.3 percent in April.
   The savings rate has been averaging about 5.1 percent this year,
up from 4.2 percent last year and a historic low of 3.2 percent in
1987. Analysts believe the rising savings rate this year indicates
consumers are becoming more cautious.
   Before rising a weak 0.3 percent last month, personal consumption
spending, which includes everything except interest on debt, had
surged 1.1 percent in April and risen 0.4 percent in March.
   The Commerce Department said much of the May weakness and April
strength was accounted for by swings in auto buying, which have been
influenced by introduction of manufacturers' incentives in April and
their partial rescission in May.
   Spending on durable goods, big-ticket items including autos, fell
1.5 percent last month to an annual rate of $465.7 billion after
rising 4.4 percent in April.
</TEXT>
