<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Japanese Stocks Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout with midmorning prices.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was lower against the Japanese yen in
morning trading Friday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange moved higher.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost 20.31
points Thursday, gained 192.07 points, or 0.57 percent, to finish
the morning session at 33,517.04.
   The dollar was trading at 140.15 yen at late morning. After
opening at 139.60 yen, down 1.80 yen from Thursday's close of 141.40
yen, the currency ranged between 139.40 yen and 140.60 yen.
   The dollar's drop followed its overnight plunge in New York,
where it closed lower at 139.30 yen following a false rumor that
President Bush had been shot.
   Traders said continued buying by Japanese importers and by
institutional investors helped the U.S. currency move back above 140
yen.
   Finance Minister Tatsuo Murayama told a news confernce Friday
morning that there is still specualtion in the currency market, but
said the market would appear to be ``in the process of deciding the
dollar's (direction).''
   In referring to last week's surge of the dollar past the 151 yen
level, Maruyama restated his belief that the dollar's recent
strength will be short-lived.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the Nikkei index's gain was
partly based on a stronger yen and higher prices Thursday on Wall
Street.
</TEXT>
