<FILEID>AP-NR-06-23-89 1946EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ChildCare 1stLd-Writethru   06-23 0832</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Child Care, 1st Ld-Writethru,0858</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Passes Child Care Bill; White House Warns of Veto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Moved on general news wires as 2nd Ld-Writethru.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Friday passed a
multibillion-dollar child-care plan but the Bush administration
labeled it ``a candidate for a veto'' despite Democratic compromises
to accommodate the president.
   The voice vote sent to the House a partisan fight over child
care, with Democrats and Republicans alike jockeying for credit on
an issue both parties have made a priority.
   Overall, the Senate package, with its $1.75 billion in direct
subsidies for the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1and about $3 billion a
year in tax credits, represents the greatest government effort to
address child-care needs of working parents since an emergency plan
adopted during World War II.
   When GOP senators and the White House scoffed Friday morning at a
Democratic compromise it appeared a lengthy battle over amendments
was in store.
   But Republicans acknowledged their inability to muster enough
votes to defeat the majority Democrats and relented by midafternoon
to reach agreement on a timetable that allowed for the final vote in
time for senators to leave town to begin a two-week recess.
   Action on child care is expected to accelerate in the House
beginning next week, and Republicans made clear they wanted to
revise the Senate measure substantially.
   ``I'm going to encourage the administration not to view what
happened in the Senate as final,'' Senate Republican leader Bob Dole
of Kansas said just before the final vote. ``There's a long way to
go.''
   But Democrats characterized the legislation as historic and a
long-overdue effort to support low-income parents who want or need
to work but cannot find or afford child care. '
   ``The real winners, the children, are closer to a safer, more
effective and affordable child-care program,'' said Sen. Edward M.
Kennedy, D-Mass.
   ``This is a monumental achievement,'' said Republican Sen. Orrin
Hatch of Utah, who crossed party lines to co-sponsor the plan with
Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.
   Still, Dole said changes would be needed to win Bush's support.
   ``There's nothing in this bill for the president of the United
States,'' Dole said. ``He supports child care. He wants a bill he
can sign. But to get one you've got to give him something that he
wants.''
   Exasperated Democrats said they had done just that.
   An amendment by Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, added to the
Democrats' bill a tax credit the White House had sought. Bentsen
copied it from an alternative Republican child-care package defeated
Tuesday.
   Another Bush-supported provision already was included in the
Democratic package, as well as a third credit to help pay for
children's health insurance, which Bush opposes.
   The president also opposes the centerpiece of the Democratic
bill: a $1.75 billion authorization for direct subsidies to help
parents pay for child care and to help states improve the
availability and affordability of services.
   ``I offer this amendment in the spirit of compromise,'' Bentsen
said. ``The president of the United States can't have it all.''
   But as the Senate voted 54-45 along partisan lines in favor of
Bentsen's proposal, the White House served notice that adding
provisions Bush supports would not sway his opposition to the
legislation, the Act for Better Child Care.
   ``The ABC bill, in any combination, is a candidate for a veto,''
Bush spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   After failing to defeat Bentsen's proposal, Republicans offered
another amendment that would heave essentially repealed it,
signaling an escalated political fight with more than a dozen
amendments to come.
   But when Democrats again beat back the GOP effort, 53-44, the
confrontational mood gave way to businesslike though partisan
consideration of the remaining amendments.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell had promised to an unusual
Saturday session to finish the bill but that proved unnecessary.
   The new twist in Bentsen's amendment was an expansion of the
earned income tax credit to provide up to $750 a year in new tax
relief to low-income parents with children under 5.
   The proposal mirrored the central element of the defeated GOP
alternative, which had White House support.
   Already in the Democratic bill was a provision allowing
low-income parents to take advantage of the existing dependent care
tax credit up front by making it refundable _ paying cash to
families who are eligible for the credit but cannot take advantage
of it because they don't make enough to owe any federal taxes.
   Both Bush's and the Democrats' original proposal would have made
the dependent care credit 100 percent refundable. Bentsen's
amendment made it 90 percent refundable, a change he made to pay for
the expanded earned income credit without adding to the estimated $3
billion annual cost of the tax-relief portion of the bill.
   Republicans argued that the credit should remain 100 percent
refundable. They called for the elimination of the third part of the
Bentsen package, a credit of up to $500 a year to help pay for
children's health insurance.
